<1ST_LINE>r a AM-RockwellIndictment     03-07 0175</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Rockwell Indictment,0180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rockwell Pleads Innocent in Overbilling Indictment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rockwell International Corp. and two former
managers pleaded innocent Monday to charges that they overbilled
the Air Force by $450,000 on a sophisticated satellite navigational
system.
   In a brief hearing, U.S. District Judge Consuelo Marshall
ordered the company and its former managers to file pretrial
motions by April 4 and set a May 3 trial date, Rockwell spokesman
Jeff Charney said.
   He indicated the company plans to make pretrial motions but
declined to elaborate.
   The company and the former managers _ Donald Carter, materials
division director at the its Seal Beach plant, and Robert
Zavodnick, manager of major subcontracts within the division _ were
named in a 25-count federal indictment in January.
   The indictment alleged that the company and two men
double-billed the government for work on the NAVSTAR global
navigational system that uses radio signals from satellites to
pinpoint locations on earth.
   As a result, the indictment claimed, Rockwell received $450,000
in unlawful profits.
   The company has denied the allegations.
</TEXT>
