<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-Soviet-Minorities     03-07 0546</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Soviet-Minorities,0561</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Communist Powers Face Similar Minority Problems
^An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Tuesday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Militant monks in Tibet and restive Armenians in
the Soviet Union are among the minority nationalities in those
countries now testing, sometimes with violence, the limits of their
governments' professed policies of openness.
   Moscow calls them ``hooligans.'' To Beijing they are
``splittists.'' But to both countries they represent a threat to
the reputation and unity of the state.
   Thirty-one people died last week in rioting in the Soviet city
of Sumgait in Azerbaijan, where Christian Armenians are unhappy
about being part of mostly Moslem Azerbaijan. In Tibet, up to 23
have died in clashes between Chinese police and Tibetans in October
and over the weekend.
   In both countries, the Communist governments in the past have
suppressed their minorities to unite vast tracts of land under the
ruling ethnic group, the Hans in China and the Russians in the
Soviet Union.
   Josef V. Stalin purged the Ukraine in the 1930s, and Mao
Tse-tung swiftly cracked down on unrest in Tibet and Moslem west
China in the 1950s and 1960s.
   Both countries, with China in the lead, have now declared
greater tolerance for different views, exposing both to flashpoints
of nationalist sentiment.
   China blames outside forces for its troubles, saying
pro-independence supporters of Tibet's exiled religious leader, the
Dalai Lama, were responsible for the first outbreak of violence in
the Tibetan capital of Lhasa last October.
   Moscow is faced with a wider problem of ethnic disputes in
Armenia, religious identity in Kazakhstan and political activism in
the Baltic republics of Estonia and Lithuania.
   Foreign journalists in China have had slightly better access to
the troubled areas than their Moscow-based counterparts. China
expelled 14 foreign journalists from Lhasa last October, and has
since given permission for only a few to return.
   But Lhasa authorities, hungry for tourist spending to help
China's poorest province, have not stopped group tours, and some
reporters have joined excursion groups to Tibet.
   The Soviet Union let a few correspondents go to Vilnius,
Lithuania, on a Foreign Ministry-sponsored trip for a planned
demonstration to mark the Feb. 16 declaration of independence.
   But reporters there were followed constantly.
   No foreign journalist has been allowed lately into Armenia or
Azerbaijan. Telephone calls to Yerevan sometimes went through, but
Nagorno-Karabakh, the center of the Armenian-Azeri dispute, cannot
be reached at all and Sumgait only rarely.
   Reflecting Moscow's ``glasnost'' and Beijing's similar policy of
``kaifang,'' the official media in both countries have carried
limited reports of the disturbances.
   China's press has stressed that only a small number of Tibetans
have joined the disturbances, and has sent out a barrage of stories
about Tibetans criticizing the separatists and saying how much
better life is under socialism.
   The government has stressed that it will continue to respect the
local customs and help alleviate poverty in the regions where the
nation's 67 million non-Han minorities live.
   Moscow, too, has linked the rioting to a small number of
``hooligans.'' Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev, however, in a Feb.
18 speech stressed the importance of working out a new policy on
nationalities and said the Cental Committee would hold a special
plenary session to discuss the matter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
