<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Reagan-NearCollision     03-07 0297</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-Near Collision,0304</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Private Pilot Sentenced For False Statements</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Army private who flew his small airplane
into prohibited airspace over President Reagan's Santa Barbara
County ranch must spend 30 weekends in jail.
   Ralph William Myers, 33, of Fort Lewis, Wash., convicted of
lying to authorities about the reason he strayed into prohibited
airspace on Aug. 13, was sentenced Monday by U.S. District Judge
Manuel L. Real.
   Despite a Probation Department recommendation of probation, Real
sentenced Myers to three years in jail for each of two counts of
making false statements and then suspended all but 60 days of the
incarceration. The judge also ordered Myers to donate 1,000 hours
to charitable service.
   Myers' jail time will begin April 9 and is not to interfere with
his military service. Myers could have been sentenced to 10 years'
imprisonment and a $500,000 fine.
   Outside court, Myers said he was made a scapegoat by the federal
government because reports that there had been a near-miss caused
``hysteria.''
   Myers maintains his plane was no closer than 800 feet from the
president's helicopter, Marine One. Reagan's Marine pilot, Lt. Col.
Michael Glynn, says Myers' plane passed about 200 feet in front of
his helicopter and 150 feet below it.
   Myers' attorney, Manuel Araujo, said they will appeal the
sentence.
   Myers, who has been stripped of his pilot's license, originally
told federal agents he strayed into the prohibited airspace while
looking for a lost contact lens in the cabin. He later said he had
lied about the lens because, ``I was trying to stay out of more
trouble.''
   Myers was demoted from private first class to private for being
absent without leave. He still has 18 months left in the Army.
</TEXT>
