<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Panama-Attack 2ndLd-Writethru a0828 03-07 0646</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Panama-Attack, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0828,0660</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Men Backing New Panama Government Smash Into Consulate</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS Delvalle ousted Feb. 26, sted last week, in grafs 3,
10.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Panama, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of men backing Panama's new government
seized control of the country's disputed consulate in London Monday
night by smashing through the glass door with a Land Rover, police
reported.
   The British Broadcasting Corp. said the seizure took place
because the consul in London, Eduardo Arango, refused to give up
his post despite being fired by the new government.
   Control of Panama's Embassy in Washington is also in dispute
following the ouster on Feb. 26 of President Eric Arturo Delvalle.
He was removed from office after he tried to dismiss Gen. Manuel
Antonio Noriega, the military leader and de facto ruler.
   The London consulate is about a mile east of the embassy. The
BBC said Arango was not in the consulate when the raid occurred.
   Police said in a statement that six men _ two representatives of
Panamanian Ambassador Guillermo Vega and four members of a British
security firm _ smashed their way into the consulate.
   ``Shortly after this, several people left the building,
including three women believed to be secretaries, and a number of
security staff. One glass-paneled front door was damaged and no one
was injured as a result of the incident,'' the statement added.
   One of the staff members forced out of the consulate, Tourism
Commissioner Rolando Domingo, 24, said: ``We were just working in
there and then suddenly we heard a crash.''
   He said the Land Rover broke through the glass doors and then a
group of men burst into the building carrying large hammers. ``They
threatened us with hammers and one tried to hit my face. They took
my passport and documents. Then they pushed me down the stairs and
out of the building,'' Domingo said.
   London police sealed off the area around the consulate in Tudor
Street in the City, London's financial district.
   The United States and many other countries still consider
Delvalle the president of Panama. He was removed from office by the
National Assembly, which is dominated by Noriega supporters.
   The Reagan administration has called for Noriega's ouster since
he was indicted in Florida last month on drug trafficking charges.
   The BBC reported that Arango was in Panama at the time of
Delvalle's ouster and has said he helped smuggle Delvalle from his
residence to a hiding place in the Central American country.
   The British domestic news agency Press Association said Arango
received a phone call at home from the consulate staff about the
Monday night raid.
   The agency quoted Arango as saying he was prevented from
entering the consulate after the attack and that one of the men
occupying it had told him they were working for Vega and carrying
out orders from Panama.
   British government officials said they were told last Friday
that Arango was being fired as consul.
   Arango said he had received letters from Panama saying he was
dismissed but had ignored them, Press Association said.
   As workmen repaired the doors, one of the British security
guards who took part in the raid said:
   ``It is an exaggeration to say we smashed in. We nudged the
doors with the Land Rover. The police say they may prosecute us for
mounting the pavement (sidewalk) but I don't think they can do
anything else. We were authorized to enter the building but I
cannot divulge any more.''
   The four guards involved work for GB Security, a private
security company based in south London. They said they would be
guarding the building overnight.
   A spokesman at the British Foreign Office, who in accordance
with British practice declined to be named, said it was too early
to say what action, if any, Foreign Secretary Sir Geoffrey Howe
might take over the incident.
</TEXT>
