<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Obit-Bradley     03-07 0298</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Bradley,0307</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chairman of St. Joseph News-Press & Gazette Co. Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. JOSEPH, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   David R. Bradley Sr., chairman and chief
executive officer of the St. Joseph News-Press & Gazette Co., has
died at age 70.
   Bradley, who died Sunday at a Kansas City hospital, was the
second generation of a communications family that has published The
News-Press and Gazette for nearly 50 years.
   He was publisher of the St. Joseph newspapers from 1956 to 1981,
succeeding his father, Henry D. Bradley, as president of the
company in 1972. The elder Bradley died in 1973.
   Bradley was known for keeping the newspapers on the leading edge
of technology, switching to all-electronic production more than a
decade ago. He also led the company into the TV market.
   The company's holdings include stations in Savannah, Ga.;
Jackson, Miss.; Hattiesburg, Miss.; Sioux Falls, S.D., and
Wilmington, N.C., and cable TV systems in St. Joseph, Savannah and
Macon, Mo.
   He was active in The Associated Press and served as a director
of the news cooperative from 1970 to 1979. He also was first vice
chairman of the AP, serving in that position from 1977-79.
   ``Dave had a unique combination of common sense, a sharp
business mind and a zest for life,'' said Louis D. Boccardi,
president and general manager of the AP. ``You could count on him
to help you get to the heart of any problem, but also to remind you
that your problem was probably a little less earth-shaking than you
thought it was. He was a treasured friend and a wise counsel.''
   Bradley was born in Toledo, Ohio, and graduated from the
University of Wisconsin in 1939.
   Survivors include his wife, Shirley Wyeth Bradley; two
daughters; two sons and 11 grandchildren.
   Funeral arrangements were incomplete Sunday.
</TEXT>
