<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Czechoslovakia-Church     03-07 0406</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Czechoslovakia-Church,0417</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Demands For Religious Freedom After Packed Mass</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of Roman Catholics
chanted ``We want religious freedom!'' after thousands crowded into
a cathedral for a Mass honoring a 13th-century Czech princess who
renounced royal wealth to serve God.
   The Mass on Sunday at St. Vitus Cathedral, in the Castle complex
where Communist President Gustav Husak lives, drew about 8,000
people.
   It was one of the biggest religious services in the capital
since the Communist takeover in 1948 and an indication of the
reviving strength of the nation's Roman Catholic church.
   Dozens of plainclothes security officers were seen inside and
outside the cathedral while Mass was held to honor the princess who
is to be canonized by the Vatican later this year.
   Police arrested 16 dissidents and religious activists under
48-hour detention orders on Friday and Saturday, apparently to
prevent them from attending the Mass. A dissident source said five
people remained in detention Sunday night, but four of them were
expected to be freed today.
   Augustin Navratil, a Roman Catholic activist from Moravia, was
detained Friday morning but there was no word he was free late
Sunday, the source said.
   Navratil was the author of a 31-point church petition for more
religious freedom that has gained more than 300,000 signatures,
making it the largest such action in the Soviet bloc since 1945.
   Five other dissidents were briefly detained when they tried to
visit a British diplomat Friday, and two others also were briefly
held that night.
   After the Mass, about 1,000 people went from the cathedral to
the nearby residence of Cardinal Frantisek Tomasek. A few hundred
chanted ``We want bishops,'' ``We want religious freedom'' and ``We
want the Pope.''
   The chanting crowd appeared to reflect growing discontent among
Catholics at the lack of bishops in 10 of the country's 13 sees.
   The Vatican has refused to accept government proposals to
appoint as bishops members of the state-sponsored Pacem in Terris
organization, a group of priests not recognized by the Holy See.
   ``Long live the Holy Father'' was another chant from the crowd
outside Tomasek's residence, which adjoins the castle where Husak
lives. The presidential flag was flying, indicating the 75-year-old
president was home during the unusual demonstration.
   There is no official estimate of the number of believers in
Czechoslovakia, but Vatican officials estimate about 60 percent of
the 15.5 million citizens are Catholic.
</TEXT>
