<FILEID>AP-NR-03-07-88 0807EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TuitionPlan     03-07 0301</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Tuition Plan,0311</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>University's Pre-Payment Plan Suspended</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Falling bond interest rates and unexpectedly
high tuition increases have forced Duquesne University to suspend a
trendsetting tuition prepayment plan, according to school officials.
   The small Roman Catholic university announced three years ago
that alumni could enroll their newborn children for $4,450 as full
tuition payment for four years of education. The plan was expanded
in 1986 to include non-alumni.
   The college takes the money and invests it, with the proceeds
covering tuition for four years of college when the child is grown.
   The plan prompted about a dozen other private colleges to follow
suit. Six states also adopted plans that would enable parents to
prepay a fixed amount of the child's college tuition, starting at
birth.
   Duquesne spokeswoman Ann Rago confirmed Sunday that the
university's board of trustees had voted Wednesday to suspend the
plan.
   ``When we began the program, it was a much different economic
climate, but things have changed so we decided to suspend it,'' she
said.
   The college will keep its commitment to 622 families already
enrolled in the program, Ms. Rago said.
   When the plan was created, according to Ms. Rago, the
university's rate of return on the bonds was 10.8 percent. It has
since dropped to 8.52 percent, she said.
   Tuition for 1988-89 recently was raised 8 percent, rather than
the originally projected 6 percent.
   The university found it would be necessary to raise the 1987
tuition prepayment for a newborn to $8,630. That was calculated to
cover tuition costs of $102,604 over four years, ending in the year
2005.
   For a 15-year-old, the one-time investment rose from $12,864 to
$24,310.
   ``At this time, those numbers don't make the plan feasible,''
Ms. Rago said. ``The administration will re-examine it if the
economic conditions change.''

</TEXT>
</DOC>
