<FILEID>AP-NR-03-07-88 0858EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-FerryMemorial     03-07 0557</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ferry Memorial,0570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tears, Pleas For A New Beginning On Ferry Anniversary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDITH M. LEDERER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ZEEBRUGGE, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Survivors and those who lost loved
ones in a ferry disaster retraced the voyage of the Herald Free
Enterprise, casting wreaths and notes over the spot where it
capsized a year before.
   ``Daddy, Miss You,'' said one of the more than 100 cards dropped
into the water Sunday, a cold, bleak day with a fine drizzle _
remarkably similar to the day the Herald turned over and 193 of its
passengers died.
   Others joined in prayer Sunday in this Belgian port and across
the North Sea in the English port of Dover to mark the worst
peacetime disaster involving a British ship since the sinking of
the Titanic in 1912.
   About 270 set out from Zeebrugge and stopped just outside the
harbor wall where the ferry capsized March 6, 1987, when water
rushed in through its open bow doors five minutes after it left
port.
   For 20 minutes they cast flowers onto the choppy seas from the
Baltic Ferry, which the Herald's owners P and O pressed into
service for the sad pilgrimage.
   Some were led away to be comforted by Red Cross and social
workers. Others clung to their families. A few went off by
themselves and stood looking into the murky waters.
   On the upper car deck, which was transformed into a makeshift
chapel bedecked with flowers, prayers were said by three clergymen
_ an Anglican, a Roman Catholic and a major from the Salvation Army
_ during a half-hour service.
   ``This service can mark a new beginning,'' said The Rev. Peter
Bowers, vicar of St. Peter's and St. Paul's Church in Dover. ``It
does not mean we forget those who we have loved. ... In fact, it is
from that memory that we build a new future.''
   His words were echoed by The Bishop of Dover, The Rt. Rev.
Richard Third, who told more than 600 bereaved at the Anglican
church of St. Mary The Virgin in Dover that it was time to leave
their grief behind.
   ``It is right to grieve. It is health-giving to express your
sorrow _ but you can't go on doing it for a lifetime. There must
come a moment when you surrender your grief, when you stop crying.''
   At St. Donaas Roman Catholic church across the road from
Zeebrugge port, the Sunday service was turned into a memorial for
the ferry victims.
   The Rev. Wim Catry also offered prayers that the survivors and
bereaved would be able to reconstruct their lives. He said in his
sermon that a rose garden and plaque would be unveiled in May in
front of the church to commemorate the dead.
   Andrew Parker, who turned his body into a human bridge so 20
passengers including his wife and daughter could walk across his
back to safety, paid his own private tribute.
   He went out on a Belgian tug to the spot where the Herald
capsized and with his 13-year-old daughter Janice dropped 193
flowers into the water, one by one. His wife, Eleanor, like several
other Britons who came here, remained onshore, unable at the last
minute to relive their nightmares.
   Said Mrs. Parker: ``I hate this day _ I just wish I could take
it off the calendar.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
