<HEAD>Chicken Violates Sign Code</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA ANA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sanford and Linda Simmons have run
afoul of Orange County's sign code, but they want their six-foot
mechanical chicken to keep on clucking.
   ``We've got a lot of money tied up in this chicken, so we're
fighting back,'' Simmons said.
   The couple started a ``Save Our Chicken'' petition drive at
their Stuf'd Chicken restaurant and say they have about 500
signatures.
   The issue involves an ordinance prohibiting free-standing or
temporary signs in unincorporated parts of the county, said Gary
Boettcher, the Southern California county's enforcement manager.
   ``We're trying to improve the visual aspects of Sunset Beach,
and if everybody did this it would promote a garish image,''
Boettcher said. The restaurant faces fines or citations if they
don't take the chicken down.
   Simmons said the $800 mechanical chicken, which went up two
weeks ago, has proved an ideal replacement for reluctant teen-agers
he had been paying to stand by the side of the road dressed in
chicken outfits.
   ``It's hard to find people to be a chicken,'' he said.
</TEXT>
