<2ND_LINE>PM-Iran-Iraq, 2nd Ld - Writethru,a0492,0489</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran And Iraq Lob More Missiles Into Each Other's Capitals</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 13 grafs to UPDATE attack numbers, edits to
conform; picks up 14th graf pvs; Iran's Foreign...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran and Iraq shot missiles into each
other's capitals today and both reported dozens of deaths as the
``war of the cities'' persisted between the two Persian Gulf war
foes.
   Iran's official Islamic Republic News Agency said 12 civilians,
including women and children, were killed and 30 wounded when an
Iraqi missile exploded in Tehran today. It said a hospital clinic,
several houses and 30 vehicles were destroyed in the blast.
   The missile was one of three Iraq said its army shot into Tehran
early today in the latest round of the bruising offensive that has
claimed hundreds of lives in both countries.
   IRNA said another 61 civilians were killed and 427 wounded
Sunday in Iraqi air raids on 16 Iranian cities and towns.
   The agency said schools and hospitals were hit in the wave of
Iraqi raids on the southern city of Shiraz and Dezful, Arak
Khorramabad and other population centers in the west. Eight other
people were wounded in missile strikes on Tehran on Sunday, it said.
   It said Iraqi artillery was shelling the northwestern border
town of Marivan, but made no mention of casualties or damage.
   Baghdad communiques said Iraqi fighter-bombers flew 118 combat
missions against ``military and economic targets'' in 12 Iranian
cities Sunday in retaliation for ``criminal attacks on Iraqi
civilian areas.''
   IRNA reported that Revolutionary Guards fired four missiles into
Baghdad today.
   It said they were aimed at ``military centers.'' Baghdad said
the first two missiles crashed into residential sections of the
capital, killing or wounding ``many civilians, including women and
children.''
   The agency said Iraq retaliated by firing three long-range ``Al
Hussein'' missiles, named after a 7th Century Shiite Moslem saint,
into Tehran today.
   INA quoted a military communique as saying: ``Iran's rulers must
realize their weakness and stop fighting.''
   The eight-day missile exchange has been the fiercest since the
gulf war began in September 1980 and the first time that Tehran has
been hit by missiles.
   Iraq says it has fired 41 projectiles into the Iranian capital
since the eye-for-an-eye missile duel began Feb. 29, when Iran sent
two missiles crashing into Baghdad.
   Iran's Foreign Minister, Ali Akbar Velayati, admitted Saturday
that ``more than 30'' missiles had hit Tehran.
   The Iranians have reported firing 22 missiles in that period,
but the Iraqis have only acknowledged 18 hits.
   Iran has reported at least 106 civilians killed and more than
200 wounded in the Iraqi missile blitz, with more than 100 killed
and more than 500 wounded in air raids over the last week.
   Iraq has reported heavy civilian casualties, but has given no
numbers.
</TEXT>
