<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SchoolRape     03-07 0445</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-School Rape,0460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Student Says Youths Laughed As They Watched Her Being Raped</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A special education student says no other
youths moved to help her when two boys raped her in a classroom,
and when the bell rang at the end of the period they left laughing.
   The Magee resident also said two boys charged with the rape at
Magee High School had harassed her for about two years.
   ``Me and (he) fight every day,'' the 16-year-old girl said in a
weekend interview with The Clarion Ledger at her parents' rural
Simpson County home. ``He just picks on me and call my mom and
daddy names.''
   The girl said she was raped by two male students on Feb. 26
while she and other students were in study hall under the
supervision of teacher John Grantham, who said he had gone to check
on a school bus he drives when the attack occurred.
   The girl, who has a learning disability, and her family agreed
to discuss the attack if their identities weren't disclosed, the
newspaper said Sunday.
   The girl said the youths, ages 15 and 17, grabbed her around the
neck when she and another girl went to sharpen their pencils. They
grabbed the other girl, too, but let her go, she said.
   ``They carried me in the back of the room. I told them to leave
me alone.''
   The girl said the youths pulled off her underwear, and each
raped her twice, she said.
   ``One was holding me,'' she said. ``Every time I tried to get
up, they hold me down.''
   The attack occurred within sight of several other students, she
said. All the students in the study hall, except for one of the
attackers, were regular students, said Betty Dickson, Simpson
County School Board chairwoman.
   One of the boys is educably mentally retarded, according to
special education director John Hardy.
   No one stopped the attack, the girl said, even though she told
the other girl at the pencil sharpener to alert a principal or
teacher.
   ``When the bell rang, they walked out the door, laughing,'' she
said.
   The girl's father said he is as upset with school officials as
he is the two boys. ``I send them to learn, not to be going down
there to get raped,'' he said.
   The father said he called police and took his daughter to Magee
General Hospital that night to be examined.
   The two youths were arrested Thursday, charged with rape and
jailed in lieu of $50,000 bond each. Although they will be tried as
adults, officials refused to release their names.
   Dickson said school officials are planning counseling for the
girl.
</TEXT>
