<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HouseShot     03-07 0322</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-House Shot,0330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teen-ager Upset About School, Basketball Shoots Up Own House</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIGA, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 15-year-old boy described as despondent over
school problems and upset about the outcome of a college basketball
game blasted away with an assortment of rifles and handguns for
five hours inside his home, officials said today.
   No one was injured in the incident, which ended when deputies
talked the boy into surrendering early today, said Monroe County
sheriff's spokesman Thomas Ryan.
   ``The house is a shambles,'' Ryan said this morning. ``He shot
out the television, the stove, the walls and ceilings, windows,
sliding glass doors, a water pipe which ruptured and squirted water
everywhere, and even the electrical box in the basement.''
   Ryan said the boy, whose name was withheld because of his age,
had picked up a gun and started shooting Sunday night. His mother
ran next door to call police.
   When deputies arrived at the house in the rural area southwest
of Rochester, they heard bullets whizzing by their heads and
evacuated the house next door. Deputies then set up a command post
in a house down the road, from which negotiators talked to the
youth by telephone, Ryan said.
   Before the boy surrendered early Sunday morning he had fired at
least 300 rounds of ammunition had been fired from a variety of
weapons, Ryan said. The boy's father had four or five rifles and
shotguns and four handguns, Ryan said.
   ``The boy had been suspended from high school last week for
disciplinary problems,'' Ryan said. ``Whether this triggered him,
we don't know. The only other thing he mentioned to hostage
negotiators was that he was upset that Syracuse lost to
Pittsburgh.''
   Pittsburgh edged Syracuse University 85-84 to take the Big East
Conference college basketball title Sunday afternoon.
   The youth was taken to Strong Memorial Hospital in Rochester for
a mental examination before being turned over to family court
officials, said Ryan.
</TEXT>
