<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Canton     03-07 0705</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Canton,700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Will Try Again to Decide on Suing Cities in Ohio Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court said today it will try again
to decide whether cities may be sued successfully when citizens'
rights are violated due to alleged inadequate training of municipal
employees.
   The justices said they will study the issue in an appeal by
Canton, Ohio, officials.
   The city is seeking to kill a lawsuit by a woman who says police
violated her rights by failing to provide her medical attention
after she was arrested for speeding.
   The justices last year backed out of deciding the
municipal-liability issue in a case from Springfield, Mass.
   By a 5-4 vote, the court declined for procedural reasons to
decide whether Springfield should be forced to pay damages in the
death of a fleeing motorist killed by a policeman's bullet.
   The ruling left intact a $50,000 damage award the city was
ordered to pay to the victim's family.
   The case acted on today involves Geraldine Harris, who was
granted a retrial of her lawsuit by a lower court.
   Canton officials said alleged inadequate training of police in
summoning medical help should not be the basis for a lawsuit
against the city.
   Mrs. Harris' lawsuit grows out of an April 26, 1978, incident in
which she was stopped for speeding while driving her teen-age
daughter to school.
   Police said they put Mrs. Harris into a patrol wagon after the
52-year-old woman became upset and uncooperative. On arrival at the
police station, the officers said she was lying on the floor of the
vehicle.
   She repeatedly slumped to the floor during a stay of 30 to 40
minutes at the stationhouse.
   Police officers did not call for medical help. They said they
believed Mrs. Harris was merely excited and would calm down if left
alone and permitted to see her family.
   When family members arrived, they had Mrs. Harris taken by
ambulance to a hospital where she was diagnosed as suffering from
stress reaction, anxiety and depression. The symptoms included
immobility and difficulty in breathing. She was under psychiatric
care for more than a year later.
   The Harris family sued the city in federal court, and a jury
awarded $200,000 against the city on grounds Mrs. Harris
unreasonably was denied medical attention.
   The 6th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals threw out the verdict last
July, saying it was unclear on what theory the damage award was
based.
   The judge's instructions to the jury could have allowed it to
decide erroneously that the city was at fault even if the failure
to summon medical attention was not the result of a city policy,
the appeals court said.
   ``This instruction allows a finding of municipal liability
merely because (the city's) supervisory personnel did a bad act,
with no need to find that the city was a bad actor through a city
policy or custom. This was error,'' the appeals court said.
   Canton officials asked the Supreme Court to throw out the
lawsuit.
   City officials said the 6th Circuit court ruling will allow the
city to be found liable for misconduct at the retrial under an
unreasonably broad theory.
   The city may be forced to pay damages if the jury decides that
police were not trained adequately to summon medical help in such
cases, city officials said.
   The appeals court ruling will impose ``the novel requirement
upon cities that their police forces must provide paramedical
officers or other trained medical specialists who exercise some
type of professional judgment at the jail,'' city officials said.
   The Supreme Court recently has had trouble providing clear
guidelines on the issue of inadequate police training as grounds
for municipal liability in federal civil rights suits .
   In a 7-1 ruling in 1985 the justices threw out a $1.5 million
award against Oklahoma City in the shooting death of a tavern
patron by a police officer.
   Only four justices agreed it was a mistake for the jury to be
told it could infer from a single incident that the city was
grossly negligent in its police training. Three other justices
voted to throw out the award for other reasons.
   The case is Canton vs. Harris, 86-1088.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
