<HEAD>Hearings Finish In Dartmouth Confrontation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL MOKRZYCKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HANOVER, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A white student editor testified before a
Dartmouth College disciplinary panel that his staff was ``polite''
and did not harass a black professor in an incident that sparked
racial turmoil at the Ivy League school.
   But professor William Cole told the panel, which met over the
weekend, that the four white staff members of the conservative
Dartmouth Review were bigots and said he was harassed by them.
   The students said they were acting as journalists when they
confronted Cole on Feb. 25, several days after the off-campus
newspaper published an article sharply criticizing Cole.
   The disciplinary board will begin deliberating the fate of the
four reporters tonight. They face possible expulsion on charges of
harassment, disorderly conduct and invasion of privacy for taking
Cole's picture and recording him without his consent.
   The Committee on Standards heard nearly 16 hours of testimony
Saturday and Sunday concerning last former Review staffers made up most
of the roughly 25 people
watching the hearings, looked at each other with expressions of
disbelief.
   ``I think it had racial overtones, yes,'' said freshman Suzanna
Dotson after the hearing. ``He was saying without directly saying
that Professor Cole, who is of color, comes from a violent
background and that the four students, who are white, did not.''
   The defendants were Baldwin, Review photo editor John Quilhot,
executive editor John Sutter, and contributor Sean Nolan.
</TEXT>
