<FILEID>AP-NR-03-07-88 1022EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HelicopterReport     03-07 0485</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Helicopter Report,0500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Air Ambulance Firm Accused Of Federal Rule Violations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Utah company that provides helicopters and
crews for a third of the nation's civilian air ambulance services
has been accused of violating federal aviation regulations,
probably unintentionally, a newspaper reports.
   Most of Rocky Mountain Helicopter Service's alleged violations
involved paperwork and record-keeping deficiencies, The Pittsburgh
Press reported Sunday.
   The Federal Aviation Administration findings stem from a
two-month investigation of the company's safety procedures and
regulation compliance, said Wayne Barlow, director of the FAA's
Northwest Mountain Region, which covers Rocky Mountain's
headquarters in Provo, Utah.
   The alleged violations are being reviewed and the final number
could be fewer than the 120 now pending, Barlow said.
   ``It looks like a case where a small company based in one
location grew very rapidly to the point where it had aircraft and
people operating in dozens of states and no real handle on how to
manage them,'' he told The Press.
   Rocky Mountain Helicopter, the industry's largest vendor,
supplies aircraft, pilots and mechanics to hospitals in 39 cities,
including Allegheny General Hospital in Pittsburgh.
   Barlow said Rocky Mountain Helicopters faces possible fines
because the investigation uncovered a number of significant
problems. However, he said, the FAA believes Rocky Mountain is now
operating in compliance with regulations and the agency had no
plans to lift their license to fly.
   Russ Spray, the company's vice president of emergency medical
services operations, said, ``We don't deny we made some mistakes,
but we're fixing them as fast as they're being pointed out.''
   The inspection was spawned by congressional pressure on the FAA
last year after a record medical helicopter accident rate in 1986,
but the FAA said it also wanted to become more acquainted with the
medical helicopter industry.
   There are more than 235 medical helicopter programs operating at
least 500 helicopters in 46 states.
   ``What we learn from Rocky Mountain will help us to manage the
whole industry better,'' Barlow said.
   The FAA's 143-page report referred to such shortcomings as a
lack of documented training in evacuating patients from the
aircraft in emergencies, The Press reported.
   Other alleged violations ranged from a lack of training for the
company's pilots to the failure of the director of operations and
chief pilot to have the proper FAA licenses for those positions,
the newspaper said.
   On Feb. 12, Rocky Mountain voluntarily grounded 62 of its
helicopters until mechanics in each city could confirm all
maintenance and accompanying paperwork were up-to-date and accurate.
   ``In most cases, this (grounding) just took long enough for a
phone call to each city, but three aircraft were grounded for a day
or so for repairs,'' Spray said.
   On Feb. 17, Rocky Mountain grounded 24 of its pilots because
they did not have the proper paperwork to show they had received
required training.
   ``Within two days, all the pilots were flying legal again,''
Spray said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
