<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Adams 1stLd-Writethru a0553 03-07 0465</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Adams, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0553,450</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 3rd graf, Adams, who, to restore first name</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today agreed to consider
reinstating the death sentence of a Florida man convicted of
killing an 8-year-old girl in 1978.
   The court is expected to use the case to study death row
inmates' right to raise new issues when they turn to the federal
courts for help and to decide whether Florida juries may be told
their life-or-death recommendations are subject to the trial
judge's approval.
   Aubrey Adams, who once worked as a corrections officer at the
Marion Correctional Institution in Ocala, was convicted of the Jan.
23, 1978, strangulation of Trisa Gail Thornley near Ocala.
   His conviction and death sentence have been upheld three times
by the Florida Supreme Court. The nation's highest court refused to
review his case twice.
   In the second federal court appeal, Adams in early 1986
challenged statements made to the jury by the judge in his state
court sentencing trial.
   Under Florida law, a jury recommends life or death for convicted
murderers in capital cases. The presiding judge is free to follow
or disregard the recommendation.
   In Adams' case, the judge told jurors about that aspect of the
state's capital-sentencing law. ``The final decision as to what
punishment shall be imposed rests solely upon the judge of this
court,'' the jury was told.
   Adams argued that such jury instructions run afoul of a 1985
Supreme Court decision in which the justices, ruling in a
Mississippi case, said a death sentence is invalid if a jury is
misled about its role in determining whether the defendant actually
will die.
   In the case, a Mississippi prosecutor had told jurors they
should not view themselves as determining life or death because
their sentence would be reviewed automatically by an appeals court.
   The Supreme Court said such a statement misled the jury, and
rendered the subsequent death sentence ``cruel and unusual
punishment.''
   A federal judge dismissed Adams' 1986 appeal but the 11th U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals last Nov. 13 threw out his sentence.
   The appeals court said the judge's instructions to jurors
violated the Supreme Court's 1985 decision, adding that Adams was
entitled to ``a new sentencing proceeding before an untainted
jury.''
   In the appeal acted on today, Florida prosecutors noted that the
Florida Supreme Court previously had rejected an appeal in which
Adams mounted an identical challenge to the judge's instructions to
jurors.
   They asked the justices to resolve the conflict between the
state's highest court and the 11th Circuit court.
   The state's appeal also contended that Adams' challenge should
not have been allowed because he did not raise it in his first
federal court appeal.
   The case is Dugger vs. Adams, 87-121.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
