<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Churches     03-07 0610</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Churches,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Refuses to Free Churches from Financial-Disclosure Laws in
Tennessee Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today refused to free
churches from having to comply with state financial-disclosure laws
when waging public referendum campaigns.
   The court, citing the lack of a ``substantial federal
question,'' turned away a challenge by 13 churches from Jackson,
Tenn., to a law they contend violates their freedom of religion and
freedom of speech.
   The Tennessee law also affects other non-political organizations
that decided to campaign for or against issues that appear on
election ballots.
   The controversy arose during an August 1984 election held in
Jackson to determine whether establishments within the city would
be allowed to sell liquor by the drink.
   The local option referendum was defeated by a vote of 6,514 to
6,474 _ a 40-vote margin.
   The 13 area churches, nine of them Baptist-affiliated, took
varying steps to make public their opposition to allowing
on-premise liquor consumption in Jackson.
   The churches spent a total of $5,150, mostly for advertising, in
opposition to the referendum. But they failed to register as
``political campaign committees'' as required by the Tennessee
Campaign Financial Disclosure Act of 1980.
   The law defines such committees as any combination of two or
more people ``making expenditures to support or oppose any
candidate for public office or measure.'' It requires that the
committees designate a political treasurer and file
campaign-disclosure statements.
   The churches sued the state to challenge the law as applied to
them.
   At trial, pastors for the churches testified that the referendum
opposition resulted from moral, not political, concerns and that
they considered their actions to be part of the churches' religious
mission.
   The pastors also testified that their churches had not, and
would not, get involved in partisan political campaigns as a matter
of religious conviction.
   A state trial judge ruled against the churches, finding that all
of them are ``political campaign committees'' as defined by the
1980 state law and that the law is constitutional.
   A state appeals court later overturned the state law as a
violation of constitutional free-speech rights.
   The Tennessee Supreme Court last May 26 ruled that the law does
not violate free-speech rights when applied to either partisan
elections featuring candidates or non-partisan referendum elections.
   ``The recent history of campaign financial abuses as well as the
growth and possible dominance of special interest political action
committees make the state's disclosure requirements necessary to
allow the public to have some gauge by which to assess the sources,
content and frequency of campaign publicity and activity,'' the
state court ruled.
   Its ruling did not discuss the churches' argument that the law
violates their right to exercise freely their religious beliefs.
   In the appeal acted on today, lawyers for the 13 churches noted
that the justices have ``never passed on the validity of disclosure
requirements in referendum campaigns.''
   The appeal questioned whether any state may justify ``prior
registration and disclosure requirements to non-political
organizations in general and churches in particular.''
   Tennessee Attorney General W.J. Michael Cody urged the high
court to reject the churches' appeal.
   ``The fact that this is a referendum election does not make the
state's interest in providing any information to the voters as to
how the election is financed any less compelling,'' Cody said.
   The 13 churches who challenged the law are Bemis Pentecostal,
Calvary Baptist, Englewood Baptist, First Assembly of God, First
Baptist Church of Bemis, First Baptist Church of Jackson, Malesus
Baptist, North Jackson Baptist, Northside Assembly of God, Poplar
Heights Baptist, Skyline Church of Christ, West Jackson Baptist and
Woodland Baptist.
   The case is Bemis Pentecostal vs. Tennessee, 87-317.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
