<HEAD>Nunn Backs Gore In Democratic Presidential Race</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Sam Nunn, whose support is considered
important in the South, says he has cast his absentee ballot for
Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore Jr. in Tuesday's Democratic presidential
primary in Georgia.
   Nunn, D-Ga., in a statement released Sunday by aides as he was
leaving for a week-long trip to the Soviet Union, said he voted for
Gore because ``his views come closest to my own views as to the
steps our nation must take to meet our challenges at home and
abroad.''
   Nunn had refused on Friday during a news conference with Georgia
reporters to disclose how he voted, saying his position as chairman
of the Democratic Leadership Council precluded him from taking a
public stand between Gore and Missouri Rep. Richard Gephardt, both
members of the DLC.
   But he said in his statement Sunday that since that news
conference he had eceived ``a number of inquiries from Georgians
asking me privately whom I had favored in the March 8 primary
election.''
   ``Because I have responded frankly to these private inquiries, I
feel that it is now more appropriate for me to state publicly what
I have stated privately _ I voted for Al Gore,'' Nunn said.
