<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Access     03-07 0506</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Access,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Lets Stand Ruling on Criminal Trials in Louisiana Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today let stand a ruling
that the public has no right to attend hearings into the alleged
tainting or bribing of a criminal trial jury while the trial is
underway.
   The justices, without comment, refused to second-guess the
validity of conducting such hearings in secret during the 1986
racketeering trial of Louisiana Gov. Edwin W. Edwards.
   A federal appeals court, in upholding the closed hearings, ruled
that the public's constitutional right to attend criminal trials
does not extend to ``the midtrial questioning of jurors.''
   The appeals court also ruled that transcripts of the closed
hearings may be withheld from public disclosure during the trial
even if the jury is sequestered, and that the names of the jurors
involved may be erased from the transcripts.
   After a 1985 trial ended in mistrial because a federal jury
could not reach a unanimous verdict, then-Gov. Edwards and four
co-defendants stood trial again in 1986 on charges of racketeering
and bribery.
   All were acquitted after a two-month trial.
   On two occasions during the second trial, U.S. District Judge
Marcel Livaudais Jr. received reports that the sequestered jury had
been tainted.
   The first report suggested that one juror had told another that
jury members in Edwards' first trial were paid to vote for
acquittal.
   The second report suggested one juror had told another of a
possible bribery attempt by one defendant.
   In both instances, Livaudais conducted proceedings in his
chambers and determined that the people involved could continue
serving as jurors.
   Courtroom spectators, including news reporters, were given only
vague accounts of why the hearings were held. The judge said he
would release partial transcripts sometime after the trial was
completed, but that those transcripts would not include juror names.
   Three news organizations _ The Times-Picayune, Gannett News
Service and Capital City Press _ and several of their reporters
challenged the judge's use of closed hearings.
   The Times-Picayune is a New Orleans newspaper. Capital City
Press publishes the Morning Advocate and State-Times newspapers in
Baton Rouge.
   The challenge contended that Livaudais should have given the
reporters a chance to argue in favor of conducting open-court
hearings and that he was required to tell why it was necessary to
conduct the hearings in secret.
   The 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals last July 31 upheld the
closed hearings.
   The appeals court noted that past Supreme Court rulings have
established a public right of access to criminal trials but ruled
that under that constitutional right ``no presumption of openness
attaches to proceedings involving midtrial questioning of jurors.''
   ``If the questioning of impaneled jurors were held in open court
there is a substantial probability that what may have begun as a
`tempest in a teapot' will end in a mistrial, a hung jury or a
reversal on appeal,'' the 5th Circuit court said.
   The news organizations then sought Supreme Court review.
   The case is Times-Picayune Publishing vs. Edwards, 87-872.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880307-0037 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-07-88 1043EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Philippines     03-07 0531</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Philippines,0547</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ambush Near U.S.-Run Base Kills Nine Filipinos</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist rebels ambushed and killed
six Filipino sailors assigned to Subic Naval base 10 miles from the
U.S.-run installation, the military said today. Three civilians
also died in the shootout.
   Philippine officials today urged President Corazon Aquino to
develop a unified negotiating strategy before talks on the future
of American bases in the Philippines.
   One of the country's best-known rebel priests fled to Cebu City
from Mindanao island after he was wounded by comrades who learned
he was planning to surrender, officials said today.
   The Philippine Constabulary said the Philippine sailors were
traveling to Manila Sunday when rebels opened fire on their land
rover near the town of Hermosa on the Bataan peninsula.
   Three civilians were killed in the cross fire during the
15-minute battle, the military said. There were no reports of rebel
casualties.
   Subic, 50 miles west of Manila, is one of six installations
technically under Philippine command but effectively under U.S.
control.
   Communist rebels operate near both Subic and Clark Air Base,
about 50 miles north of Manila. In October last year, rebels killed
three Americans and a Filipino of U.S. extraction in coordinated
attacks outside Clark.
   Cabinet secretaries and members of Congress' Foreign Affairs
Committee told reporters after a two-hour meeting today with Mrs.
Aquino that they would continue talks to firm up the government
position on U.S.-run bases.
   The United States and the Philippines are expected to begin
talks in the next few weeks on the future of the U.S.-run
installations. Under the current agreement, either government can
unilaterally close the bases if it serves one-year's notice after
Sept. 16, 1991.
   Mrs. Aquino says she will honor the current bases treaty but has
refused to say whether she will agree to extend the agreement. Any
extension beyond 1991 requires approval by two-thirds of the
23-member Philippine Senate, where opposition to the bases is
strong.
   Sen. Leticia Shahani said matters to be discussed in the review
include the future of Filipino employees at the bases and the
possibility that nuclear weapons are being stored at the facilities.
   She said Mrs. Aquino is ``leaving us the liberty of taking a
stand. On the other hand there is a need to coordinate the
positions of the executive and the legislative.''
   Romeo Capangpangan, spokesman of the Department of Social
Welfare, said the rebel priest, Rev. Frank Navarro, sent word that
he was recuperating in a Cebu area hideout and wanted to surrender
and be granted amnesty.
   Navarro has been identified by the military as a New Peoples
Army commander in eastern Mindanao.
   Capangpangan said Navarro was apparently suffering from a bullet
wound in the shoulder which he received in an ambush by his own
followers last week in Mindanao's Surigao Del Sur province.
   Welfare Department official Amelita Costas told reporters that
her office was willing to meet Navarro at the place of his choice
and take him to safety without any military escorts.
   The government amnesty program for communist and Moslem rebels
expired at the end of February. But Defense Secretary Fidel Ramos
said rebels who wanted to surrender could receive amnesty on a
case-by-case basis.
</TEXT>
