<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Vindictive     03-07 0384</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Vindictive,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Refuses to Reinstate Charges Against 36 Arrested Outside
White House</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today refused to reinstate
charges against 36 people arrested outside the White House while
protesting Reagan administration domestic and foreign policies.
   The court, without comment, left intact rulings that dismissed
the charges on grounds government prosecutors acted vindictively.
   A demonstration for ``peace, jobs and justice'' occurred April
22, 1985. About 200 participants were arrested.
   They were charged with violating the terms of their U.S. Park
Police march permit by sitting down on sidewalks outside the White
House.
   Most of those arrested agreed to pay a $50 fine for
demonstrating without a permit rather than stand trial.
   But 36 demonstrators chose to stand trial. They were charged _
in addition to demonstrating without a permit _ with obstructing
the sidewalks adjacent to the White House.
   Each charge carries a maximum penalty of six months in prison
and a $500 fine.
   U.S. District Judge Aubrey Robinson ordered all charges against
the 36 dismissed, ruling that prosecutors acted vindictively by
bringing the second charge only for those who chose to stand trial.
   The U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals upheld Robinson's decision
last year.
   The appeals court said there was ample evidence for Robinson to
conclude that prosecutors added the second charge to punish
demonstrators for choosing to stand trial.
   ``A large group of defendants threatened to go to trial on what
the government considered petty offenses,'' the appeals court said.
``The government had a strong incentive to try to keep clear of
this courtroom morass. It wished to avoid the annoyance and expense
of prosecuting these minor cases at a potentially drawn-out trial.''
   Prosecutors showed a `` disturbing willingness to toy with the
defendants,'' the appeals court added.
   It said Robinson was justified in throwing out both charges
against the 36 demonstrators, not merely the second accusation that
they obstructed the sidewalks.
   ``If in cases of vindictive prosecution the trial court judge
may only dismiss the additional charge, the prosecutor wil have
nothing to lose by acting vindictively,'' the appeals court said.
   The Reagan administration said the lower court rulings could
``significantly hamper'' the government's handling off mass
demonstrations in the nation's capital.
   The case is U.S. vs. Meyer, 87-730.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880307-0039 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-07-88 1045EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Blatty     03-07 0207</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Blatty,180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Refuses to Review Lawsuit By Author Against New York Times</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today refused to revive a $3
million lawsuit by author William Peter Blatty against The New York
Times for the treatment his 1983 novel ``Legion'' received on the
newspaper's weekly Best Seller List.
   The justices, without comment, let stand a California Supreme
Court ruling that dismissed Blatty's lawsuit alleging intentional
interference with prospective business advantage.
   Blatty, author of ``The Exorcist,'' contended that the Times
excluded ``Legion'' from the weekly list for a period even though
the newspaper knew the novel had sold enough copies to qualify.
   The California Supreme Court, by a 7-0 vote last Dec. 29, said
Blatty could not pursue the lawsuit.
   Four of the state court's justices based their ruling on the
federal Constitution's free-speech protections and the even greater
protections for speech offered by the California Constitution.
   They said such a lawsuit is barred unless a defendant has made a
statement ``of and concerning'' the plaintiff.
   Three of the state court's justices said Blatty had failed to
suggest that the newspaper intentionally misrepresented the results
of its bookstore sales survey to hurt him financially.
   The case is Blatty vs. New York Times, 86-1803.
</TEXT>
