<2ND_LINE>PM-Jordan-Shultz,0311</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jordan Says It Welcomes U.S. Peace Mission</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMAL HALABY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMMAN, Jordan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jordan said today it welcomed the U.S.
peace initiative but insisted that the PLO participate in talks to
quell violence in the Israeli-occupied territories.
   Information Minister Hani Khasawneh said Amman will ``be
reporting to the U.S. administration as soon as we finish our
consultations'' with other Arab countries on the peace plan carried
to the Middle East last week by Secretary of State George P. Shultz.
   ``We always seek a united Arab stand toward any peace process in
the area,'' he said.
   He said there was no deadline for formulating a response to the
U.S. initiative. Shultz reportedly has asked Jordan, Syria, Egypt
and Israel to report back by the middle of the month.
   The American plan calls for an international conference to
launch bilateral talks between Israel and a Palestinian-Jordanian
delegation.
   The two sides would start in May to negotiate limited self-rule
for the 1.5 million Palestinians and in December would begin talks
on a final settlement of the Arab-Israeli conflict.
   Israel's coalition government is split along party lines over
the American plan.
   The blueprint outlined by Shultz proposed an international peace
conference involving Jordan, Syria and Palestinian representatives,
but not the Palestine Liberation Organization.
   Both the United States and Israel refuse to meet with the PLO
because they consider it a terrorist organization.
   The Jordanian minister renewed Jordan's call for an
international peace conference under U.N. auspices and attended by
all concerned parties in the conflict, including the PLO and the
Soviet Union.
   Asked if Jordan was optimistic, he said: ``We can't say so yet,
but we hope we'll get fruitful results.
   ``We're interested in a peace settlement and that's why we
welcome the U.S. movement,'' Khasawneh said.
</TEXT>
