<HEAD>Family Fears For Safety Of Man Kidnapped In Nicaragua</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GREENSBORO, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A co-worker and a relative of an
American kidnapped in Nicaragua last week by Contra rebels say they
have been told he is safe, but add that they don't trust the
Contras.
   Richard Boren, of Elkin, was among 12 people abducted Tuesday
from the village of Mancotal in northern Nicaragua.
   ``The main thing that my family wants is for him to be
released,'' said Carol Owens, Boren's sister, who lives in Carrboro.
   Contras, who oppose Nicaragua's leftist Sandinista government,
claim the group was ``detained,'' not kidnapped.
   Boren, 30, is a long-term volunteer with Witness for Peace, a
U.S.-based grass-roots ecumenical group that works in the war zones
of Nicaragua trying to change U.S. policy toward the country.
   He has been in Nicaragua since November, assigned to travel from
town to town along the Honduran border recording witnesses' stories
of Contra attacks.
   Dennis Marker, director of the Washington office of Witness For
Peace, said Contras kicked down the door of a house in which Boren
was staying and began shooting, wounding a 13-year-old girl in the
leg.
   Boren was taken prisoner at gunpoint while trying to bandage the
girl's wound, Marker said.
   Six of the abductees have escaped since Tuesday, he said, and
one has told Witness For Peace specifics of the incident.
   ``The Contras still have Richard, and he obviously can't go
until they let him go,'' Marker said. ``I believe if they wanted
to, they could release him immediately.''
   ``We're not one bit happy that they're holding him, and we don't
trust them, quite frankly,'' Marker said.
   Marker said a Contra leader confirmed Friday only that they had
Boren and that he was safe.
   Ms. Owen, who said she didn't learn of the abduction until
Thursday night, said State Department officials told her Saturday
that her brother was all right.
</TEXT>
