<1ST_LINE>r i PM-India-Punjab     03-07 0344</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-India-Punjab,0357</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government To Amend Constitution For Punjab</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government announced plans today to
amend the constitution to make it easier to extend direct federal
rule in troubled state of Punjab, where Sikh militants have been
waging a bloody campaign for independence.
   P. Chidambaram, deputy home minister, told the governing lower
house of Parliament the amendments would only apply to Punjab.
   He said the amendments would allow the government to extend
direct federal rule for more than the one year presently allowed by
the constitution.
   Punjab's state government was dismissed in May 1987 for failing
to curb Sikh terrorism, and the state was placed under federal rule
for six months. The duration was extended for another six months.
   On Sunday the federal government went a step further and
dissolved the state assembly, paving the way for fresh elections.
   Chidambaram said articles of the constitution dealing with
emergency rule will be amended to enable the government to impose a
state of emergency on one state at a time.
   Under the current rules, a state of emergency can be imposed on
the whole country but not on individual states.
   At least 391 people have been killed in Punjab this year in
attacks blamed on Sikh extremists. More than 1,000 people were
killed last year.
   The minister, citing a government report on Punjab, said the
state assembly was dissolved because of the ``interference from
members of the legislative assembly in the effective and efficient
working of the police.''
   There were numerous reports, he said, when legislators ``not
only attempted to interfere, influence and prevent the police
action but also threatening police officers of dire consequences if
they failed to obey their commands,'' Chidambaram said.
   He claimed the imposition of direct federal rule had brought
about a ``distinct'' improvement in the situation in Punjab.
   The formal bill proposing the amendments is likely to come at
the end of the month. It is expected to pass easily since the
Congress Party of Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi has a majority in the
lower house.
</TEXT>
