<DOCNO> AP880307-0049 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-07-88 1108EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-AgeBias     03-07 0500</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Age Bias,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Refuses to Reinstate Pennsylvania Law on Retirement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today refused to reinstate a
Pennsylvania law forcing state police officers to retire at age 60.
   The court, without comment, let stand a ruling that the state
law violates federal restrictions against discrimination based on
age.
   The 3rd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ruled last June that
Pennsylvania violated the federal Age Discrimination in Employment
Act.
   The appeals court said it is illegal to presume that officers
over 60 are physically unfit for their work when officials have
failed to adopt minimum fitness standards for all workers.
   ``Until minimum standards are developed, implemented and
enforced, the Pennsylvania State Police cannot justify its
mandatory retirement law by relying on good health and physical
conditioning as ... reasonably necessary to Pennsylvania State
Police business,'' the appeals court said.
   The appeals court noted that New Jersey, a neighboring state of
Pennsylvania, has a mandatory retirement age of 55 for state
troopers that has been upheld in the courts.
   But the appeals court said, ``All members of the New Jersey
State Police are subject to mandatory fitness requirements and are
sanctioned for non-compliance.''
   The federal law against age bias generally permits employers to
force workers to retire before 70 only if it can be shown that
being under 70 is a bona fide occupational qualification or if
employers can prove it is highly impractical to test workers
individually to assure they are still fit.
   The Supreme Court, in a pair of 1985 rulings that reinforced the
employment rights of older workers, struck down efforts to force
city firefighters to retire at age 55 and flight engineers at age
60.
   The 3rd Circuit court cited those cases in invalidating
Pennsylvania's mandatory retirement age for state police officers.
   Pennsylvania officials said the appeals court ruling places a
heavy financial burden on the state.
   The state said it could be forced to pay $4 million in back pay
and benefits to officers who have been forced to retire.
   Officials also said that testing state police officers for
fitness would be a costly process. They said it would cost some
$2.4 million to determine whether the force's 4,000 members are
healthy and fit.
   The state said its retirement-age policy is reasonable because
of statistics that show a sharp decline in average fitness and
health for older people.
   For example, the state said the decrease in aerobic capacity for
an average group of men aged 26 and an average group of men age 58
is 57 percent. Relative strength declines by about 35 percent
between the ages of 29 and 50 and muscular endurance slips by 30
percent between ages 30 and 60, the officials said.
   Pennsylvania's retirement law was challenged by the federal
Equal Employment Opportunity Commission and Otto J. Binker, a
lieutenant on the state police force who was near age 60 in 1983
when the suit was filed.
   The case is Pennsylvania vs. Equal Employment Opportunity
Commission, 87-958.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880307-0050 </DOCNO>
