<FILEID>AP-NR-03-07-88 1127EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Iran-Contra     03-07 0442</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iran-Contra,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Casey's Widow Testifies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The widow of former CIA director William J.
Casey testified today before the special federal grand jury that is
investigating the Iran-Contra affair.
   Sophia Casey likely was questioned about what her husband might
have told her before his death last year about the sale of U.S.
arms to Iran to obtain the release of American hostages and whether
he mentioned anything about the diversion of proceeds to the
Contras.
   Casey, who died of pneumonia on May 6, 1987, after suffering
from brain cancer, was CIA director when U.S. arm were sold to Iran
in 1985 and 1986.
   The agency provided logistical support to covert operations to
help the Contras. Those operations were coordinated by former
National Security Council aide Lt. Col. Oliver L. North.
   North told Congress that he was acting with Casey's approval and
that the former CIA director recommended that he recruit retired
Air Force Maj. Gen. Richard V. Secord to set up the private supply
network because Secord had experience in special operations.
   Secord, who set up secret Swiss bank accounts to funnel private
donations to the Contras, also helped broker the sale of U.S. arms
to Iran with his partner, Albert Hakim.
   North told Congress last summer that Casey saw the diversion as
part of an effort to create a ``stand-alone'' or ``off-the-shelf''
enterprise that could engage in covert activities outside
congressional review.
   Mrs. Casey's testimony comes as the grand jury appears to be
preparing to return criminal indictments against the targets of the
investigation, including North, Secord, Hakim and former national
security adviser John M. Poindexter.
   Mrs. Casey, who lives in Roslyn Harbor, N.Y., last fall disputed
a published account by journalist Bob Woodward that Casey knew
about the diversion to the Contra rebels.
   In his book ``Veil: The Secret Wars of the CIA,'' Woodward said
that during an interview in the hospital Casey acknowledged knowing
about the diversion.
   In a Sept. 28, 1987, interview, Mrs. Casey said her husband
never told her of the diversion and expressed doubt that he knew
about it.
   She termed ``absolute blasphemy'' Woodward's account that Casey
had criticized President Reagan as ``lazy and distracted.''
   ``He's lying about that,'' Mrs. Casey told The Associated Press.
   She described her husband as ``a team player'' and a ``great
patriot who would never do anything to harm his president.''
   Mrs. Casey also expressed outrage at Woodward's report that
Casey was ``struck by the overall passivity of the president.''
   ``Bill would never say that about the president,'' she said.
``Bill loved Reagan and they were very close. It's been very
hurtful.''
</TEXT>
