<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Iditarod 1stLd-Writethru a0513 03-07 0377</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iditarod, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0513,0385</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Leaders Warm Weather Slows Mushers</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout, mushers moving out of Finger Lake</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fighting warm temperatures and wet
snow, the leaders in the Iditarod Trail Sled Dog Race were out of
Finger Lake and on their way to Rainy Pass early today.
   Thirteen teams left the Finger Lake checkpoint, 193 miles from
the 1,158-mile race's starting line, in one hour late Sunday.
Twenty-three other teams had arrived at the checkpoint.
   Lavon Barve of Wasilla and Jerry Austin of St. Michael pulled
out at 7:39 p.m. They were followed by DeeDee Jonrowe of Bethel,
1987 champion Susan Butcher of Manley, four-time champion Rick
Swenson of Two Rivers and Tim Moerlein of Kasilof.
   Barve and Swenson had declared their 24-hour layovers, then
canceled the layover. All mushers are required to halt for one full
24 hour period during the race to rest themselves and their dogs.
   Temperatures in the Rainy Pass area were in the high 20s early
today, the National Weather Service reported. Temperatures that
hovered around 32 degrees on Saturday took a toll on many of the
sled dogs, which are accustomed to running in much colder weather.
   Herbie Nayokpuk was 18th into Skwentna, a checkpoint 148 miles
from Anchorage, and notified officials he would take the race's
mandatory 24-hour layover in Skwentna.
   ``I've got to save some of my dogs,'' he said. ``I almost burned
them up. I'll have to rest them a little bit.''
   When the lead mushers reach Puntilla Lake in Rainy Pass, they
will have covered 223 miles of the 1,158-mile race.
   Fifty-two teams started the race early Saturday. Defending
champion Butcher finished last year's race in a record 11 days, two
hours.
   The race is inspired by a 1925 dog sled relay that rushed
diphtheria serum to Nome during an outbreak of the disease. The top
20 mushers will split a purse of $150,000. The winner will get
$30,000.
   U.S. mushers from outside Alaska, and their positions: Frank
Teasley of Jackson, Wyo., was 15th; Terry Adkins of Mikado, Mich.,
was 21st; Robin Jacobson of Minnetonka, Minn., was 27th; Dan
MacEachen of Snowmass Village, Colo., was 29th; John Patten of
Grand Marais, Minn., was 35st; and Stan Ferguson of Philadelphia
was 41th.
</TEXT>
