<DOCNO> AP880307-0060 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-07-88 1218EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Negotiations     03-07 0704</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Negotiations,700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Retransmitting to fix priority code</HEAD>
<HEAD>Court Gives Investors Important Victory</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court, in an important victory for
investors, today placed a heavy burden of proof on companies that
are sued for denying they are holding merger negotiations after
such preliminary talks are underway.
   By a 4-2 vote, the court said if companies withhold important
information affecting stock prices, it must be presumed that
investors who bought and sold the securities were relying on that
information.
   ``An investor who buys or sells stock at the price set by the
market does so in reliance on the integrity of that price,'' said
Justice Harry A. Blackmun for the court. ``Because most publicly
available information is reflected in market price, an investor's
reliance on any public material misrepresentations, therefore, may
be presumed.''
   The absence of a five-vote majority in the case raises the
possibility the issue could be reconsidered by the justices in
another case with a different result. But, for now at least,
today's decision is likely to have important repercussions on Wall
Street.
   Justice Anthony M. Kennedy, who joined the court last month, did
not take part in considering the case. Chief Justice William H.
Rehnquist and Justice Antonin Scalia disqualified themselves from
participating without explanation.
   The court ordered further hearings in a dispute involving Basic
Inc. of Cleveland.
   The company merged with CEBAS Inc., a subsidiary of Combustion
Engineering based in Connecticut, in December 1978.
   Stockholders said Basic executives falsely denied for 14 months
prior to the merger that at least preliminary talks were underway
between the two companies.
   As a result, many investors said they sold their stock at far
less than its value.
   Combustion Engineering is a conglomerate that makes alumina or
acid-based refractories _ non-metallic ceramic substances used as
structural materials. Both Basic and Combustion Engineering were
traded on the New York Stock Exchange.
   The stock of Basic was selling at well under $20 a share when
merger rumors began surfacing in late 1977. There was a dramatic
increase in the volume of activity in the stock accompanied by a
sharp run-up in price. The eventual merger price of the stock was
$46 a share.
   Company officials repeatedly said they could not account for the
activity and denied merger negotiations were underway.
   The 6th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ruled in 1986 that public
statements by Basic management during the period leading up to the
merger were misleading or untrue, even if the company's denials of
negotiations might be correct technically.
   The Supreme Court today rejected the appellate court's reasoning
that the company's denial of the preliminary talks by itself
created grounds for the investors to win their suit.
   Information about a company that is otherwise insignificant does
not become important _ or material to the stock's value _ solely
because the company denied existence of the development, Blackmun
said.
   ``Materiality is something to be determined on the basis of the
particular facts of each case,'' Blackmun said. ``Materiality
depends on the significance the reasonable investor would place on
the withheld or misrepresented information.''
   Using that standard, the court ordered further lower court
hearings in the suit by investors in Basic who said they lost money
because facts were withheld from them.
   Blackmun said the presumption at the new hearings must be that
the investors would have relied on those facts, unless the
management of Basic can prove otherwise.
   ``Where materially misleading statements have been disseminated
into an impersonal, well-developed market for securities, the
reliance of individual plaintiffs on the integrity of the market
price may be presumed,'' Blackmun said.
   He was joined by Justices William J. Brennan, Thurgood Marshall
and John Paul Stevens.
   Justice Byron R. White, in an opinion joined by Justice Sandra
Day O'Connor, said the ruling ``may have many adverse, unintended
effects as it is applied and interpreted in the years to come.''
   For example, White said many investors in Basic who are now
suing may have doubted the company's denials that preliminary
merger talks were underway.
   ``Such investors, the savviest of the savvy, will be able to
recover under the court's opinion,'' White said.
   The case is Basic Inc. vs. Levinson, 86-279.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
