<2ND_LINE>AM-South Africa,0221</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Blacks Killed In Police Shootout</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two blacks described by police
as ``trained terrorists'' were killed, and six policemen were
slightly injured in a shootout at a house in Queenstown, police
said Monday.
   Police, acting on a tip, surrounded a house in the southern city
on Friday afternoon and ordered the inhabitants to leave. When the
occupants refused, police threw ``stun grenades'' into the house,
police said in a statement.
   A stun grenade contains no shrapnel and is considered non-lethal.
   A shootout ensued, and two black men inside the house were
killed. The six officers suffered minor injuries, the statement
said.
   Police did not say how they knew the men were ``trained
terrorists.''
   Also Monday, police said they expelled seven police reservists
because they were members of the extreme right-wing Afrikaner
Resistance Movement.
   The paramilitary group seeks a whites-only homeland within South
Africa and has been taking an increasingly confrontational stance
recently against the white-led government.
   Several thousand members marched on government buildings on Feb.
27 to present a petition calling for an all-white state.
   The government said last week it would dismiss policemen holding
membership in the organization. The seven reservists, from northern
Transvaal province, were the first policemen expelled under the
government's new policy.
