<FILEID>AP-NR-03-07-88 1230EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Mob     03-07 0565</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Mob,0581</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rackets Run Rampant In Mobster-Riddled Republic, Pravda Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corruption is so rampant in the Soviet republic of
Turkmenia that a powerful underworld has developed, complete with
hit men, protection rackets, police payoffs and powerful mob
chieftains, Pravda said Monday.
   The Communist Party newspaper even noted that the funeral of an
underworld crime boss drew 400 mourners.
   Pravda said many police officers not only looked the other way
at crime in the Central Asian republic, but masterminded some of
the schemes. It said 12 are now are on trial for extortion.
   ``They extorted money mostly from those who wouldn't appeal to
the police, like a certain Gavrush Sarkisya, a former shop foreman,
who confessed to the police later that he owed the criminals
($150,000),'' Pravda said. ``And they threatened him with a firing
squad should he fail to pay up.''
   Other Central Asian republics also have been blasted by the
Soviet media for large-scale corruption. In recent months, the
media have exposed millions of dollars in graft in Uzbekistan,
Turkmenia's neighbor to the north.
   On Jan. 20, the weekly Literaturnaya Gazeta disclosed that the
head of an agricultural complex in Uzbekistan built his own mob
empire, complete with his own courts and an underground prison
constructed by 1,000 workers.
   The expose was striking in its recitation of abuses.
   Pravda's account on Turkmenia, while not as dramatic, was the
strongest criticism yet of the Soviet Union's southernmost
republic, which has 3.27 million people, mostly Moslems.
   Official media criticism of Turkmenia usually has centered
around Moslem customs judged by the central government to be
abhorent, such as reports of young women being killed for
insufficient marriage dowries.
   ``The republic suffers a difficult situation, created over years
of bureaucratic rule,'' Pravda said. Referring to the swelling
bureacracy, it added: ``Every sixth person in the republic is a
hack official.
   ``Many highly placed police officials, and policemen of lesser
ranks, were involved in all kinds of crimes and often acted as
their skilled masterminds,'' the newspaper reported.
   Pravda said the crackdown in the region began with the recent
appointment of Alexander F. Udalov as the republic's police chief.
Pravda said he was threatened shortly after taking office by Ilyas
A. Sarkiev, one of those now on trial.
   ``Just leave me alone. Quit this case. Several hundred thousand
rubles will go your way,'' Sarkiev was quoted as telling Udalov.
``Also keep in mind. I know the city your daughter lives in. I have
nothing to lose, you know. You won't be able to get all my people.''
   The newspaper said that Sarkiev was arrested three days after
making the threat.
   Pravda also described a threat against A. Allaverdov, the
manager of a footwear shop in Ashkabad. He reported that when he
had a falling out with Sarkiev, violence began.
   Allaverdov told authorities his new car was stolen and found
burned the next morning in the center of the city. The windows of
his apartment were shot out, he said, and he received a threat that
his son would be kidnapped.
   Pravda said the recent crackdown has routed several
``criminals'' from official posts in Turkmenia, but it noted that a
recent funeral illustrated continuing problems.
   ``A well-known underworld figure died in a traffic accident.
Four hundred criminals came to his funeral from different cities,
which goes to show the atmosphere in Ashkhabad quite well,'' Pravda
said.
</TEXT>
