<2ND_LINE>AM-Flynn-Parade,0284</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mayor May Skip Hometown Parade And Spend St. Patrick's Day In
Ireland</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Raymond L. Flynn says he may skip Boston's
St. Patrick's Day parade because he and his wife have been invited
to Dublin by Irish Prime Minister Charles Haughey.
   Missing the parade in South Boston would mean Flynn would not
face jeers similar to those he faced at a recent hearing on his
plan to desegregate housing projects in that neighborhood.
   Flynn was invited to Dublin to help celebrate that city's
millenium.
   Police said Flynn's integration proposal has made him a target
of increasing death threats.
   ``We've gotten threats periodically since he came into office,
but they've increased over the past few weeks,'' said Sgt.
Detective Edward Wallace. ``We're treating it as a serious matter.''
   Flynn's wife, Cathy, said she was preparing to go to church
Sunday when police told her someone had threatened to bomb the
house. Wallace said a search failed to turn up any explosive device.
   ``I took a position that I believe in and I'm going to see that
it's implemented,'' the mayor said Saturday about his housing plan.
``I can't just worry about the political consequences of everything
I do. People in Southie have more respect for somebody who takes a
position rather than someone who ducks and hides behind someone
else.''
   City Councilor James Kelly, of South Boston, said he believed
Flynn was skipping the parade to avoid potential embarrassment.
   ``I think the mayor feels he would not be that well-received,''
said Kelly, a vocal Flynn critic. ``Obviously that would not be
good for his image. After all, this is his neighborhood.''
</TEXT>
