<FILEID>AP-NR-03-07-88 1241EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Terrorism-EastEurope     03-07 0820</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Terrorism-East Europe,790</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Gains East German, Polish Aid in Closing Abu Nidal Business</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. officials are monitoring Polish and East
German cooperation with efforts to close down an arms trading
office affiliated with the Abu Nidal terrorist group.
   According to a CIA report, Abu Nidal kept an apartment in Warsaw
and his associates ran a trade operation from an office tower there
after he was forced to leave Iraq in 1983.
   Last summer, U.S. diplomats began pressuring the Polish
government privately, and in August the Poles promised to close the
operation, S.A.S.-International Commerce and Investments, and order
its staff to leave the country. A similar operation was closed in
East Germany.
   ``The front offices have been shut down in Poland and East
Germany,'' a State Department official said. ``They have told us
and we believe that they have been shut down.''
   ``This doesn't necessarily mean that these governments have
ended all their contacts with Abu Nidal's associates for good. We'd
like to think so. It is something that remains to be seen,'' said
the source, who like others interviewed over the past week spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   Polish officials insisted that the government ``had no idea''
what S.A.S. was.
   But U.S. officials say Polish security agencies must have known
that Abu Nidal had overall control over S.A.S., and that the
organization was selling Soviet-bloc arms in the Middle East.
   ``There are factions in these governments, and top political
leaders and places like the foreign ministries might not have known
what was going on,'' one U.S. government terrorism expert said.
   Abu Nidal, nom de guerre of Palestinian-born Sabri al-Banna, is
now believed to live in Tunis, according to Soviet-bloc and
administration sources.
   Abu Nidal's group is blamed for numerous terrorist incidents,
including attacks in the Rome and Vienna airports on Dec. 27, 1985,
in which 18 people were killed.
   The head of S.A.S., Samir Hasan Najmeddin, was forced to leave
Poland on Jan. 14, several days after the departure of his top
deputy, according to Polish officials.
   The Poles delayed the expulsions for nearly a month past a
promised December deadline, upsetting some U.S. counterterrorism
officials who pushed for release of an unclassified version of the
CIA report.
   U.S. diplomats dealing with Europe, meanwhile, sought to keep
the affair under wraps, administration sources said.
   Some details of the report were published in The New York Times,
however, angering Polish leader Wojciech Jaruzelski, who complained
about the leak during a January meeting in Warsaw with Deputy
Secretary of State John C. Whitehead, the No. 2 official in the
department, sources said. Whitehead expressed ``regret'' about the
disclosure, the sources said.
   The CIA report, which was discussed by administration officials
but not shown to the AP, said Najmeddin settled in Warsaw in 1973
at No. 3 Bagno St., Apt. 24, and founded S.A.S. 10 years later to
sell arms and other goods abroad, mainly in the Middle East. S.A.S.
maintained offices on the 25th floor of the Intraco Building in
Warsaw.
   Poland earned badly needed foreign currency from the enterprise,
and Abu Nidal's group kept most of the profit as well as weapons.
   S.A.S. was the most important link in a chain of legitimate
business enterprises affiliated with Abu Nidal in Europe, the U.S.
report said.
   The East Germans allowed an Abu Nidal affiliate called Zibado
Consultant and International Commerce to keep an office on
Friedrichstrasse in East Berlin in 1983-86, but now have closed it,
and Bulgarian officials also have curtailed their ties with
terrorist organizations, according to a senior administration
source.
   Polish government spokesman Jerzy Urban announced the closure of
the S.A.S. office in January and said authorities did not know
whether Abu Nidal had ever been in Poland.
   ``I am saying this cautiously, because the authorities cannot
exclude'' that Abu Nidal entered the country under another name,
Urban told reporters.
   According to the CIA, Abu Nidal presided over at least four
meetings in Warsaw, two in December 1983, again in September 1984
and most recently in June 1987.
   In Poland, S.A.S. dealt with the Etat Cenzin Co. and paid its
representative, Andrzej Marchewska, $600 a month to facilitate
visas for Palestinian operatives and obtain customs clearances for
shipments of pistols, rifles and hand-held anti-tank and
anti-aircraft weapons.
   The CIA report said many of these weapons went to terrorists
linked to Abu Nidal.
   In the summer of 1984, the report said, S.A.S sold Libya 4,000
Soviet-designed Kalashnikov assault rifles made in East Germany for
about $500,000.
   The next year, S.A.S. was agent for the sale of rifles and
pistols in the Middle East.
   In 1986, the report said, the company obtained 115 British
Enfield anti-riot weapons, keeping 15 and giving 100 to East German
authorities.
   Additionally, the report said, S.A.S. sponsored scholarships for
Palestinians to study in Poland, and some of them were recruited
into Abu Nidal's terrorist organization.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
