<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Palestinian     03-07 0269</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Palestinian,0275</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>El Al Bomb Convict Loses Appeal Against Sentence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Palestinian convicted of trying to plant a bomb
on an Israeli airliner lost his bid to appeal his 45-year sentence
Monday after a judge declared the prison term was ``not a day too
long.''
   Nezar Hindawi was jailed in October 1986 for duping his pregnant
fiancee into carrying a bomb aboard an El Al jumbo jet at London's
Heathrow Airport the previous April. Israeli guards found the bomb
before it reached the plane.
   Allegations that the Jordan-born Palestinian was in league with
the Syrian Embassy in London led Britain to sever diplomatic ties
with Damascus. Hindawi claimed the Israelis framed him.
   Hindawi's sentence was ``not a day too long'' for ``as foul and
as horrible a crime as can possibly be imagined,'' ruled Lord Chief
Justice Geoffrey Lane, presiding over the three-judge Appeals Court.
   Hindawi's attorney, Michael Massih, argued that Hindawi's
actions had not caused loss of life. But Lane said, ``It is no
thanks to him that he did not succeed in destroying 36O to 37O
lives in an effort to promote one side of a political dispute by
terrorism.''
   Pleading for Hindawi to be permitted to appeal his sentence,
Massih argued that it was harsh compared with the 35-year sentence
imposed on Patrick Magee, convicted of planting an Irish Republican
Army bomb in a hotel where Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher was
staying. That bomb killed five people.
   Lane pointed out that unlike Magee, Hindawi could get one-third
off for good conduct and serve only 30 years.
   Hindawi, 33, was not in court.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880307-0080 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-07-88 1256EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w BC-ScotusAt-a-Glance     03-07 0673</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Scotus At-a-Glance,650</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here, at a glance, are highlights of actions
taken Monday by the Supreme Court.
   
   ADULT BOOKSTORES
   
   The court agreed to decide whether states may use
anti-racketeering laws to close down adult bookstores.
   The justices said they will review a pair of free-speech
challenges to such an Indiana law.
   The cases are Fort Wayne Books vs. Indiana, 87-470; and
Sappenfield vs. Indiana, 87-614.
   
   DEATH PENALTY
   
   The court agreed to consider reinstating the death sentence of a
Florida man convicted of killing an 8-year-old girl in 1978.
   The court is expected to use the case to study death row
inmates' right to raise new issues when they turn to the federal
courts for help and to decide whether Florida juries may be told
their life-or-death recommendations are subject to the trial
judge's approval.
   The case is Dugger vs. Adams, 87-121.
   
   VACCINE
   
   The court left intact a $1.13 million jury award to an Idaho boy
paralyzed from the waist down after he was given a vaccination for
three diseases.
   The court, without comment, rejected arguments by the vaccine
manufacturer that such verdicts could force drug companies to
abandon the production of essential vaccines.
   The case is Lederle Laboratories vs. Toner, 87-1151.
   
   FARM BANKRUPTCY
   
   The court ruled unanimously that financially troubled farmers
may not avoid foreclosure under federal bankruptcy law by promising
to use their labor, experience and expertise in continuing to
operate their farm.
   By an 8-0 vote, the court said a secured creditor's right to
``adequate protection'' under bankruptcy law cannot be satisfied by
such a promise.
   The case is Norwest Bank Worthington vs. Ahler, 86-958.
   
   CHURCHES
   
   The court refused to free churches from having to comply with
state financial-disclosure laws when waging public referendum
campaigns.
   The court, citing the lack of a ``substantial federal
question,'' turned away a challenge by 13 churches from Jackson,
Tenn., to a law they contend violates their freedom of religion and
freedom of speech.
   The case is Bemis Pentacostal vs. Tennessee, 87-317.
   
   SECRET HEARINGS
   
   The court let stand a ruling that the public has no right to
attend hearings into the alleged tainting or bribing of a criminal
trial jury while the trial is underway.
   The justices, without comment, refused to second-guess the
validity of conducting such hearings in secret during the 1986
racketeering trial of Louisiana Gov. Edwin W. Edwards.
   The case is Times-Picayune Publishing vs. Edwards, 87-872.
   
   GLOBE LIBEL
   
   The court cleared the way for a jury trial in former
Massachusetts Gov. Edward J. King's $3.6 million libel lawsuit
against the Boston Globe.
   The justices, over one dissenting vote, left intact a
Massachusetts Supreme Judicial Court ruling that a jury should hear
King's contention that he was libeled by a Nov. 8, 1981, column.
   The case is Globe Newspaper Co. vs. King, 87-731.
   
   MOBILE HOMES
   
   The court cleared the way for a trial in what may become an
important test case on the power of cities to control rents and
otherwise protect mobile home residents.
   The court, without comment, rejected an appeal by Santa Barbara,
Calif., officials aimed at killing a lawsuit by owners of a mobile
home park who claim they unfairly are being deprived of their
property's full value.
   The case is Santa Barbara vs. Hall, 87-220.
   
   JEHOVAH'S WITNESS
   
   The court refused to hear the appeal of a Florida woman who says
she was denied custody of her young child because she is a
Jehovah's Witness.
   The justices, without comment, let stand state court rulings
that bar Rita Mendez from exposing her daughter to any of her
religious beliefs.
   The case is Mendez vs. Mendez, 87-1166.
   
   CITIES
   
   The court said it will try again to decide whether cities may be
sued successfully when citizens' rights are violated due to alleged
inadequate training of municipal employees.
   The justices said they will study the issue in an appeal by
Canton, Ohio officials.
   The case is Canton vs. Harris, 86-1088.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880307-0081 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-07-88 1256EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-UnionsProtest     03-07 0199</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Unions Protest,0206</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Union Construction Workers Protest Builders Association Convention</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of this city's influential
construction unions threw rocks and eggs and shouted pro-union
slogans today outside the annual convention of the Associated
Builders and Contractors, officials said.
   Police in helmets were called in to keep traffic flowing outside
Moscone Center, where about 2,000 demonstrators from the building
trade councils of three San Francisco Bay area counties stood
five-deep blocking buses carrying convention guests and their
families, officers reported.
   The association will seek a court injunction against the
demonstrators, said Terry Maenza, spokesman for the association.
   ``We have met this morning with unruly and irresponsible
behavior that has jeopardized the safety of our members and their
families,'' said Mike Perkins, national president of Associated
Builders and Contractors.
   The association is a fast-growing organization of 19,000
employers who hire mostly non-union workers.
   Although 2,000 association members were expected at the meeting,
only 400 had arrived when it opened.
   Union members claim the contractors' organization is seeking to
break union control of construction projects.
   About 10,000 workers are employed on construction sites
throughout the city, said Tom Thompson, director of one of the
union contractor's associations.
</TEXT>
