<2ND_LINE>PM-Mecham, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0580,0803</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Immunity For Key Witness At Issue</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to add Milstead testimony; picks up 4th
graf pvs: On Friday ...; DELETES outdated 11th graf pvs: Department
of ...; retransmits a0628 to fix category code to a</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto covering</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURIE ASSEO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Arizona's top police officer testified
today at Gov. Evan Mecham's impeachment trial that he was
``surprised and shocked'' when the governor told him not to
cooperate in an investigation of an alleged death threat.
   Department of Public Safety Director Ralph Milstead told the
Senate today that Mecham told him last Nov. 15 the alleged threat
``was a family spat.''
   Impeachment charges against the 63-year-old Mecham, first-term
Republican, included a charge that he tried to thwart an
investigation of the alleged threat.
   Milstead quoted Mecham as saying, ``The attorney general is out
to hang me and I'm not going to help him in any way ... Don't tell
the attorney general anything.''
   ``He said, `Never, don't give them any help,''' Milstead said.
``This whole situation surprised and shocked me... I just cannot
cover up, even if the governor is the one telling me to do that.''
   The Senate decided earlier this morning not to grant immunity to
the man accused of making the threat, former state official Lee
Watkins.
   Attorney General Bob Corbin told lawmakers that granting
immunity to Watkins, former head of state prison construction,
could wind up protecting him from prosecution for alleged crimes
``you have no way of knowing about today.''
   Senators were considering whether to grant ``use immunity'' to
Watkins to force him to say whether he threatened the life of Donna
Carlson last November, which would have meant his testimony could
not be used against him in criminal court.
   On Friday, Watkins invoked the Fifth Amendment right against
self-incrimination in refusing to testify before the Senate.
Watkins said today that if the state grand jury probe were over he
would have no problem with testifying.
   ``These are the people (the attorney general's office) that are
out to get the governor,'' Watkins said. ``Anybody that gets in the
middle is going to get hurt.''
   Shortly after the Senate's voice vote, Watkins admitted he
hadn't expected to get immunity.
   A grant of immunity should be made only if the testimony sought
is central to the case, if lawmakers think Watkins will tell the
truth and if the immunity will not compromise a criminal
investigation, Corbin said.
   A state grand jury investigation of Watkins is continuing,
Corbin said.
   Mecham's defense lawyer, Jerris Leonard, accused prosecutors of
trying to harm Watkins' reputation in testimony last week and of
``splattering the mud broadly enough so that it splatters on the
respondent (Mecham).''
   Department of Public Safety Director Ralph Milstead also was
scheduled to take the stand today. Mecham is accused of ordering
Milstead not to cooperate with Corbin's investigation of the
alleged threat.
   Mecham was impeached Nov. 5 by the House, which also accused him
of concealing a $350,000 campaign loan and misusing $80,000 from
the governor's protocol fund by loaning it to his auto dealership.
   Watkins has been investigated by the state grand jury in
connection with the alleged threat but has not been charged.
Attorneys said last week the inquiry was continuing.
   Last Friday, Peggy Griffith, head of the Governor's Office of
Women's Services, testified that Watkins told her Nov. 12 that Ms.
Carlson, a former special gubernatorial assistant who was about to
testify before the grand jury on the $350,000 loan, was a ``bad
girl.'' She told the trial that if Ms. Carlson kept talking ``she
is going to take a long boat ride.''
   Watkins has denied making a threat, and prosecutor William
French asked him Friday if he had taken six lie-dectector tests in
an effort to prove he hadn't made the threat. Watkins refused to
answer the question.
   Mrs. Griffith also testified that when she described the alleged
threat to Max Hawkins, then Watkins' boss, he shrugged it off as
``just a bunch of hot air.''
   Mecham, in testimony before a House impeachment committee in
January, acknowledged that he may have told Milstead not to
cooperate with the attorney general's probe. However, Mecham also
contended he was not fully informed about the seriousness of the
situation before his conversation with Milstead.
   Mecham, the first U.S. governor to face an impeachment trial in
six decades, did not attend the first five days of testimony last
week.
   A two-thirds vote of the 30-member Senate is required to convict
Mecham and remove him from office. Mecham also faces a May 17
recall election and a March 22 criminal trial in connection with
the $350,000 campaign loan.
</TEXT>
