<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PanamaCanal 1stLd-Writethru a0481 03-07 0499</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Panama Canal, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0481,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede NEW YORK</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 4 grafs new with Fitzwater statement; picks up 2nd graf
pvs, Any user.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration said today it has
protested poor maintenance of some Panama Canal facilities, but
said the problem was not linked to the recent political turmoil
there.
   ``There are some facilities that are maintained by Panama that
we have protested in a sense of not being adequately maintained,''
said White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater.
   He said the complaint was registered ``sometime previously'' and
was not intended to justify an abrogation of the Panama Canal
treaty.
   Meanwhile, a newspaper reported that political appointees
installed by the Panamanian government are mismanaging operations
of the canal that have been turned over by the United States.
   ``Any user of those facilities will tell you there are
difficulties now that simply did not exist 10 years ago,'' an
unidentified Panamanian economist told The New York Times.
   Among the facilities suffering from mismanagement are ports,
marine bunkering installations, a railroad, a bridge and air
traffic control, according to the Times, which interviewed canal
employees and shipping experts.
   ``This government has put a political aspect to an equation that
has no room for politics,'' said a Panamanian engineer who has
worked at the canal for more than a decade. ``As soon as you start
to mix Panamanian politics with the running of the canal, that is
the end of things.''
   The country's political situation has been particularly troubled
in recent weeks. Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega, the military leader
who is Panama's de facto leader, engineered the ouster of President
Eric Arturo Delvalle after Delvalle tried to fire him.
   The United States still recognizes Delvalle, who is in hiding,
as Panama's rightful president and has brought economic pressure to
bear to oust Noriega. Noriega is also under indictment in the
United States for alleged drug trafficking.
   Panama is scheduled to take control of the waterway in the year
2000, according to the 1977 treaties. But some of the 7,000 canal
employees, 83 percent of whom are Panamanians, fear that domestic
political interference could hinder their ability to run the canal
professionally, the Times said.
   ``As the year 2000 approaches, it is going to be necessary for
laws to keep this organization a bit apart from the normal
government structure, so there is no interference by other
ministries or the implantation of political but unskilled people in
the upper echelons,'' said Dennis P. McAuliffe, an American and
chief administrator of the canal.
   A Panamanian civil engineer told the newspaper that derailments
on the railroad have increased because of lack of maintenance and
that rail yards ``are in a state of disrepair.''
   Shipping lines complain that lights and gangways don't work and
that fenders along docks are not maintained.
   The Panama Defense Forces have taken some of the best office
buildings for their own use as warehouses or as prisons, the Times
reported, forcing some canal operations to move elsewhere.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
