<1ST_LINE>u w PM-Reagan 2ndLd-Writethru a0592 03-07 0691</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0592,680</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 3 grafs new material for 5th graf pvs, After the</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan lashed out today at
congressional opponents to Contra aid, accusing them of a lack of
courage in the battle against communism in Central America.
   In a speech to the Veterans of Foreign Wars convention, Reagan
talked about the votes last week in Congress that left the rebels
battling the leftist government of Nicragua without U.S. funding.
   The 216-208 vote defeated a Democratic plan to provide $30.8
million in food, clothing and medical aid to the rebels. The vote
was scheduled by the Democratic leadership so the House could not
vote on an aid plan favored by the Republicans.
   ``Courage hasn't exactly been the watchword of some opponents of
Contra aid,'' Reagan said. ``... Last week, aid opponents tried to
pass the buck of responsibility for abandoning in the field the
young men and women of the Democratic resistance, and that ploy
failed as it should have.''
   Administration officials have expressed the hope Congress could
come up with an alternative plan to keep the rebels alive as a
fighting force.
   After Reagan's speech, White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater
acknowledged that a ``real problem'' exists for the administration
because a new Contra aid package might not be considered for some
time.
   ``It's just a matter of time,'' he said. ``We will produce a
package,'' he vowed at another point.
   In his speech, Reagan recalled that Nicaraguan President Daniel
Ortega dismissed Cardinal Obando y Bravo as the mediator in peace
talks with the rebels.
   ``You know where Ortega stands. Isn't it time for Congress to
have the courage to show where it stands?'' Reagan asked
rhetorically.
   ``Now it's time for Congress to show that it knows you can't
have real peace negotiations when one side has helicopter gunships
and the other has bandages,'' he said.
   Reagan said the defeat of the Contras would mean a ``grave
strategic defeat for the United States.''
   ``The communists in Central America understand this, the Soviets
understand this _ it's time that Congress understood it, too,''
Reagan said, adding, ``A Soviet base on the American mainland is a
pistol pointed at the heart of the Americas.''
   Reagan contended that the ``real issue'' before the Congress is
not the Contras, ``it is communisim in Central America.''
   The president, who was warmly greeted by the audience of older
veterans, told them of his recent trip to Brussels, Belgium, where
he met with NATO leaders. He asked their support for the
ratification of the recently signed U.S.-Soviet treaty banning
medium-range nuclear missles from Europe.
   Reagan also called on Congress to reject further cuts in the
nation's defense budget and allow for a strong alliance defense.
   ``This is not the time to drop our guard,'' Reagan said. ``It's
just this simple. If we put Americans in harm's way, we owe them
the best weapons money can buy.''
   ``We'll need to keep up our strength if we're to succeed, and
that's why the Congress must not further reduce the defense
budget,'' Reagan said.
   Offering a report on the Brussels meeting in his Saturday radio
address, Reagan declared that ``arms reduction is not enough'' in
dealing with the Soviets and demanded they abandon the ``offensive
strategy'' displayed against the Western alliance on the European
continent.
   Reagan said there was a ``lesson learned'' at the meeting, which
was the first full-scale summit for the leaders of the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization in six years.
   ``One must always negotiate with the Soviets from a position of
strength,'' Reagan said.
   Following the NATO summit, a White House advance team traveled
to Moscow to scout out possible sites for the fourth meeting
between Reagan and Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev, planned for
late May or early June.
   In his radio speech, Reagan pointed out that while the allies
praised the new U.S.-Soviet agreement to remove all medium-range
nuclear missiles from Europe, they reaffirmed the need to remain
united and keep their guard up.
   ``That's why continued modernization of NATO forces _ nuclear
and conventional _ is essential,'' Reagan said.
</TEXT>
