<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ReligiousSchools-Lawsuit     03-07 0611</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Religious Schools-Lawsuit,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Seeking Dismissal Of Suit To Bar Federal Aid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. government is seeking the dismissal
of a lawsuit that would end federal aid to religious schools
abroad, primarily Jewish schools in Israel, a prosecutor said
Monday.
   Bernard Bell, an assistant U.S. attorney in New York's Southern
District, said he filed papers in federal court Friday arguing that
the case ought to be dropped because the American Civil Liberties
Union does not have ``standing,'' a legal term which means the
right to bring the lawsuit.
   But C. Edwin Baker, a staff attorney the ACLU in New York, said
the civil liberties group maintains that it can pursue the lawsuit
because the ACLU represents American taxpayers whose money is used
for the schools. The ACLU has until March 24 to respond.
   The lawsuit stemmed from reports last December that Sen. Daniel
K. Inouye, D-Hawaii, had persuaded his colleagues to allocate $8
million to build schools in France for North African Jews.
   The program provoked a firestorm of criticism, prompting Inouye
to ask Congress to rescind the money. Lawmakers agreed to Inouye's
wish.
   After President Reagan signed the bill killing the $8 million
program last month, the ACLU amended its complaint to cover Jewish
and Catholic schools that receive money under the American Schools
and Hospitals Abroad program, which is administered by the Agency
for International Development.
   Baker said lawyers learned about the program in the course of
their research into the Inouye-supported item.
   The lawsuit, filed in U.S. District Court in New York, claims
that providing money to ``pervasively sectarian schools'' or for
construction of sectarian schools is a violation of the
Constitution's First Amendment calling for separation of church and
state. The ACLU asks the court to block further spending on the
schools.
   Under the schools and hospitals program _ a favorite in Congress
_ grants are awarded to a non-profit American organization that
sponsors an institution overseas. The program is designed to
promote American educational methods abroad and train foreigners in
medicine and promote American educational values.
   AID, which has regulations governing the program, awards the
grants on a competitive basis. Congress is notified before the
money is spent.
   The budget figures indicate how fond Congress is of the program.
In fiscal year 1988, AID asked for $10 million; Congress increased
the budget to $40 million. The previous fiscal year the program
received $35 million.
   The ACLU is not challenging grants given to hospitals or
non-sectarian schools abroad, Baker said. But the group wants to
end support for schools that have as a stated goal the teaching of
principles and doctrines of Roman Catholicism and orthodox Judaism.
   AID documents for the four years ending in 1986 show that
institutions in Lebanon were given the most money, a total of $24.8
million. The lion's share _ $24 million _ went to the American
University of Beirut.
   Institutions in Israel snagged the second largest amount of
money, a total of $20.2 million. Project HOPE, which operates
schools worldwide, received $14.3 million.
   All of the religious schools named in the lawsuit are in Israel.
   Among the institutions which teach Judaism and have received
money since fiscal 1983 are: The American College of Belz,
Jerusalem, $500,000; Beth Rivka Comprehensive School, Kfar Chabad,
$750,000; Beth Yaacov Avat, Ashdod, $100,000; Boys Town, Jerusalem,
$1.2 million; Emunah Women of America Community College, Jerusalem,
$650,000; Gan Yavne Youth Village, Gan Yavne, $150,000; Machaniam
High School, Kiryat Gat, $400,000; Ohr Somayach School, Jerusalem,
$2 million' Sha'Alvim Teachers' College, D.N. Agalon, $400,000.
   The lawsuit does not name any Catholic schools for which it
wants to eliminate money.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
