<1ST_LINE>r w PM-US-ChinaRockets 2ndLd-Writethru a0570 03-07 0684</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-China Rockets, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0570,680</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: New material, editing throughout with administration
expressing concern about violence in Tibet.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration expressed deep
concern today about violence in Tibet as Chinese Foreign Minister
Wu Xueqian opened talks with Secretary of State George P. Shultz.
   ``We remain deeply concerned about the state of human rights in
Tibet and the recurring incidents of violence,'' said Charles E.
Redman, the State Department spokesman. ``We urge all concerned to
exercise restraint in order to avoid further bloodshed.''
   At the same time, Redman said Tibet is considered an integral
part of China. ``Nothing has changed on that,'' he said.
   Redman said he expected Shultz would take up the situation with
Wu during their talks.
   The State Department and Congress have accused China of harsh
measures in putting down unrest in Tibet.
   Reports that reached Beijing on Sunday said thousands of rioting
Tibetans had set bonfires in Lhasa's streets and several people
were killed during more than 12 hours of clashes with police. The
protesters were demanding Tibet's independence from China.
   Police fired bullets and tear gas at protesters Saturday and
three to nine people were killed, according to the unconfirmed
reports from Western sources in Lhasa.
   The administration, meanwhile, is dangling high-technology sales
as an inducement for China to give firm assurances it will halt
delivery of Silkworm missiles to Iran.
   The tradeoff _ and at least Chinese neutrality in a U.S. drive
to impose an international arms embargo against Iran _ looms as the
potential highlight of the talks Wu opened today.
   It is his first visit in four years, and the agenda is
substantial. For instance, Shultz will solicit China's support for
his proposal for Arab-Israeli peace talks.
   Shultz is trying to structure a peace conference in which the
United States, the Soviet Union, China, Britain and France would
serve as sponsors, but without the power to impose terms of a
settlement.
   That calls for some delicate diplomacy. Shultz is walking a
tightrope between Jordan and Israel on the subject.
   King Hussein refuses to negotiate unless he has Big Power
support. But Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir refuses to allow
China or the Soviets, who usually support Arab positions, to take
an active role.
   Wu arrived Sunday, had dinner with Shultz and sees him and
Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci separately today. On Tuesday,
the Chinese foreign minister calls on President Reagan at the White
House and meets with Shultz again.
   The shipping war in the Persian Gulf is uppermost in U.S. minds.
   China may be Iran's largest arms supplier. Sales last year were
worth an estimated $1 billion.
   The most dangerous of the weapons are Silkworm missiles _
short-range rockets that even in unskilled hands can wreak havoc on
merchant ships. Iran has used them effectively.
   Despite U.S. appeals, China persisted in delivering installments
of the Silkworms to Iran last year _ and denied what Carlucci and
other U.S. officials said it was doing.
   Frustrated, the United States retaliated in October by
suspending a decade-old process of liberalizing the types of high
technology American companies could sell to China.
   Since then, China has said it has stopped selling Silkworms to
Iran. A U.S. official, speaking Friday on condition of anonymity,
said ``our information is that they've been living up to that.''
   Still, before resuming liberalization of the high-technology
trade, ``we want to be sure we're in sync with the Chinese on what
we're talking about,'' the official said. ``We want to be sure that
this responsiveness will continue.''
   On an arms embargo, meanwhile, Shultz would like a commitment
from Wu that China would not veto a resolution in the U.N. Security
Council to impose a worldwide arms embargo against Iran.
   The sanctions would enforce a cease-fire resolution adopted last
July that Iraq accepted but Iran scorned.
   State Department experts believe China would at least remain
neutral if the Soviet Union agreed not to veto the resolution. The
United States has been after Moscow since July for support, but is
not sure it has it yet.
</TEXT>
