<1ST_LINE>r w PM-US-Panama 1stLd-Writethru a0527 03-07 0406</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Panama, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0527,380</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: New material, editing thruout</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration is considering
economic and trade sanctions against Panama, including withholding
monthly payments for the Panama Canal, but has not made any
decisions yet, a White House spokesman said today.
   Spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said meetings will be held later this
week to discuss options on how the United States can apply pressure
to force the ouster of Panama's military strongman, Manuel Antonio
Noriega.
   On March 15, the United States is due to pay $6.5 million to the
Panama Canal Commission, a monthly payment toward the $75 million
to $80 million the United States makes each year under the Panama
Canal treaty.
   One of the options under consideration, Fitzwater said, is to
put the money into an escrow account instead of paying it to Panama.
   Earlier in the day, Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y., said the
United States was right to put economic pressure on Noriega's
government, which D'Amato predicted would fall within 10 days.
   ``We are grinding him down to a halt, and we should,'' D'Amato
said on NBC-TV's ``Today'' show.
   ``I think we could have moved much faster,'' added D'Amato, who
is sponsoring a Senate resolution calling for a total trade embargo
against Panama.
   ``We begin to see the incredible effects that we do have
economically,'' the New York Republican said.
   Panama's 12 local banks have been closed since Tuesday; branches
of international institutions closed their doors Friday.
   The administration last week backed legal efforts to freeze
Panamanian government deposits in U.S. banks, and authorities in
Panama were prevented from drawing on those accounts to keep the
nation supplied with U.S. dollars, the official currency of Panama.
   Calling the Panamanian strongman a terrorist and ``petty
tyrant,'' D'Amato asked:
   ``If we can't take Noriega on with the power that we have in the
area economically, militarily, ... how are we going to deal with
the drug lords of Mexico and Colombia and Bolivia and when are we
really going to take on that war?''
   ``This is an opportunity and time for us to strike a blow for
democracy and to go after one of the drug lords in this
hemisphere,'' he said.
   Questioned as to when he thinks Noriega will be forced from
power, D'Amato replied, ``I would say within 10 days.''
   Appearing with D'Amato, Juan B. Sosa, the ambassador of Panama's
deposed president, Eric Arturo Delvalle, agreed with that
prediction.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
