<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-OccupiedLands     03-07 0602</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Occupied Lands,0618</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Twelve Arabs Wounded, Rioters Hurl Grenades At Soldiers</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli soldiers shot and wounded at least 12
Palestinians on Monday, and the army said Arab rioters hurled a
grenade for the first time since violence began in the occupied
territories three months ago.
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin defended the behavior of soldiers
in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip. He told Parliament it was
the first time in Israel's 40-year history ``in which face-to-face,
close, they see the ... hate of the rioters.''
   Strikes and job boycotts extended to the administration of the
territories. Palestinian employees of the Gaza tax department were
summoned to military headquarters Monday after 38 of the 40 workers
said they were resigning.
   Inside Israel, Palestinian guerrillas captured a commuter bus
near Beersheba and soldiers stormed the vehicle. Three Israelis and
three guerrillas were killed.
   According to the army spokesman's office, soldiers shot and
wounded seven Palestinians at Idna after attackers threw a grenade
at troopers who raided the West Bank village to arrest ``rioters
and inciters of rioting.'' The Arab-run Palestine Press Service put
the number of wounded at eight.
   It was the first use of a grenade since Arab riots began Dec. 8.
   The first army report of Arab gunfire in a demonstration
occurred Sunday in the Askar refugee camp near Nablus. No soldiers
were injured.
   Israeli surveillance and restrictions make it difficult for
Arabs to get firearms, and the Palestine Liberation Organization
has ordered protesters to avoid using guns.
   International sympathy has been created by images of well-armed
soldiers shooting and beating youths armed only with rocks and
homemade gasoline bombs in what Arabs call ``the uprising.''
According to U.N. figures, 83 Palestinians have been killed.
   At Al-Ittihad hospital in Nablus, Dr. Hamdallah Kazlak said two
Palestinians were treated for gunshot wounds suffered in clashes
with troops at the nearby Balata refugee camp.
   He said 20-25 others from Balata and the Askar camp were treated
for injuries caused by clubs, rubber bullets or tear gas, including
a 4-year-old girl hit in the head by a rubber bullet.
   A 33-year-old Arab from Askar, Salah Eddin Abdul-Raouf, was dead
on arrival at the hospital and Kazlak said his relatives attributed
the death to tear gas. He said the cause of death was unclear,
however, and noted the man suffered from heart disease.
   Army officials said they were investigating reports of the
protests.
   Hospital officials in the Gaza Strip said soldiers shot and
wounded three Arabs during protests on the anniversary of Israel's
withdrawal from the strip soon after invading it in 1956. Israel
captured Gaza from Egypt, and the West Bank from Jordan, in the
1967 Middle East war.
   Army spokesmen said soldiers opened fire when rubber bullets and
tear gas did not disperse ``a violent demonstration in the Shati
camp,'' wounding three Palestinians.
   The hospital officials, speaking anonymously, said more than 100
people were treated for beatings and injuries caused by tear gas
and rubber bullets, most suffered at Shati.
   Military authorities summoned employees of the Gaza tax
department to discuss a Sunday letter signed by 38 of the 40
workers saying they were resigning in response to a call by
underground Palestinian leaders.
   A senior official said the Israelis explained the financial
difficulties workers would face if they quit and ``the general
situation in terms of public services that will be damaged.'' He
said the workers had not yet resigned officially.
   Israeli officials claim Arab government workers in the
territories have been threatened by Palestinian nationalists and
Islamic militants.
</TEXT>
