<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SpaceScience     03-07 0577</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Space Science,0588</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NASA Official, Academicians Urge Expansion Of Space-Based Research</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States has been embarassed in space
research since the Challenger disaster, and risks forfeiting its
edge in high technology and other fields unless it expands
space-based scientific missions, a NASA official and researchers
told a congressional hearing Monday.
   Further delays in projects already backed up three years plus a
lack of funding for new space experiments will allow the Soviet
Union, Japan and European nations to cement the lead they have
taken over the United States since the Challenger explosion, said
Lennard A. Fisk, associate administrator of the National
Aeronautics and Space Administration.
   ``A lead that we had was allowed to erode and now we have to ask
ourselves where we are going,'' said Fisk, who outlined the
science-related portion of NASA's proposed fiscal 1989 budget to
the Senate Subcommittee on Science, Technology and Space.
   Fisk said 20 major science-related payloads are scheduled to be
carried into space in the next four years, half of them aboard
space shuttles and half on expendable rockets.
   The projects include probes to Venus and Jupiter and the
launching of an X-ray telescope, space telescope and gamma ray
observatory designed to work in tandem to study a number of
phenomena, including a supernova that occurred last year.
   The new X-ray telescope, the Advanced X-Ray Astrophysics
Facility, should also help researchers determine what the universe
looked like up to 20 billion years ago and produce dramatic
improvements in pharmaceuticals and computer chips, said Dr. Harvey
Tananbaum of the Harvard-Smithsonian Center for Astrophysics.
   Resumption of the shuttle program and approval of NASA's
science-related budget is vital to getting the 20 projects launched
by 1993 and to prove to commercial businesses which pay to have
satellites and experiments carried into space that the Unites
States will re-establish itself as a dominant force in space, Fisk
said.
   He also urged researchers to develop new space-based experiments
and technology so that NASA can begin planning missions past 1993,
when it is scheduled to complete current projects.
   ``We have a hiatus in space science launches today because of
the Challenger tragedy,'' Fisk said. ``Let us not create another
hiatus in the mid-1990s by failing to start major flight projects
now.''
   Sen. John Kerry, D-Mass., a subcommittee member who presided
over the hearing, said a revitalized space program also was vital
to Massachusetts businesses and universities, which received 846
contracts totaling $413 million in 1987 and have to date in 1988
been awarded 710 contracts totaling $388 million.
   Fisk and the academicians told the subcommittee that NASA should
not be pressured to curtail manned missions with civilian
researchers because of the January 1986 Challenger explosion that
killed seven astronauts, including New Hampshire teacher Christa
McAuliffe.
   David L. Akin, associate director of the Massachusetts Institute
of Technology Space Systems Laboratory, said that while computers
and robots can greatly contribute to space research, their
advancement should not be used to support calls for an end to
manned space flights.
   ``Exploration is one of the last jobs which should be turned
over to robots, as the curiosity for thirst and knowledge
underlying the urge to explore is one of the finest attributes of
being human,'' Akin said. ``Let us instead spend our efforts
getting humans out of mine shafts and off high steel construction
sites. Robots should totally replace man in the worst of jobs, not
the best.''
</TEXT>
