<FILEID>AP-NR-03-07-88 1446EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Tibet     03-07 0378</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tibet,0388</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dalai Lama Holds Special Prayer Service for Tibet</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Dalai Lama, god-king of Tibetans,
held a prayer service Monday in northern India to mourn weekend
violence in Lhasa, capital of Tibet.
   In New Delhi, hundreds of Tibetan refugees chanted ``We shall
overcome'' in a demonstration solidarity with people in Tibet.
Police prevented the crowd from marching on the Chinese Embassy.
   A statement from the Dalai Lama's New Delhi office said the
trouble in Lhasa ``is yet another indication of the depth of
Tibetan people's resentment and opposition to Chinese rule.''
   Hundreds of Tibetans attended the service in Dharmsala, the
Dalai Lama's exile headquarters in northern Himachal Pradesh state,
the statement said. It declared that the Tibetan issue ``cannot be
solved by use of force'' and called on China ``to seriously
negotiate for a solution.''
   In a statement from Dharmsala, the Dalai Lama urged the Chinese
to ``work toward a settlement which will benefit both the Tibetan
and the Chinese peoples.'' He asked that Tibetans ``in the meantime
... refrain from violence in spite of repressive measures that the
Chinese may take.''
   Official reports in China said one policeman was killed and 28
were injured in the Lhasa clash Saturday. Unconfirmed reports from
Western sources put the toll at three to nine dead, including a
Buddhist monk and two Chinese policemen.
   The Dalai Lama fled to India with about 100,000 of his followers
in 1959, after an abortive Tibetan uprising. China, which claims
Tibet has been an integral part of it for centuries, moved troops
into the remote mountain region in 1950.
   Saturday's violence was the first in Lhasa since Oct. 1, when
2,000 Tibetans led by Buddhist monks set fire to a police station
facing the Jokhang Temple. Police opened fire and at least 14
people were reported killed.
   Many Tibetans resent the government in Beijing because of
oppression of Tibetan religion and customs and destruction of
temples during the 1966-76 radical Cultural Revolution.
   Although China has tried to redress past wrongs, friction
remains between Tibetans and Chinese who continue to hold many
senior posts in Lhasa.
   The Tibetan government has refused nearly all requests by
foreign journalists to visit Lhasa and has restricted tourism since
the disturbances last October.
</TEXT>
