<FILEID>AP-NR-03-07-88 1448EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Hospital-Hostages     03-07 0616</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hospital-Hostages,0638</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prisoner Gives Up After Threatening Explosion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAYNER PIKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A prisoner handcuffed to a hospital bed broke
the bed rail Monday and overpowered his police guard, then took the
officer's gun and held two people hostage before giving up about
six hours later.
   The prisoner freed the hostages, both hospital engineers, but
continued to hold police off while threatening to shoot himself or
fire into potentially explosive tanks of acetylene and oxygen in a
subbasement of North General Hospital in Harlem.
   ``He was rational but very upset,'' said Detective Frank
Gallagher, the chief negotiator. ``He had fits of depression and at
one point put the gun to his head and at another point to his
mouth.''
   The prisoner, identified as Yusuf Harris, 27, freed himself
around 4:25 a.m. in his seventh-floor room at the hospital, where
he had been taken for treatment of exposure after being arrested on
kidnap charges early Saturday, officials said.
   Authorities were investigating how he broke his bed rail without
alerting the guard, officer Timothy Austin, in a hallway outside,
said Chief of Patrol John P. McCabe said.
   After getting Austin's gun, the barefoot Harris, wearing only a
hospital gown and dragging a wedge-shaped section of aluminum-pipe
bed rail from his wrist, made his way to the second floor, where he
got the drop on a security guard, according to patients who saw the
incident.
   Harris allegedly took the guard's wallet, with $7, then forced
him to break open a window leading onto a setback.
   Around this time Harris fired Austin's .38-caliber service
revolver, Chief Robert Johnston said, but it was not known whether
the discharge was accidental or Harris had tried to hit someone. No
one was shot.
   Harris made his way to the subbasement, where he burned his
buttocks while clambering over a boiler, said Johnston.
   He took his hostages, Ray Cadmus, 50, of Nesconset, and Kemail
Bajramoski, 35, of Manhattan, at the engineers' office, said
police. One of the captives freed Harris from the bed rail by
chiseling the handcuff chain.
   Cadmus was freed at 7:20 a.m. after police sent in some coffee
and doughnuts, said Johnston. Bajramoski was let go about an hour
later when Gallagher agreed to stay with Harris in place of the
hostage.
   ``He said he wanted to blow himself up but he didn't want to go
alone,'' said Gallagher.
   Later, the officer saw the prisoner turn the gun on himself.
   ``He said to me, `You want to see me do it? I'll do it right
now,''' Gallagher related.
   Gallagher quoted Harris as saying he had tried to escape because
he feared going back into the criminal justice system.
   The prisoner was calmed by talking on the telephone to his
father and sister and to an assistant district attorney, Steven
Nuzzi, who were brought to the hospital.
   Finally, he threw the gun out ``and walked out and took my
hand,'' said Gallagher.
   Still barefoot, but with a red plaid shirt and a sheet over his
gown, Harris was brought out at 10:45 a.m.
   McCabe said he would be charged with robbery, reckless
endangerment and weapon possession.
   Austin, 28, who was treated for cuts and bruises, had arrested
Harris originally early Saturday after Harris allegedly used a
starter's pistol to force a cabbie to drive him from the Bronx to
Manhattan.
   Harris fled the cab and jumped into the East River when the
driver got the attention of police in eastern Harlem, authorities
said. Harbor police fished him out and Austin arrested him on
charges of kidnap, menacing and gun and marijuana possession,
police said.
   He had been taken to the hospital for treatment and observation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
