<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Canada-Palestinian     03-07 0416</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Canada-Palestinian,0429</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Convicted Palestinian Terrorists Loses Bid to Halt Deportation
Proceedings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BRADLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Palestinian convicted in a terrorist attack on
an Israeli jetliner lost out Monday in his bid to block the
Canadian government's attempt to deport him.
   Federal court Justice James Jerome dismissed an application from
Mahmoud Mohammad Issa's lawyers, who argued that the scheduled
March 15 deportation hearing would violate Canada's Charter of
Rights and Freedoms.
   The attorneys said that Mohammad, 45, will not get a fair
hearing because Immigration Minister Benoit Bouchard has already
told Parliament that ``the government will not rest before he
(Mohammad) is out of the country.''
   The judge said Bouchard's comments could have been more
temperate. But he said the process ``also involves a sense of
fairness to Canada'' and is necessary to assess ``who should come
in and who should not.''
   Lorne Waldman, one of Mohammad's lawyers, said he was filing an
immediate appeal of the decision and a request for a stay in
deportation proceedings until the appeal is heard.
   In 1970, a Greek court convicted Mohammad of manslaughter for
his part in a 1968 attack on an El Al airliner at Athens airport
that left one Israeli passenger dead. He served three months of his
17-year sentence and was released in a hostage exchange.
   He came to Canada with his wife and three children a year ago
and established a comfortable suburban life in Brantford, Ontario.
   When reporters discovered his presence in the country in
January, Mohammad acknowledged having lied about his criminal
record to gain entry to Canada. But he said he renounced terrorism
and avowed to live here peacefully.
   Some left-wing groups and newspaper columnists have been
sympathetic to his case.
   However, his claim to have renounced Palestinian terrorism long
ago has been challenged by the Israeli Airline Pilots Association,
which claims Mohammad was involved in a 1986 plot to attack a
Jewish settlement in Morocco.
   In addition, the Montreal newspaper, Le Devoir, has reported the
existence of an autobiographical book about Mohammad which depicts
him as an active terrorist in 1975.
   Mohammad has denied both allegations.
   Mohammad tried to leave Canada quietly last month through a
secret Royal Canadian Mounted Police operation. The plan called for
him to fly to London's Heathrow Airport and change planes for
Algiers, possibly continuing on to Morocco.
   Authorities have not clarified exactly what went wrong. Mohammad
flew to London but was put on a plane back to Toronto.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
