<FILEID>AP-NR-03-07-88 1458EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BibleSpeaks     03-07 0502</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bible Speaks,0516</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chain Store Heiress Wins Church Estate She Forced Into Bankruptcy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN LUMSDEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WORCESTER, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An heiress who was awarded $6 million
from a church she said exploited her won The Bible Speaks' 65-acre
headquarters Monday with a $3.23 million bid at an auction in U.S.
Bankruptcy Court.
   It was the second time that Elizabeth Dovydenas, 35, of Lenox,
had outbid others for the church's now-abandoned property, which
includes 23 buildings. Judge James F. Queenan Jr. had rejected her
November bid of $1.8 million as too low.
   ``I'd be happy either way,'' said Mrs. Dovydenas' husband,
Jonas, after learning the couple's bid was the highest of the four
sealed bids at the court hearing.
   The money Mrs. Dovydenas bid for the estate will go toward
repaying the $6.6 million claim she won in federal Bankruptcy Court
last April against The Bible Speaks.
   She had sued the church for donations she made as a parishioner
from 1982 to 1986, contending that she was lied to and that her
unquestioning trust was exploited by church founder and leader Rev.
Carl H. Stevens Jr.
   Queenan agreed in his ruling, calling the case ``an astonishing
saga of clerical deceit, avarice and subjugation on the part of the
church's founder.''
   The ruling was upheld in January in U.S. District Court in
Springfield, but the church's lawyers have announced they intend to
file an appeal.
   The dispute landed in federal Bankrupcy Court after the church
obtained Chapter 11 protection, arguing that Mrs. Dovydenas' case
could forced it into insolvency.
   The claim by Mrs. Dovydenas, an heir to the Dayton Hudson
department store fortune, is by far the largest of the 250
creditors who are owed a total of $7 million by the church.
   Her lawyer, Gordon Walker, said he doubted she will ever receive
all the money she won, although another piece of church property in
Maine recently sold for $1.1 million and a Florida condominium and
a mission ship are also up for sale by a court-appointed trustee.
   ``I hope we even get $4 million,'' the attorney said. ``The
question is, where did all that money go? We're going to look into
that question.''
   The Bible Speaks had claimed 1,200 members worldwide until the
ministry disbanded last summer, saying it would never operate under
the control of a court-appointed trustee. The trustee, David
Ferrari, had been apppointed by the bankrutpcy court to manage the
estate until Mrs. Dovydenas' claim could be paid.
   Most of the church's 20 pastors followed Stevens to Baltimore,
although a few remained behind to set up another church in Lenox.
   The church's Lenox estate had been valued at $6 million, but
investors said town zoning restrictions made it difficult to
develop the land.
   Dovydenas said Monday he and his wife planned to sell some of
the church property to developers and turn some of it into a school
and a community center for the wealthy town, the summer home of the
Boston Symphony Orchestra.
</TEXT>
