<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Gallaudet-Zinser     03-07 0377</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gallaudet-Zinser,0387</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Deaf School President Says She'll Work To Build Confidence</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Deaf School-President</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GREENSBORO, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The new president of Gallaudet
University said Monday she empathizes with students and faculty at
the all-deaf university who are protesting her appointment because
she hears.
   ``I do feel very deeply a sense of compassion and empathy,''
Elizabeth Zinser said Monday in a telephone interview. ``I know
it's hurting them because they very much wanted their seventh
president to be deaf.
   ``But I think that what the students are expressing in general
is their deep concern and care for the university. I hope that they
and I ... as soon things quiet down can begin to focus on the work
of Gallaudet University.''
   Hundreds of students shut down Gallaudet, the nation's only
university for the deaf, out of anger Monday over the selection of
a president who is not hearing-impaired.
   Zinser said she would probably begin her new job this summer.
Meanwhile, she will begin an intensive program to learn sign
language and hopes to volunteer with agencies that work with the
deaf, she said.
   Zinser, vice chancellor of Academic Affairs at the University of
North Carolina at Greensboro since 1983, was named Gallaudet
president Sunday by the school's Board of Trustees.
   Zinser said she was concerned about the student protests but not
about what impact it might have on her presidency.
   ``I think it would be inhuman on my part not to be concerned,''
she said. ``But my concern is for the pain that I know some
individuals are feeling. I do, however, believe that the board has
made its decision.''
   ``The university belongs to a large and varied constitutency of
which the president is a symbol,'' she said. ``I am not, perhaps to
some, the best symbol.
   ``I know that I cannot fully understand the experience of
deafness without being deaf. ... But I will become as knowledgable
and as understanding and as empathetic as anyone can who's a
hearing person.''
   Zinser holds a doctorate in educational psychology from the
University of California at Berkeley. Before coming to North
Carolina in 1983, she was a professor, dean of the school of
nursing and senior academic officer at the University of North
Dakota at Grand Forks.
</TEXT>
