<FILEID>AP-NR-03-07-88 1528EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CitiesConference     03-07 0468</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cities Conference,0482</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>International Conference Focuses On Making Cities More Liveable</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of experts from around the
globe gather in antebellum Charleston this week to seek ways to
make the world's cities better places to live.
   The 4th International Conference on Making Cities Liveable,
which opens Wednesday, is being held in the United States for the
first time.
   ``The quality of life in our cities has become increasingly a
national concern,'' Mayor Joseph P. Riley Jr. said Monday.
   Riley said Charleston boasts many ``important national, if not
international, examples of the liveability of cities,'' from its
preservation efforts to its innovative programs of low-income
housing to the acclaimed Spoleto arts festival.
   ``But we have so much to learn,'' he said.
   ``It's a conference for people who are concerned about the
quality of life in the city'' but isn't a professional conference,
said Suzanne Lennard, one of the organizers and a founder of the
Center for Urban Well-Being.
   ``It brings together many different kinds of people. It brings
together city planners and architects, city council presidents and
mayors and citizens who are simply concerned about making their
cities more liveable,'' she said.
   More than 300 people are expected to attend and more than 100
people are scheduled to speak. Among the topics of discussion will
be the design of public spaces, festivals, the role of markets in
the city and a number of case studies.
   The Center for Urban Well-Being, based in Southhampton, N.Y., is
a partnership that conducts research, publishes and works with
cities on urban issues.
   The first three international conferences were held in Venice.
``We wanted to bring it to America to make it more accessible for
Americans,'' Mrs. Lennard said.
   One of the topics of discussion will be public art _ sculptures
and other art in public places such as parks.
   Sculptor Bonifatius Stirnberg, who has crafted numerous,
whimsical, human-sized sculptures for parks and fountains
throughout Europe, will talk about his craft.
   Usually crafted of bronze, his works are often designed for a
particular town and tell something about its history or folklore.
They include a sculpture of carnival characters on a barge that's
part of a fountain and a long bronze sea serpent whose tail serves
as a park bench.
   Stirnberg, of Aachen, West Germany, said through an interpreter,
``The goal of my work is to make sculpture that is loved by the
people _ that people can move and touch.''
   In contrast, Riley said, ``in America we see so much public art
that is not of a human scale.''
   Riley said ``the power of a meeting like this is in the
learning, teaching and sharing. It has the potential of improving
the quality of life in cities all over America and beyond.''
</TEXT>
