<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TrainAccident     03-07 0239</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Train Accident,0245</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teen-age Girl Mimicks Movie, is Struck and Killed by Train</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 15-year-old girl who was acting out a
scene from the movie ``Stand By Me'' was struck and killed when she
misjudged the speed of an oncoming train and stepped into its path,
authorities said Monday.
   The accident Sunday in suburban Fairport occurred behind the
American National Can Co., said Fairport Police Chief Joseph D.
Picciotti.
   Kimberly Anne Strassner and three friends were singing the
movie's title song and recreating the scenes in which four boys
artfully dodge trains, Picciotti said.
   ``They actually heard the engineer (whistle) and felt the rumble
of the track,'' said Picciotti, who interviewed one of the friends
Monday. ``The victim for some unknown reason challenged the train
and lost.''
   The 105-car Conrail train was heading east when the conductor
spotted the youths and blew a caution whistle, Monroe County
sheriff's deputies said.
   Miss Strassner and her girlfriend were standing between two sets
of tracks as the train approached. At the last moment, she leaped
into the train's path and was struck and thrown 50 feet, Picciotti
said.
   Miss Strassner's mother, Patricia Sampson, said ``Stand By Me''
was her daughter's favorite movie.
   ``She watched it over and over again. And she had a crush on the
actor. She bought the video and she went to any friend who had a
VCR and watched it,'' her mother said.
</TEXT>
