<1ST_LINE>u p AM-BushSweep Bjt   03-07 0655</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush Sweep, Bjt,670</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Looks for Southern Sweep, Possible Dole Defeat in Illinois</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush, anticipating a
Super Tuesday windfall of Republican convention delegates, is
targeting Illinois, the biggest state in Bob Dole's Midwest base,
as the battleground that could end the Kansas senator's hope of a
comeback in the GOP race.
   ``I don't know what Dole does if he doesn't win Illinois,'' said
Bush campaign manager Lee Atwater.
   ``I can't wait to hear their new theory if they lose Illinois,''
he said. ``Everyone comes up with a theory on how they can still
win it.''
   A Dole campaign source agreed the Kansas senator must win
Illinois and said they would spend about $500,000 on television
advertising, their largest budget for any state.
   Rich Bond, Bush's deputy campaign manager, refused to cite a
specific figure for the campaign's advertising budget but said they
would spent ``whatever it takes.''
   Traveling with Bush in Missouri on Monday, Atwater said he
expected the vice president to win 12 or 13 of the 17 GOP events on
Tuesday.
   Asked he was hoping for a clean sweep, Bush said, ``You always
wish for that, but I certainly would never predict that. It's too
much for anyone to expect.''
   While Bush aides speculate about a possible Super Tuesday sweep
that could net the vice president up to 600 GOP convention
delegates, the Dole camp talks about surviving the South and
getting back to the Midwest, where the Kansas senator has whipped
Bush in Iowa, Minnesota and South Dakota.
   ``Dole is undefeated in the Midwest and Illinois is in the
Midwest,'' said Dole campaign aide Larry McCarthy.
   ``The key is how well we do in the Midwestern tier of states,
starting with Illinois,'' said Richard Wirthlin, Dole's pollster.
   But Bond disputed the Dole homeground advantage in Illinois.
   ``The votes aren't in Bob Dole's backyard,'' he said. ``The
votes are in Chicago and the collar counties (the Chicago suburbs)
and it's hardly a typical farm state.''
   With 82 GOP delegates at stake, the Illinois primary is March
15, one week after Super Tuesday.
   Dole has already started his television campaign in Illinois
with a biographical ad that emphasizes his humble upbringing, war
service, and leadership role in Congress.
   ``Dole turned Ronald Reagan's vision into an action plan for
America,'' said the ad, which concluded with the narrator saying,
``Bob Dole is a strong man _ with a record of solving tough
problems.''
   Dole has a strong organization in the state, headed by Illinois
House minority leader Lee Daniels and augmented by former Gov.
Richard Ogilvie.
   Backing Bush was Gov. James Thompson, as well as 93 of the
state's 102 Republican county chairmen.
   While the Dole campaign cited Illinois as the staging ground for
a comeback, Bush aides called the state important but not essential.
   ``If for some reason George Bush can't win Illinois, I still
suspect he's going to be the nominee of the Republican Party,''
said Atwater.
   The Bush campaign aide cited the key role the state has played
in past presidential nomination races.
   ``In my mind, Ronald Reagan was going to be the nominee when we
won Illinois in 1980,'' he said. ``In my mind when Mondale won
Illinois in 1984, he was going to be the nominee.''
   Atwater and Bond contended that the election calendar also is a
problem for Dole.
   They cited the fact that among the key states that follow
Illinois are Connecticut, where Bush has a big advantage, and New
York, where the vice president is the only candidate to have
delegate slates filed in every congressional district.
   ``We get 45 delegates just for showing up,'' said Bond.
   ``Even winning a state or two,'' added Bond, ``I don't see how
he (Dole) gets the upper hand. ... Can he win a state or two? Sure.
Can he stop Bush? I don't think so.''
</TEXT>
