<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ContraAid     03-07 0607</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Contra Aid,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Again Calls for Contra Military Aid, But Wright Cool</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan renewed his call Monday for
weapons for the rebels fighting Nicaragua's leftist government, but
House Speaker Jim Wright gave the request an icy reception.
   In a speech to a Veterans of Foreign Wars convention, Reagan
said his congressional opponents on the issue of aid to the Contra
rebels lack courage to fight communism, and said efforts to renew
``humanitarian'' aid for the rebels are insufficient.
   ``Now it's time for Congress to show that it knows you can't
have real peace negotiations when one side has helicopter gunships
and the other has bandages,'' Reagan told the group.
   Reagan's spokesman, Marlin Fitzwater, said later that the
administration still hopes Wright will come up with a new Contra
aid proposal and that the White House will be encouraging efforts
in the Senate to write an aid bill.
   Fitzwater acknowledged that ``time is a problem. ... We don't
know how long (the Contras) can last.'' U.S. aid to the rebels
ended a week ago.
   But on Capitol Hill, where the House last week narrowly defeated
an effort to send food and clothing to the Contras, Wright said it
is time to turn to other issues.
   ``There is a weariness with the Contra issue'' among House
members, said Wright, D-Texas. He added that he plans to begin
mapping out a program of other legislation to bring to the floor,
including issues like welfare reform and a health-care bill.
   Wright also signaled that a group of senators trying to revive
some kind of Contra aid bill could run into procedural roadblocks,
reminding reporters obliquely that the House traditionally reserves
the right to originate any legislation to appropriate money.
   ``I'm not looking for problems'' with a Senate-originated bill,
he said, but added: ``Those who draft the legislation ought to be
mindful of that.''
   Wright said last week's defeat of the Democratic $30.8 million
Contra aid package means that the United States is left with little
more than moral suasion as a tool to influence Central American
peace efforts.
   ``It just throws it into the hands of the Central Americans
entirely, and sort of withdraws the United States for the moment
from having any direct influence,'' he said.
   Wright said he has sent telegrams to both sides in the conflict,
urging them to pursue a cease-fire agreement when they meet this
week for the first time without a mediator and inside Nicaragua.
   He said he urged the Sandinista side to permit a role for
Nicaraguan Cardinal Miguel Obando y Bravo, whom Nicaraguan
President Daniel Ortega has rejected as a mediator after several
fruitless sessions. And he asked the rebels to go forward with the
talks, noting that they had been granted the high-level direct
talks they have been seeking.
   In his speech, Reagan said the defeat of the Contras would mean
a ``grave strategic defeat for the United States.''
   ``The communists in Central America understand this, the Soviets
understand this _ it's time that Congress understood it too,''
Reagan said. ``A Soviet base on the American mainland is a pistol
pointed at the heart of the Americas.''
   Reagan contended that the ``real issue'' before the Congress is
not the Contras, ``it is communism in Central America.''
   Referring to last week's 216-to-208 vote, Reagan said: ``Courage
hasn't exactly been the watchword of some opponents of Contra aid.
... Last week, aid opponents tried to pass the buck of
responsibility for abandoning in the field the young men and women
of the Democratic resistance, and that ploy failed as it should
have.''
</TEXT>
