<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Scotus-Juries     03-07 0300</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Scotus-Juries,290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court To Decide Case On Disqualifying Black Potential Jurors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court said Monday it will decide
whether a criminal defendant's right to a jury selected from a
cross-section of the community is violated when prosecutors
disqualify potential jurors because they are black.
   The court will review the case of Frank D. Teague, sentenced to
30 years in prison for the armed robbery of a Chicago supermarket
and for the attempted murder of police officers shot at after the
robbery.
   The justices in 1986 ruled in a case called Batson vs. Kentucky
that prosecutors never may disqualify potential jurors based on
their race. The court said such tactics violate equal-protection
rights.
   But a subsequent decision strictly limited the retroactive
effect of the Batson ruling.
   The court said the Batson decision does not apply to convicted
criminals who, like Teague, had exhausted direct appeals in state
courts prior to April 30, 1986, when Batson was announced.
   If the justices were to rule that the prosecutorial tactics used
at Teague's trial violated his Sixth Amendment right to
cross-sectional jury selection, he would be entitled to a new trial
even though the Batson ruling came too late to help him.
   Presumably, such a ruling would affect other prison inmates'
convictions as well.
   The 7th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ruled last May that past
Supreme Court decisions make clear that ``the fair cross-section
requirement of the Sixth Amendment does not apply to the jury
itself'' but only to the pool of potential jurors from which juries
are chosen.
   Lawyers for Teague, who is black, contend that his fair-trial
rights were violated when prosecutors used all 10 of their
so-called peremptory challenges to exclude blacks from the jury.
   The court's decision is not expected until sometime in 1989.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
