<HEAD>Candidates Ending Super Tuesday Ad Blitz, Ready to Turn to
Illinois</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Presidential candidates sent out their last
wave of commercials in Super Tuesday states on Monday, and
Republican Bob Dole was already appealing to TV viewers in the next
battleground.
   Dole was running ads in 11 states, including Illinois, which
holds its primary next Tuesday.
   In Illinois, the Kansas senator started running a spot called
``Strong Man'' that stresses the poverty and war wounds Dole
overcame in rising to his present post of Senate GOP leader. The ad
says Dole ``turned Ronald Reagan's vision into an action plan for
America. Tax cuts, aid for the Contras, fighting wasteful
spending.''
   Dole was running a mix of ads _ including an attack on Vice
President George Bush's Iran-Contra role _ in Illinois, Alabama,
Maryland, Gorgia, Louisiana, Washington, Oklahoma, North Carolina,
Missouri, Arkansas and Florida.
   Bush was expected to trounce Dole in the Super Tuesday arena and
planned ``the heaviest media buy we'll place anywhere in this
campaign'' in Illinois, according to aide Rich Bond.
   Bush has been endorsed by Illinois Gov. Jim Thompson and most of
the state's county Republican chairmen.
   Sen. Albert Gore Jr, D-Tenn., was running a mix of seven TV
spots in 13 Southern and border states. Four of the ads were
head-on criticism of rival Democrats while the other three stressed
populist, anti-establishment themes.
   Gore planned to split his time between Illinois and South
Carolina until the Saturday primary in South Carolina, and then
return to Illinois until next Tuesday's primary there.
   Rep. Richard Gephardt, D-Mo., has been endorsed by powerful Rep.
Dan Rostenkowski of Chicago and expects to spend parts of Thursday
and Friday in Illinois. Spokeswoman Lisa Cutter said Gephardt was
not advertising in Illinois as of Monday.
   The congressman was running a mix of five television spots in
eight Super Tuesday states: Texas, Oklahoma, Louisiana, Arkansas,
Alabama, Mississippi, Florida and Georgia. Among them were
endorsements by Rep. Claude Pepper, D-Fla., and Marvin Leath,
D-Texas, his famous trade ad about the $48,000 K-Car, and two
attacks on Michael Dukakis.
   Two Democratic native sons, Jesse Jackson and Sen. Paul Simon,
planned no television advertising in their home state of Illinois.
   ``We're planning to run a barnstorming campaign around the
state'' counting on news coverage, said Simon press secretary Terry
Michael.
   Simon skipped Super Tuesday, saying he couldn't afford it and it
would be inconclusive. Jackson ran a modest, upbeat TV campaign to
augment a full schedule of personal appearances.
</TEXT>
