<HEAD>US Would Welcome North Korean Participation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States would welcome participation
by North Korean athletes in the Seoul Olympics, a senior U.S.
diplomat said Monday.
   ``The Olympics would be better off if North Korea chooses to
participate,'' said Assistant Secretary of State Edward Derwinski.
``But time is running out.''
   He added that ``we have nothing but a positive attitude'' toward
participation by Pyongyang.
   Derwinski said the United States will have ``some additional
naval units'' in the region at the time of the September Olympic
Games. Speaking at the U.S. Information Agency's Foreign Press
Center, he said the additional naval presence was ``a very timely,
practical coincidence.''
   Other U.S. officials have said the additional presence will
probably consist of one or two aircraft carriers.
   Derwinski warned that any attempt by the North Koreans to
disrupt the games ``would make them a total pariah.'' North Korea
is one of only a handful of countries, including Cuba, which is
boycotting the games.
   Derwinski indicated that the United States would ask visiting
Chinese Foreign Minister Wu Xueqian to use his country's leverage
with North Korea to prevent any disruption of the Olympics.
   ``This is the logical, diplomatic way to proceed'' with the
Pyongyang government, he said. ``We have no leverage with them, and
any suggestion on our part would be counterproductive.''
