<2ND_LINE>AM-Skier Search, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0662,0265</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Searchers With Dogs Find Body of Buried Skier</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with body found; No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ASHFORD, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rescuers using trained dogs found the body
of a cross-country skier buried in an avalanche in Mount Rainer
National Park, a park spokesman said Monday.
   Pamela Benton Lee, 28, of Olympia, was buried Sunday afternoon
in the Plummer Peak area, 5,000 to 6,000 feet in elevation,
spokesman Dave Uberuaga said.
   Her companion, Sean Mehan of Olympia, told rangers he probed
unsuccessfully in the snow for about an hour before skiing out and
notifying park rangers, Uberuaga said.
   Mehan, with two rangers and two climbers, tried to get to the
site late Sunday, but had to turn back because of darkness and
avalanche hazard, Uberuaga said.
   On Monday, a team of 11 park staff, 10 members of the area
mountain-rescue council and three dog units began probing the
avalanche, Uberuaga said. An initial shoulder-to-shoulder sweep of
the avalanche failed to fine Ms. Lee, he said.
   A dog that sensed a ``hot spot'' found the body buried near the
base of the avalanche, Uberuaga said. Rescuers used probes to
pinpoint the body and dig it out. Ms. Lee had been missing about 20
hours.
   The avalanche, about 60 feet wide and 120 feet long, ranged in
depth from 2 feet to 10 feet, Uberuaga said.
   A high avalanche hazard was posted all day Sunday, after
Paradise received 10 inches of snow Saturday, bringing the total
there to 130 inches. Avalanche hazard was still considered high on
Monday.
</TEXT>
