<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Corn-Soviets     03-07 0240</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Corn-Soviets,230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Union Buys More US Corn</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union has bought an additional
300,000 metric tons of U.S. corn for delivery this year under a
long-term supply agreement between the two countries, the
Agriculture Department said Monday.
   A metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 39.4 bushels
of corn or 36.7 bushels of wheat or soybeans. The 300,000 tons of
corn would be about 11.8 million bushels.
   Corn prices recently have been averaging about $1.85 per bushel
at the farm level, meaning that the sale could have a farm value of
around $22 million.
   The corn is part of the grain the Soviet Union is committed to
buy during the fifth and final year of the agreement, which calls
for the annual purchase of at least 9 million tons of U.S. grain.
The pact expires Sept. 30.
   According to the agreement, the annual purchases are supposed to
include a minimum of 4 million tons each of wheat and corn. The
Soviets have the option of buying the remaining 1 million tons as
wheat, corn or soybeans, with every ton of beans counting as two
tons of grain _ up to a maximum of 1 million tons of grain
equivalent.
   With the latest purchases, the Soviets now have bought 3.17
million tons of corn, plus almost 6.9 million tons of wheat;
813,300 tons of soybeans, and 1.3 million tons of soybean meal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880307-0120 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-07-88 1647EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Gephardt     03-07 0371</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gephardt,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gephardt Says He's Best Candidate on Energy</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Richard Gephardt emphasized his
support for an oil-import fee on Monday, one day before four
oil-producing states vote on Super Tuesday, then went to the Alamo
to call himself the Democratic candidate for economic independence.
   ``We're standing today in front of the Alamo, a place where
there was a fight for independence,'' Gephardt said. ``This
election in 1988 is a fight again for the independence of America,
the fight for us to regain control of our economic destiny.''
   Gephardt spoke to about 400 supporters and tourists in this
city, generally considered a stronghold for Massachusetts Gov.
Michael Dukakis, after speaking at a struggling Dallas plant that
makes equipment for the oil industry.
   Dukakis was at the Alamo Sunday. Many of the Democrats here are
Hispanic, and Dukakis spoke to them in fluent Spanish.
   But Rep. Albert Bustamante, D-Texas, supporting Gephardt, told
the rally on Monday that no one suffers more from the oil
industry's downturn than South Texas Hispanics.
   ``If you want somebody who speaks Spanish, I do a little of that
and I can interpret for Dick,'' Bustamante said, noting that
Gephardt has begun studying Spanish. San Antonio Mayor Henry
Cisneros has stayed neutral, although his wife has endorsed Dukakis.
   Gephardt recalled he trained for the Missouri Air National Guard
at Lackland Air Force Base near here. He then attacked Dukakis for
wanting to cut the defense budget.
   ``He's going to leave us in jeopardy and vulnerable,'' Gephardt
said.
   He continued to criticize his foes for opposing an oil-import
fee.
   ``Anyone like Al Gore or Michael Dukakis who tells you that
they're for making America energy independent is simply trying to
deceive you in a shameful way,'' Gephardt said after touring
Dresser Industries, a Dallas plant that Gephardt said shows the
need for long-term domestic energy policy because of its nearly 50
percent cutbacks in operation.
   Gephardt has concentrated on Gore and Dukakis in his Texas
swing. Polls indicate he and Gore are battling for third behind
Dukakis and civil rights leader Jesse Jackson. But Gephardt said
his chances for winning Texas were good.
</TEXT>
