<FILEID>AP-NR-03-07-88 1647EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-SouthAfrica     03-07 0400</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-South Africa,0408</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Security Council Draft Calls For Economic Sanctions Against South
Africa</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Security Council draft resolution
circulated Monday calls for mandatory economic sanctions, including
an oil embargo, against South Africa to force the government to
abolish apartheid within a year.
   The draft resolution, to be discussed when the council meets
Tuesday, expresses outrage at the banning of anti-apartheid
activities and concern for the ``worsening of the human suffering
resulting from the apartheid system'' of racial segregation.
   The resolution says South Africa's intransigence ``compels the
international community to impose, as a first step, selective
mandatory sanctions.''
   Under South Africa's system of apartheid, the 26 million blacks
have no voice in national affairs and the 5 million whites control
the economy and maintain separate schools and districts.
   The resolution, circulated after three days of debate, calls for
a halt to export and sale of oil to South Africa; an end to further
investment and loans; a ban on imports of iron and steel; a halt of
all trade promotion and support for trade; prohibition of sale of
Kruggerands and all coins minted in South Africa; and cessation of
all forms of military, policy or intelligence cooperation,
especially the sale of computer equipment.
   South African U.N. Ambassador Leslie Manley told the Security
Council on Thursday, ``We will not bow to your threats or demands
and we reject your accusations with contempt and invite you to do
your damnedest.''
   The resolution calls for all U.N. members to back the sanctions
and report progress to the secretary-general. It establishes a
Security Council committee to monitor implementation.
   Security Council resolutions can be vetoed by any one of its
permanent members _ the United States, Great Britain, China, France
and the Soviet Union. The Council and the U.N. General Assembly
have condemned South Africa in the past, but the United States and
other countries have opposed sanctions.
   The resolution says the sanctions would remain in force for one
year, after which the council again will meet to determine if South
Africa has abolished apartheid.
   The proposed measures also require South Africa to lift the ban
on anti-apartheid political activities, release all political
prisoners, allow the free and safe return of exiles and commence
dialogue with leaders of the majority black population.
   The draft resolution was submitted by Algeria, Argentina, Nepal,
Senegal, Yugoslavia and Zambia.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880307-0122 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-07-88 1656EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Scotus-SexBias     03-07 0525</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Scotus-Sex Bias,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>High Court To Rule Whether Stereotyping Denied Woman Partnership</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court on Monday set the stage for
an important ruling on sex discrimination, agreeing to study a case
in which ``unconscious stereotyping'' allegedly played a key role
in denying a woman an accounting firm partnership.
   The justices said they will review a ruling that places a heavy
burden on employers to disprove sex bias.
   Arguments in the case will be heard in the fall during the
court's next term and a decision is not likely to be announced
until 1989.
   Price Waterhouse, one of the nation's largest accounting firms,
is accused of discriminating unlawfully against Ann Hopkins. She
quit the firm's office here after she was denied promotion to
partnership, a move that would have made her a part owner.
   Ms. Hopkins joined the firm in 1978 and was nominated for
partnership in 1982, the only woman among 88 candidates for
partnership that year.
   She had been very successful in getting business for the
company, winning government contracts worth an estimated $34
million to $44 million.
   Of the 88 candidates, 47 were invited to become partners; 21
were rejected outright; and 20 including Ms. Hopkins were placed on
hold.
   The following year she was told she would not become a partner,
and she resigned in 1984 to set up her own consulting firm.
   Both her critics and supporters at Price Waterhouse said she
sometimes was overly aggressive, too harsh, impatient with her
staff and very demanding.
   One critic suggested she needed to take a ``course at charm
school.''
   A partner in the firm who urged her promotion told her she would
stand a better chance of becoming a partner if she would ``walk
more femininely, talk more femininely, dress more femininely, wear
make-up, have her hair styled and wear jewelry.''
   Others said her use of profanity was a black mark against her.
   Ms. Hopkins then sued Price Waterhouse, accusing the company of
violating Title VII of the 1964 Civil Rights Act prohibiting
on-the-job sex disscrimination. She said that sex stereotyping,
unconscious or otherwise, barred her from being named partner.
   The Supreme Court ruled in 1984, in the case of a woman denied
partnership in a law firm, that professional partnerships are
covered by the 1964 law.
   A federal judge ruled Price Waterhouse must prove ``by clear and
convincing evidence'' it would not have made her a partner
regardless of whether sexual stereotyping played a part in its
decision.
   Price Waterhouse said it was unable to provide such proof.
   The U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals here last August said there is
``competent evidence that ... the partnership selection process at
Price Waterhouse was impermissibly infected by stereotypical
attitudes toward female candidates.''
   The appeals court said even if there is evidence that Ms.
Hopkins' personality played a part in her denial of partnership,
Price Waterhouse is unable to prove ``impermissible bias was not
the determinative factor.''
   The appeals court ordered further hearings to determine what
back pay and other remedies the company must provide.
   The case is Price Waterhouse vs. Hopkins, 87-1167.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
