<HEAD>Pakistan's President Optimistic about Afghan Peace Talks</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: One name for Najib cq in 5th graf</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED AFTAB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Zia Ul-Haq of Pakistan was quoted Monday
as saying he's certain of signing an Afghan peace accord soon, even
though his representative continued to press for an interim
government to oversee withdrawal of Soviet troops.
   Pakistan's chief representative in the peace talks, acting
Foreign Minister Zain Noorani, said Islamabad was still hoping for
Soviet cooperation, even though his country wants an interim
government to replace the present Moscow-backed regime.
   ``It is in their interest, too, to see that there is peace and
calm after they leave,'' said Noorani after talks resumed Monday
morning following a weekend recess.
   However, Zia was quoted as telling the Gulf News, a United Arab
Emirates newspaper, that ``there is no question of the accord not
going through.'' ``Allowing it to be dropped is no option,'' he
said.
   The talks adjourned so Pakistani government and opposition
leaders could discuss whether they're ready to sign an accord with
the Soviet-backed Afghan government of President Najib.
   Pakistan represents Afghan rebels in the talks and does not
recognize the Kabul government.
   Noorani declined to say what Pakistan had decided over the
weekend.
   No afternoon session was scheduled following the morning
meetings conducted separately by U.N. mediator Diego Cordovez with
the Afghan and Pakistani delegations. Asked whether there was any
progress, Afghan Foreign Minister Abdul Wakil said only, ``Ask Mr.
Cordovez.''
   Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev has named March 15 as the
deadline for signing a settlement if the pullout of 115,000 Soviet
troops is to begin in mid-May, before a U.S.-Soviet summit.
   Agreement was reached Thursday on a withdrawal over nine months
in which half of the troops would leave within 90 days.
   A spokesman for the largest group in the seven-party Afghan
rebel alliance said Monday that progress was being made in setting
up an Islamic government with headquarters possibly in Afghanistan.
Professor Abdul Kadir Kariab, in charge of political affairs of the
fundamentalist Hezb-I-Islami party, said a U.S-educated engineer,
Ahmed Shah, had already been unanimously elected head of state.
   Kariab also told reporters in Geneva that the alliance was
already in contact with Pakistan, Iran and other countries
regarding possible recognition of the future government.
   The alliance claims to represent 200,000 rebels and to control
80 percent of the Afghan territory.
   Kariab also repeated charges raised by the chairman of his
party, Gulbaddin Hekmatyar, that the United States and the Soviet
Union had struck a ``secret deal'' to prevent formation of such a
government. He said a ``Jewish lobby'' was part of such
``conspiracy'' because it feared Islamic fundamentalism.
   He said that if Pakistan were pressed to sign ``a settlement in
the present shape, (it) will be historic treason to the Afghan
people.''
</TEXT>
