<BYLINE>By DAVID GRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SOUTH BURLINGTON, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A South African diplomat was cited
for assault Monday after his car struck a protester and a police
officer outside a radio station where he had been interviewed,
police said.
   South African Vice Consul Duke Kent Brown was arrested about a
quarter-mile away after allegedly fleeing the scene, Police Chief
John Race said.
   Brown was charged with simple assault, released on his own
recognizance and ordered to appear in court in April. The charge
carries up to a year in prison and a fine of $1,000, Race said.
   Brown left the Burlington area following his release, police
said, and he failed to make three other scheduled appearances with
the media.
   Jim Condon, news director at radio station WJOY-WQCR and a
witness, said the protester who was struck suffered minor bruises.
   Race identified the injured officer as Todd Shepard, said he had
suffered leg bruises and was being examined at a hospital.
   It was unclear whether Brown would be covered by diplomatic
immunity. Race said police had called the U.S. State Department for
guidance.
   A spokesman in the South African Embassy in Washington, Third
Secretary Heyn Van Rooyen, said Brown is connected with the
consulate in New York.
   ``There are different degrees of diplomatic immunity,'' said Van
Rooyen, adding he was not sure what would apply to Brown.
   Condon said about 30 members of the Vermont Committee on
Southern Africa had gathered outside the station to protest Brown's
participation in a talk show.
   He said Brown left the station under police escort and made his
way to a car in a parking lot. Brown got in and a few protesters
sat on the hood, Condon said.
   Police were in the process of removing protesters from the hood
when Brown ``hit the accelerator,'' Condon said.
