<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BetterAir     03-07 0400</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Better Air,0409</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Better Air Campaign Exceeded Goals; Oxy Fuels Program Right On
Target</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Metropolitan area residents exceeded the goals set
by the Better Air Campaign in reducing traffic volume and wood
smoke on high pollution days and met the oxygenated fuel program's
goals, officials announced Monday.
   Gov. Roy Romer and Denver Mayor Federico Pena reported the
results of the 90-day Better Air Campaign and the two-month
oxygenated fuels program at a news conference.
   ``The people of this area are to be congratulated,'' Romer said.
``By reducing their driving between November and January and by
restricting wood burning on high-pollution days, they have reduced
carbon monoxide pollution in the metro area by up to 17 percent.''
   The campaign's purpose was to reduce traffic volume and
wood-smoke pollution on days when temperature inversions caused
Denver's carbon-monoxide levels to soar.
   The project achieved a 9 percent reduction in traffic on
high-pollution days, equivalent to three million miles daily, and a
10 percent reduction in carbon monoxide vehicle emissions, said
Anne Grady, spokeswoman for the Colorado Department of health's Air
Pollution Control Division. She said the program's goal was an 8
percent traffic reduction and a 9 percent reduction in carbon
monoxide.
   Carbon monoxide emissions from wood-burning fell 7 percent on
high-pollution days during the most recent Better Air Campaign,
said Grady, and the goal was a 6 percent reduction.
   Pena said the 7 percent carbon monoxide reduction attributable
to observance of wood-burning bans was more than double last year's
results.
   The Better Air Campaign ran from early November until the end of
January. In its previous three years, it ran for just 60 days.
   The oxygenated fuels program, which was launched for the first
time in January and lasted two months, required all service
stations along the 130-mile corridor along the Front Range between
Colorado Springs and Fort Collins to sell only oxygenated fuels, or
fuels containing at least 1.5 percent oxygen.
   The program's purpose was to provide a gasoline that would burn
cleaner in car engines and thus contribute less carbon monoxide
pollution, officials said. Motorists were offered the choice of an
ether-gasoline blend, or gasohol, which contains ethyl alcohol.
   Grady said the oxy fuels program was right on target in its goal
of reducing ambient carbon-monoxide levels by 8 percent to 10
percent. The reduction was in the 8 percent to 9.5 percent range,
she said.
</TEXT>
