<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MistakenMurder     03-07 0357</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mistaken Murder,0369</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Say Hired Killers Might Have Murdered Wrong Medical Student</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A medical student whose nickname and appearance
were similar to another student's may have been tortured and
murdered by mistake by killers hired to hit his classmate,
investigators said.
   Both students were Cuban-Americans from Florida, both were
studying medicine at the Universidad Central del Este in the
Dominican Republic, but they did not know each other.
   The body of Ignacio Pereda, 26, of Miami, dumped near a sugar
cane field two days after he was kidnapped, had been beaten so
badly that only a birthmark on the back of one hand permitted his
identification, The Miami Herald reported Monday, quoting the
victim's family.
   His abduction came just three weeks before he was scheduled to
graduate from the Caribbean medical school on Feb. 12.
   Police, stumped for a motive, began looking into an earlier
incident involving another Cuban-American student at the University.
   Shortly before the killing, student Jorge Sotolongo had a run-in
with a jealous husband, who fired his gun but hit no one, The
Herald reported.
   The two young men resembled each other and Pereda, from Miami,
was known by a nickname similar to Sotolongo _ Bobolongo.
   ``We believe the murder could have been a mistake,'' said First
Lt. Jose Antonio Torres of San Pedro de Macoris, a town about 40
miles east of the capital of Santo Domingo, where the body was
found.
   Sotolongo has returned to his home in St. Petersburg.
   ``I don't think he is in any danger, he is here with me,''
Sotolongo's father told The Herald. ``He is sorry for the other
boy. He doesn't know if they killed him by mistake or if they
wanted to kill him.''
   Pereda's murder devastated his parents, who have no other
children, and friends.
   ``He didn't smoke, or drink or fool around. He was very
educated, an old-fashioned person,'' said his classmate and
girlfriend, Virginia Garcia. ``No drugs, no alcohol, no women.
There are very few men like him nowadays.''
   One aunt, Aida Rodriguez, said she wants to go to the Dominican
Republic.
   ``We want answers,'' she said.
</TEXT>
