<DOCNO> AP880307-0128 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-07-88 1722EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CondorEgg     03-07 0427</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Condor Egg,0438</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Keepers Detect The Beginnings Of A Condor Chick</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto GO1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENNIS GEORGATOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first California condor egg produced by
captive breeding is fertile and contains the makings of a chick,
San Diego Wild Animal Park officials said Monday.
   ``You can't actually see an embryo yet, but what you can see is
the beginnings of circulatory development, which appears as a dark
dime-sized dot toward the top of the yolk,'' park spokesman Tom
Hanscom said.
   The egg was laid Thursday, the product of a male condor known as
AC-4 and a female condor called UN-1. It was removed immediately
from its nest in the park's ``condorminium'' and placed in an
incubator.
   Keepers peeked inside the egg by holding it up to a
high-intensity lamp in a process known as ``candling.'' The egg
then was returned to its incubator, where it will be kept until the
hatching expected between April 28 and May 3, Hanscom said.
   ``Now, we incubate the egg according to the parameters that have
worked so well in the past and hope ... we can hatch a healthy
condor chick,'' he said.
   All 27 living California condors are in captivity. Fourteen are
kept at the Wild Animal Park and 13 at the Los Angeles Zoo.
   Thirteen of the 27 birds were hatched in captivity in an effort
to build a breeding flock to save the rare birds from extinction.
Each of those eggs were taken from nests in the wild.
   The breeding program has been conducted at the San Diego Zoo and
its affiliate, the Wild Animal Park, since 1983 in cooperation with
state and federal wildlife officials.
   The last known wild condor was captured in April 1987 by
government biologists after it was determined the carrion-eating
birds' existence was threatened by lead poisoning in their food
supply and human encroachment upon their central California habitat.
   ``Our success or failure has pivoted on the captive production
of a fertile egg and that's what we've got,'' Hanscom said of the
4-day-old egg.
   Meanwhile, the parents of the egg were said to be doing well.
Keepers removed the shell from its nest soon after it was laid to
stimulate more breeding activity by the pair, which Hanscom said
has begun.
   ``That's real positive,'' he said. ``That would lead us to hope
for the production of a second egg, which could come as early as 30
days after the first egg.
   ``The parents are doing fine, the egg is doing fine and the
keepers are doing fine.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880307-0129 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-07-88 1754EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FloridaCrime     03-07 0589</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Florida Crime,0605</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Number Of Serious Crimes Rise By 6.3 Percent</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANA SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 1 million serious crimes were
reported in Florida last year, a record number blamed in part on
the spread of ``crack'' cocaine and other drugs, authorities
announced Monday.
   The number of reported homicides, rapes, robberies, assaults,
burglaries, larcenies and motor vehicle thefts rose 6.3 percent to
go over the 1 million mark for the first time, to 1,021,283, said
Robert Dempsey, commissioner of the Florida Department of Law
Enforcement.
   ``As you know, the crime rate is driven to a large extent by the
drug problem. There is no question about that,'' Dempsey said.
   He urged Gov. Bob Martinez and the Legislature to consider
increasing spending for criminal justice. Presently, he said, 6
percent of an $18.5 billion budget is devoted to the criminal
justice system, which includes law enforcement and the courts, he
said.
   ``It's intolerable. We need to do something about addressing
credibility in the criminal justice area,'' Dempsey said. ``We need
to address the career criminals, the jail situation and some of the
weaknesses in the so-called criminal justice system, which as many
of you know is no system at all.''
   Dempsey also said citizens need to start a grassroots campaign
to help prevent violence and property thefts. Increases in property
crime, particularly in some of the more rural counties, can be
directly attributed to the increase of the powerful crack form of
cocaine, the commissioner said.
   ``Anybody who tells you the drug problem is leveling off is in
fairyland. They don't know what's happening,'' he said.
   The Florida figures released Monday were preliminary. A complete
report was expected to be issued later this year.
   The commissioner said Florida continues to lead other states in
crime rates, or the number of crimes reported per 100,000
population. He compared Florida's 1987 figures with figures
reported by other states in 1986.
   ``We have the highest crime rate in the nation,'' said Dempsey.
   Department spokesman John Joyce said Florida's per-capita crime
rate, which increased by 2.9 percent in 1987, has been
significantly higher in past years than the figures reported by
other states. Since Florida is one of the first to release its
figures, new data was unavailable in other states.
   In 1986, Florida had 8,238 serious crimes reported per 100,000
population, compared with 7,408 in Texas, 7,322 in Arizona, 7,081
in Oregon, 7,032 in Colorado, 6,880 in Washington, 6,763 in
California, 6,626 in New Mexico, 6,491.5 in Michigan and 6,290 in
Nevada.
   The District of Columbia actually had the highest of all with
8,339 per 100,000 population.
   In Florida, the total arrests for cocaine last year were up 32.8
percent over 1986, while property crimes increased 6.7 percent over
1986. The number of motor vehicle thefts rose by 16.4 percent, and
aggravated assaults showed a 3.1 percent increase.
   The number of reported murders and rapes was slightly down.
Homicides declined from 1,371 to 1,368 and rapes declined from
6,153 to 6,017.
   More police officers were assaulted and killed in 1987 than the
previous year, 10 compared with six. Assaults on police officers
rose from 7,289 in 1986 to 7,833 in 1987.
   Dempsey acknowledged that the overall crime increase was not as
high as had been reported in recent years. From 1985 to 1986, his
department reported a 7.9 percent increase. The increase was 11.4
percent from 1984 to 1985.
   ``It's true the rate of increase is dropping but it is still an
increase,'' Dempsey said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880307-0130 </DOCNO>
