<1ST_LINE>r a AM-EasternScuffle     03-07 0270</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Eastern Scuffle,0277</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Scuffle Over Eastern Bumping Leaves One Hurt, One Arrested</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Eastern Airlines passenger was free on bond
Monday after allegedly battling police and ticket agents when he
and 200 irate passengers were bumped off New York-bound flights.
   It was the latest of several incidents in recent months that
have plagued Eastern in the wake of canceled flights and bumpings.
   The confrontation Sunday began when 226 passengers were bumped
from a 3:15 p.m. flight to La Guardia, said Eastern spokesman Bob
Carson. Some were later bumped repeatedly from other flights, and
were demanding to get on the final flight of the night about 9:30
p.m.
   The angry passengers pushed up against the ticket counter when
the flight was called, and Jack Lemonik, 26, of Great Neck, N.Y,
allegedly went behind the counter, said Metro-Dade police Lt.
Robert Otero.
   Lemonik allegedly punched one ticket agent in the chest and
pushed another with his rucksack before police moved in.
   Three officers grabbed Lemonik, Otero said. One hit his leg on a
trash can and fell to the ground, and was later treated for a knee
injury, Otero said.
   Passengers shouted angrily at police as they struggled with
Lemonik, said Curt Arnel, 30, of Merrick, N.Y.
   Lemonik was charged with two counts of simple battery,
aggravated battery and resisting arrest with violence, said
Metro-Dade police spokeswoman Lizette Williams. He was released on
$5,500 bond Monday, police said.
   Passengers who could not be booked back to New York on Sunday
were put up in hotels and were to be put on flights Monday, said
Eastern spokeswoman Karen Ceremsak.
</TEXT>
