<2ND_LINE>AM-Robertson,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Robertson Renews Contention of Missiles in Cuba</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SHREVEPORT, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pat Robertson renewed his contention that
there are Soviet missiles in Cuba on Monday and also said the
Federal Reserve Board was unconstitutional.
   Earlier, in Wichita Falls, Texas, the Republican presidential
candidate said he was satisfied with a federal judge's dismissal of
his libel suit against a former congressman who had questioned
Robertson's war record.
   In Texas, the biggest Super Tuesday prize with 111 GOP
delegates, Robertson talked about military needs and about his
contentions concerning missiles.
   ``In New England, they thought it was a gaffe when I said there
were missiles in Cuba, but those Cubans (in Florida) don't believe
it's a gaffe. They believe there's Russian missiles in Cuba,'' he
said.
   Later, in a call-in show on Shreveport's KFLO radio, he said,
``Everybody in the Miami area _ almost without exception _
certainly 95 percent of those Cuban-Americans know in their hearts
that there are missiles in Cuba. I don't think the missiles ever
got taken out in '62. And I am somewhat convinced that more
missiles have been introduced.''
   To support his contention, he said Cuban leader Fidel has denied
the missiles are there and has criticized Robertson for saying they
are.
   On other subjects raised on the call-in show, Robertson said:
   _``There has been filed, by a United States senator from
Montana, a suit in the federal court alleging that the Federal
Reserve Board is unconstitutional. I think it's true.''
   _The Supreme Court needs people like (Justices) Antonin Scalia,
William Rehnquist (and defeated nominee) Robert Bork, people like
that, who honor the Constitution as it was written.''
   _``Not one of the trading partners of America truly is dealing
fairly with us. They're either restricting imports into their
country on the one hand, or they are subsidizing unfairly exports
from their country to us.''
   _``I believe, in my heart, and from some indication from some
people who I've talked to, that there are American servicemen still
in Laos. They aren't in Vietnam, they're in Laos. ... I believe we
could put a throttle-hold around some of those Southeast Asian
nations, to make them insist those missing-in-action people come
out of there.''
   _Raising the possibility of an alternative to the United
Nations, ``I think if we had an alternate organization of free
nations, democratic nations, who did not commit terrorism and did
not torture and abuse their own citizens, we could have the power
of the world. And we could exclude from that agency the Soviet
Union, the East Bloc countries and these other dictators that are
practicing slavery and what have you against their people.''
   In Washington, a U.S. District Court judge dismissed Robertson's
$35 million suit against former Rep. Paul N. McCloskey Jr., who had
accused Robertson of ducking combat duty during the Korean War.
   ``The judge gave me what I consider a real victory,'' Robertson
said during a news conference at Wichita Falls' Municipal Airport.
   However, McCloskey said, ``This is a confirmation of my
integrity.'' Robertson, in asking that the suit be dropped, ``is
admitting that he is the one who is the liar,'' McCloskey said.
``The court's service was to unmask this man as the fraud he is.''
   Robertson had said he had to ask that the suit be dismissed
since he couldn't pursue the presidency and go through the trial
that was to start on Tuesday.
