<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Gorbachev     03-07 0560</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Gorbachev,0576</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Makes Sales Pitch on Economic Reform to Workers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mikhail S. Gorbachev has told factory workers not
to be discouraged by slow improvements in their standard of living
and to have faith in his overhaul of the economy.
   He visited the enormous First State Ball Bearing Plant in
Moscow, his first meeting with rank-and-file workers since a
sweeping law took effect Jan. 1 giving factories more financial
independence from central ministries.
   Gorbachev said he was particularly sensitive to complaints about
poor housing and food and said they were top priorities for
improvement.
   The 57-year-old Soviet leader visited the factory Friday but
media did not report on the trip until Monday. Why the reports were
delayed was not clear.
   ``Of course we have a sufficient number of problems,'' Gorbachev
told the workers. ``Part of them are left from the past, others
were born today, in the course of restructuring, in the process of
realizing economic reforms. That's natural. But I have the
impression that you haven't panicked, and I would say are
optimistically looking to the future and confidently going
forward.''
   Gorbachev has visited factories several times since becoming
Communist Party general secretary three years ago, highlighting the
importance he attaches to workers' roles in reviving the sluggish
Soviet economy.
   The ball bearing plant employs 20,000 factory and office
workers. Gorbachev said he wanted to get a first-hand look at how
the government's new economic reforms are being implemented.
   ``For politics, the most important thing is to know the mood of
the people, to feel the pulse of life,'' Gorbachev said in remarks
carried by the official news agency Tass.
   He explained to the workers why some of his economic policies
may be hard to swallow, because they mean harder work and in some
cases less pay. Salaries, he said, must be adjusted according to
the productivity and quality of labor.
   ``How can you pay someone a full ruble if he hasn't earned it?
What will he buy with this money?'' he said.
   He said the reason desired goods have not been available in
stores is that workers were guaranteed salaries whether or not they
did their jobs properly.
   Under the new law, managers at factories responsible for 60
percent of the country's industrial output can bargain with
suppliers and wholesale customers for some products. Enterprises
are free to keep some of their profits, but those that are
unsuccessful are liable to be declared bankrupt. The factories set
workers' salaries according to the quality of their work.
   Gorbachev critcized plant managers who try to find an easy way
out of improving output by buying foreign equipment.
   ``Obviously you must buy some things, but only that which is
absolutely necessary, and you should rely on your own domestic
machine-building, on the achievements of our engineering.''
   He assured the workers socialism will not be threatened by the
country's growing private enterprises, known as cooperatives.
   ``It's understood that we need industrious and honest
initiative, but not of the kind of some cooperatives which exploit
a deficit and engage in outright money-grabbing,'' Gorbachev said.
   Limited private enterprise has been allowed to supplement
state-run enterprises since May 1987. Prices of the goods and
services produced by cooperatives are generally much higher, but
Gorbachev told the workers the government plans to get its fair
share of profits, through a progressive tax.
</TEXT>
