<1ST_LINE>r a AM-INSStrip-Search     03-07 0258</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-INS Strip-Search,0264</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Bars INS from Routine Strip-Searching of Children</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Routine strip searches of children awaiting
deportation are unconstitutional, a federal judge ruled Monday,
saying immigration agents must first have a reasonable suspicion
that drugs or weapons have been hidden.
   U.S. District Judge Robert Kelleher rejected an Immigration and
Naturalization Service argument that the body-cavity searches are
needed because adults will use children as couriers if agents
cannot search them.
   ``Children confined by the INS are not charged with any criminal
offense, let alone an offense that might indicate a propensity to
conceal weapons or contraband on their persons,'' Kelleher ruled.
   In 1987, of 84,000 aliens searched, there were 20 discoveries of
contraband or weapons, only four of which were related to
juveniles, Kelleher noted.
   His ruling came in a class-action suit filed in 1985 by a
coalition of immigrants' rights groups that challenged what they
described as routine strip-searches of children upon admission to
INS detention facilities and following all visits with anyone other
than attorneys.
   Children are particularly susceptible to trauma from strip
searches, Kelleher said. He rejected an argument by Assistant U.S.
Attorney Ian Fan that children from Central America have no
expectation of privacy when arrested here.
   ``Many carry the expectation of liberty, opportunity and a
better life, the embodiment of which is our Constitution,''
Kelleher wrote.
   Only children are affected by the ruling. John Hagar, an
American Civil Liberties Union lawyer involved in the suit, said
the ruling covers all nine states in the INS' Western Region.
</TEXT>
