<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Nazi-WatchList     03-07 0324</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nazi-Watch List,310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Justice Office Adds 9,800 Former Nazi Guards To Watch List</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   S
   WASHINGTON (AP) _ The Justice Department's Nazi-hunting unit has
identified 9,800 people as former concentration camp guards and
said Monday it will have them placed on the immigration watch list
of individuals to be barred from the United States.
   The Office of Special Investigations compiled the names with the
assistance of a sophisticated new computer database.
   Names of suspected criminals and Nazi persecutors are
systematically checked against immigration records to determine if
they are in the United States.
   The names of individuals not found to be in this country are
included in the watch list to prevent them from entering.
   OSI has listed thousands of such people in the past few years.
But the 9,800 now to be placed on the watch list of the U.S.
Immigration and Naturalization Service ``for serving as
concentration and death camp guards is probably the greatest
number'' to be added at one time, said the office's chief, Neal
Sher.
   The watch list includes people who are prohibited from entering
the United States under a federal law barring individuals who
assisted or otherwise participated in Nazi-sponsored persecution.
   The provision, known as the Holtzman Amendment, was invoked when
Austrian President Kurt Waldheim was placed on the watch list last
year following a decision by Attorney General Edwin Meese III.
   The Justice Department cited evidence that Waldheim had
participated in activities amounting to persecution of Jews and
others in Greece and Yugoslavia in World War II when he was a
German army intelligence officer.
   The immigration watch list contains some 40,000 names. In
addition to those participating in Nazi-directed persecution, the
list contains the names of criminals, known terrorists, communists
or people who have been deported from the United States.
   Duke Austin, an INS spokesman, said names submitted by the
office of special investigations are routinely added to the watch
list.
</TEXT>
