<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Israel     03-07 0731</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Israel,730</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Again Says It Wants Early Response to Mideast Peace Proposal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration renewed its request
on Monday for an ``early response'' from Israel to a U.S. Middle
East peace initiative.
   It also said it welcomed the ``the support and advice'' of 30
senators who contend Israel should be willing to give up control of
occupied land in return for Middle East peace.
   At the State Department, spokesman Charles Redman said the
administration is looking for a reply to Secretary of State George
P. Shultz's plan to set up negotiations on Palestinian self-rule by
May 1.
   Redman's comment appeared to be directed to Israeli Prime
Minister Yitzhak Shamir, who is due in Washington next week for
meetings with President Reagan and Shultz.
   ``We believe all the parties understand and appreciate the
reason that we've asked for these kind of responses,'' Redman said.
   Shultz just returned from a Middle East trip during which he
promoted a plan to bring Israel, Jordan, Syria and Palestinian
Arabs to a peace conference by May 1. One goal is to stop violence
in the Israeli-occupied Gaza Strip and West Bank regions that has
claimed some 80 Arab lives in three months.
   Shultz briefed Regan on Monday on his travels.
   On Sunday, Shamir blocked a decision by the Israeli Cabinet on
the U.S. initiative. He said he would permit a vote after he
returns from his talks in Washington, but Israeli Foreign Minister
Shimon Peres had demanded a Cabinet decision before Shamir departed.
   Redman avoided a direct reaction to Shamir's move, but he went
on to call for an ``early response'' from Israel and the three Arab
governments _ Jordan, Egypt and Syria _ to whom Shultz submitted
his plan.
   Shultz said during his Middle East travels last week that he
hoped for a reply within about 10 days. He said he believed in
deadlines as a way of accelerating action.
   At the White House, spokesman Marlin Fitzwater was asked about
the letter from the 23 Democrats and seven Republicans, a group
that included several strong supporters of the Jewish state.
   The senators noted that Israel has in the past supported the
idea of ``land for peace'' by returning the Sinai Peninsula to
Egypt. But they cited a statement by Shamir that ``this expression
of territory for peace is not accepted by me.''
   ``We hope that the prime minister's statement did not indicate
that Israel is abandoning a policy that offers the best hope for
long-term peace,'' said the letter, dated March 3.
   ``The administration welcomes the support and advice from this
group. They are senators of considerable stature and interest and
involvment in Middle East affairs,'' Fitzwater told reporters.
   ``We are in the midst of an ongoing processs. The views of these
senators are helpful to us and probably instructive to other
parties in the region,'' he added.
   The spokesman said the administration was involved in a process
``that involves a blend of some new ideas and new beliefs,'' but he
refused to comment further.
   At the State Department, Redman said Shultz would respond to the
letter. He declined to address the matter further, except to say
the administration prefers ``to maintain a certain discreet
distance'' in the Mideast peace process.
   When he returned Saturday from the Middle East, Shultz expressed
no criticism of Shamir's position. He said the prime minister and
Peres agreed that Israel's annexation of territory could be a topic
for negotiations.
   Peres and his Labor Party have openly endorsed Shultz's
proposals, while Shamir and his Likud Party have not.
   Strong supporters of Israel signing the letter included senators
Alan Cranston, D-Calif.; Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass.; Daniel Patrick
Moynihan, D-N.Y.; Howard M. Metzenbaum, D-Ohio; Frank R.
Lautenberg, D-N.J.; Carl Levin, D-Mich.; and Rudy Boschwitz, R-Minn.
   Others whose names were on the letter included senators Daniel
Inouye, D-Hawaii; Lowell P. Weicker Jr., R-Conn.; George J.
Mitchell, D-Maine; Brock Adams, D-Wash.; Thomas A. Daschle, D-S.D.;
J. Bennett Johnston, D-La.; Donald W. Riegle Jr., D-Mich.; Tom
Harkin, D-Iowa; Warren B. Rudman, R-N.H.; Bob Kasten, R-Wis.; J.
James Exon, D-Neb.; Patrick J. Leahy, D-Vt.; John Kerry, D-Mass.;
Mitch McConnell, R-Ky; William S. Cohen, R-Maine; Alan K. Simpson,
R-Wyo.; Christopher J. Dodd, D-Conn.; Dennis DeConcini, D-Ariz.;
Kent Conrad, D-N.D.; John Glenn, D-Ohio; Timothy E. Wirth, D-Colo.;
Wendell H. Ford, D-Ky., and Bob Graham, D-Fla.
</TEXT>
