<HEAD>Congressman Says Soviets Renege on Pledge to Free
Lithuanian-American</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department has confirmed that the
Soviet Union is not allowing Lithuanian-American Povilas
Peciulaitis to emigrate despite a statement last December that he
would be free to leave, Rep. Edward Feighan said Monday.
   Feighan, D-Ohio, urged Secretary of State George P. Shultz to
quickly intervene and requested a meeting with Soviet Ambassador
Yuri Dubinin. He also sent a letter to Soviet leader Mikhail
Gorbachev asking that the matter be resolved quickly.
   ``They have the audacity to tell us now that it was a mistake,''
Feighan said of the Soviets. ``If the Soviets think I'm going to
stand by and meekly accept this broken promise, they had better
think again.''
   Peciulaitis, 64, was born in Lithuania, but his parents were
naturalized American citizens.
   Feighan said he fears for Peciulaitis' personal safety, adding
that verbal attacks against the man have recently appeared in
newspapers and on television in Lithuania.
   ``If the Soviets can renege on a promise, we can't be sure that
they won't try to harm Mr. Peciulaitis,'' Feighan said.
   Peciulaitis, who was exiled to Siberia for 22 years, is being
sponsored by his brother, who lives in suburban Cleveland.
</TEXT>
