<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     03-07 0380</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0387</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Snow Falls Heavily In The Colorado Rockies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A sharp cold front brought a renewal of winter weather whistling
across the central Rockies and the western Plains on Monday.
   A winter storm warning was posted through the night into Tuesday
for the mountains of southern Colorado. Snowfall totals of 8 to 16
inches were possible, along with gusty wind causing considerable
blowing and drifting, the National Weather Service said.
   Advisories for snow and blowing snow were posted into the night
the southeastern Colorado plains and adjacent foothills and for the
San Luis Valley.
   A mixture of rain, sleet and snow extended from North Dakota to
western Nebraska and temperatures were in the 20s and 30s.
   An advisory for snow and blowing snow was issued for western
South Dakota, where wind accompanying the snow gusted to 59 mph at
the Rapid City Airport.
   Strong southerly wind ahead of the cold front drove temperatures
up into the 70s across much of Texas, and into the 60s as far north
as eastern Kansas and southern Missouri.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 22
degrees at Laramie, Wyo., to 82 at Fort Myers, Fla. The low for the
day was 3 degrees above zero at Yellowstone National Park in
Wyoming.
   For Tuesday, showers and thunderstorms were forecast from
northern Texas and the central Gulf Coast into the middle
Mississippi Valley and the lower Ohio Valley, with showers in
southern sections of the upper Great Lakes. Snow was forecast in
the upper Mississippi Valley and northern sections of the upper
Great Lakes. Widely scattered showers were forecast from
northwestern Texas across much of Kansas and eastern Colorado.
   Highs in the 30s and 40s were predicted across a wide area from
northwestern Texas and western Oklahoma, much of the Rocky Mountain
region, the northern Plains, the upper Mississippi Valley across to
New England; above 60 from Oregon to California and from the Rio
Grande Valley of Texas to the southern and mid-Atlantic Coast; in
the 70s from central California to southern Arizona, from
south-central Texas to Tennessee and Alabama, and from West
Virginia to northern Florida; in the 80s in southern Florida and
the lower Rio Grande Valley of Texas; and in the 50s elsewhere.
</TEXT>
