<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DenverCityWorkers     03-07 0534</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Denver City Workers,0549</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mayor Shakes Up Public Works Department In Wake Of TV Report</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A television expose showing city workers goofing
off has added fuel to a campaign to recall Mayor Federico Pena, the
mayor's opponents said Monday.
   A top public works official and two street workers lost their
jobs and Pena suspended four others following the KUSA-TV report
last week about city street crews.
   The mayor, who announced the action over the weekend, said he
will continue his investigation of the allegations and within the
next week expects to discipline several mid-level supervisors in
the Public Works Department, the city's largest agency with 1,770
employees.
   Meanwhile, Marge Doty, chairwoman of the Metropolitan Action
Committee, which is pushing the Pena recall, said the revelations
have ``added impetus to our movement, absolutely.''
   The campaign has half the petition signatures needed to force an
election to replace Pena, who was re-elected to a second three-year
term last year. Ms. Doty said she has not counted how many
signatures have been gathered on the 1,200 petitions being
circulated.
   A KUSA reporter and cameraman, using an unmarked car, followed
six city street crews around for several days to see what they
accomplished. Only two crews were shown working without excessive
breaks. In one case, a pothole repair crew did no work at all
during an eight-hour period, spending the time visiting several
food stores and loafing near parks.
   Lee Ramirez, deputy manager of the Public Works Department,
resigned following the reports, and Pena then fired two workers and
suspended four others.
   Pena told a news conference that Ramirez was ``a hard-working
and dedicated employee'' who had ``the fortitude ... to tender his
resignation in the best interest of the city. And I agree with that
conclusion.''
   Steve Newman, executive director of the Colorado chapter of the
American Federation of State, County and Municipal Employees, said
two of the disciplined public works employees are innocent and
their punishments would be appealed.
   He also blamed the department's problems, which include a $1
million budget deficit, on poor management, nepotism, cronyism and
missing equipment.
   ``I will be meeting with the mayor this week, probably on
Thursday, and I will have a long list of documented problems and
incidents we've brought to their attention,'' he said. ``Hopefully,
this time he'll deal with it.''
   The movement to recall Pena began after citizens complained of
unplowed, impassable streets following a Christmas weekend
snowstorm.
   The Metropolitan Action Committee has until mid-April to collect
40,000 petition signatures.
   Gov. Roy Romer and three other Democratic leaders on Saturday
announced their opposition to the recall drive.
   ``Properly filling potholes'' is an issue worth debating, but
not serious enough to merit a recall election, the governor said.
   Sen. Tim Wirth, D-Colo., said Pena ``is the person who has
finally broken loose the airport and has made the convention center
come closer to being a reality. Those are the issues it seems to me
that we ought to be talking about.''
   Denver is close to reaching agreement to build a new, $4 billion
airport in neighboring Adams County to replace Stapleton
International Airport, and it will begin construction soon on a
$115 million convention center.
</TEXT>
