<HEAD>Grain Talks To Begin March 19 In Washington</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The opening talks on a new long-term grain
agreement between the United States and the Soviet Union will get
under way here on March 19 instead of in Vienna, Austria, on March
11 as previously announced, a senior trade official said Monday.
   Deputy U.S. Trade Representative Alan F. Holmer said in a
one-paragraph statement issued by the Agriculture Department that
the change was ``due to scheduling conflicts'' but did not
elaborate.
   The current five-year pact will expire on Sept. 30. It calls for
annual purchases of grain from the United States.
   Officials announced on March 4 that the negotiations on a new
agreement would begin March 11 in Vienna.
