<HEAD>52 Senators Urging Release Of South African Journalist</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fifty-two members of the Senate are urging
South African President P.W. Botha to release a prominent South
African journalist jailed without charges for the last 14 months.
   In a letter made public Monday, the senators asked Botha to work
for the immediate release of Zwalakhe Sisulu, 38, an award-winning
journalist and editor of the The New Nation, a newspaper sponsored
by the Catholic Church. Sisulu was a Nieman fellow at Harvard
University during the 1984-85 academic year.
   The letter was made public by Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass.,
who hailed Sisulu as ``the best that journalism has to offer'' and
a reporter and editor who is ``passionate in his commitment to
non-violence and to building a truly non-racial society in South
Africa.''
   ``His arrest and incarceration were unconscionable,'' Kennedy
said. ``His continued detention _ without bail, without charges and
without trial _ is indefensible.''
   The letter said that Sisulu's imprisonment ``strengthens the
cause of those who pursue a racial agenda and who seek a violent
solution to South Africa's problems.''
