<HEAD>Government Presents Artworks To Museum</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government Monday presented 25
photogravures seized from a now-imprisoned drug dealer to the
National Museum of American Art.
   The work by photographer Edward Sheriff Curtis, part of the
artist's 20-volume work on North American Indians, was turned over
to museum director Charles C. Eldredge by Attorney General Edwin
Meese III.
   The photographs printed from specially etched plates in a
process yielding great sensitivity of tone were among the items
confiscated from Ronald Francis Perry of San Francisco under a
federal law allowing the federal government to seize the assets of
drug traffickers.
   The photogravures were forfeited to the government after San
Francisco police investigating Perry discovered two pounds of
cocaine, a $30,000 art collection and $14,500 hidden in a secret
panel in a closet and took the case to the Drug Enforcement
Administration.
   Perry pleaded guilty to drug and tax charges in 1987 and is
serving a sentence in federal prison in Allenwood, Pa.
   The government is selling Perry's home and the remainder of his
property, which includes 75 cases of fine wine, eight rare Persian
carpets, several handguns, a Porsche and a Mercedes.
