<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0603,0478</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Guerrillas Ambush Vehicle near Subic, Kill Six</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS name to Nabua stead Nanua in 8th graf bgng: They
said they...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES W. HATTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist guerrillas ambushed a
vehicle near Subic Bay, killing three civilians and six Filipino
sailors assigned to the U.S.-run naval base, the military said
Monday.
   The sailors, and three civilians who had hitched a ride, were
traveling from Subic to Manila on Sunday when rebels of the New
People's Army fired on their Land-Rover near Hermosa, on the Bataan
Peninsula 40 miles west of the capital, the Philippine Constabulary
reported.
   There were no reports of rebel casualties in the 15-minute
battle.
   Subic, about 50 miles west of Manila, is one of six military
facilities operated by the United States under an executive
agreement that expires in 1991.
   Communist rebels operate near both Subic Bay and Clark Air Base,
50 miles north of Manila. Last October, guerrillas killed three
Americans and a Filipino in coordinated attacks outside Clark.
   In a related development Monday, two Philippine Constabulary
troopers held hostage by Communist rebels for more than a month
said they killed nine guerrillas in an escape the day before.
   Noel de Leon and Roberto Nabua said they were captured Feb. 3 at
a rebel checkpoint outside San Francisco, a town near Catanauan,
110 miles southeast of Manila in Quezon province. They spoke to
Filipino reporters in Catanauan.
   They said they were tied up for 32 days and were moved from
place to place. De Leon and Nabua also said a foreigner they did
not identify took videotape pictures of them.
   On Sunday, the two said, they loosened their bindings and
grabbed the M-16 rifles of their two guards, who were cooking a
meal in a house at Buenavista, about 10 miles north of Catanauan.
They said they killed both guards and seven other rebels.
   In another report Monday, officials said one of the best-known
rebel priests had fled southern Mindanao island after being shot by
comrades who learned he was planning to surrender.
   Romeo Capangpangan, spokesman in Cebu City for the Social
Welfare Department, said the Rev. Frank Navarro was reported shot
in the shoulder last week by his own followers in Mindanao's
Surigao del Sur province.
   He said Navarro had sent word that he was recuperating at a
hideout in the area and wanted to surrender in return for amnesty.
Cebu City is 360 miles southeast of Manila.
   The government amnesty program for Communist and Moslem rebels
expired Feb. 29, but Defense Secretary Fidel Ramos said rebels
still could receive amnesty on a case-by-case basis.
   According to the military, Navarro is a New People's Army leader
in eastern Mindanao. The army issued two reports last year that he
had been killed.
</TEXT>
