<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Kemp     03-07 0366</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kemp,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kemp Says He'll Stay in Race</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON JENKINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Jack Kemp said Monday he would press
on with his Republican presidential campaign regardless of the
outcome of the Super Tuesday contests.
   Kemp told a news conference at the state Capitol that his
disappointing showing in the race so far had not caused him to
consider dropping out.
   ``I'm running for ideas, for a cause, to keep the Reagan
revolution alive,'' he said.
   He said he did not know how he would do on Super Tuesday, but
thought the race would remain open. And he said he planned to press
his campaign in next week's Illinois primary.
   Kemp said he saw himself as ``a bridge candidate,'' whom
followers of Vice President George Bush, Kansas Sen. Bob Dole and
former television evangelist Pat Robertson all could turn to if the
race is not wrapped up by the time of the Republican National
Convention.
   ``I think ultimately that the Republican Party is going to want
a conservative to follow Ronald Reagan,'' he said.
   He repeated his assertion that he is not interested in the vice
presidential nomination.
   ``I don't expect it. I don't think it will be offered. I don't
want it. And besides, I'm a quarterback and not a lineman,'' said
the former professional football player.
   Kemp conceded that the oil and agriculture industries had not
shared fully in the economic successes of the Reagan
administration. But he said he did not favor an oil import fee,
calling that ``a quick fix.'' He said lower interest rates would
help the energy industry more in the long run.
   He also advocated repealing the windfall profits tax and called
for further deregulation of natural gas.
   In a speech to the Oklahoma Legislature prior to the news
conference, Kemp drew applause when he denounced Panamanian
strongman Manuel Antonio Noriega and called for continued support
of the Contras in Nicaragua.
   He said it would be ``a big mistake'' for the United States to
accept a communist base in Nicaragua. He said that would pose a
threat to the Panama Canal and Nicaragua's neighbors and
``ultimately to Mexico.''
</TEXT>
