<1ST_LINE>r i AM-ChilePresident     03-07 0228</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chile President,0235</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Military to Pick Presidential Candidate in June or July</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Navy chief Jose Toribio Merino said
Monday the nation's military commanders will select in June or July
the candidate for a yes-or-no presidential vote later this year.
   It was the first time a time frame has been set for the
nomination of the presidential candidate. No date has been set for
the election.
   President Augusto Pinochet, the general who has ruled Chile
since the 1973 coup that ousted the elected government of Marxist
President Salvador Allende, has given every indication he will seek
the nomination.
   As the powerful army commander, the 72-year-old Pinochet will be
among the four military chieftains selecting the candidate for an
eight-year term.
   Merino spoke with reporters after a meeting of the law-making,
four-member junta that he heads.
   He said the presidential election ``has to take place during the
second half'' of this year.
   According to the 1980 constitution drafted by the armed forces,
Chile's president for the 1989-97 term will be chosen in a
yes-or-no plebiscite on a single candidate.
   The candidate will be named by the commanders of the army, navy,
air force and national police.
   If the military-picked candidate is rejected by the voters, an
open presidential election must be called in 1990 with Pinochet
remaining in power until then, according to the constitution.
</TEXT>
