<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LiuKilling     03-07 0375</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Liu Killing,0385</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trial Starts In Journalist's Death</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE CARPENTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>REDWOOD CITY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jury selection began Monday in a
trial of a Taiwanese gangster accused of killing a Chinese-American
journalist openly critical of the Taiwanese government.
   Tung Kuei-sen has pleaded innocent in the 1984 shooting of Henry
Liu at the writer's Daly City home.
   The plea puzzled his attorney, since the 35-year-old Tung
testified two years ago in a New York drug trial that he and a
fellow member of Taiwan's largest criminal syndicate, the United
Bamboo gang, gunned down Liu on government orders relayed by gang
chief Chen Chi-Li.
   ``I suspect he just wants to tell the jury and everyone else his
story,'' said defense attorney Douglas Gray. ``He thought he was
doing his government's bidding ... and he was left twisting slowly,
slowly in the wind.''
   Prosecutor Robert Bishop said he expects the trial before San
Mateo County Superior Court Judge Margaret Kemp to last two weeks
and he will call up to 18 witnesses. Gray said he was unsure how he
would present his case.
   Tung faces one count of murder and one special allegation that
he used a gun in the Oct. 15, 1984, slaying. If convicted, he could
face 27 years to life in prison.
   Tung was convicted of heroin smuggling after a federal trial in
New York in 1986 and was sentenced to 20 years in prison.
   Liu, a long-term critic of the Taiwanese government, was a
columnist for a Chinese-language newspaper in San Francisco and had
just published a book that attacked the island nation's ruling
party when he was killed.
   The U.S. Congress and the State Department condemned Liu's
murder and House hearings were held to look into the murky
circumstances surrounding it.
   Chen has blamed the killing on Taiwan's former chief of military
intelligence, Vice Admiral Wang Shi-ling, who said he only directed
that Liu be taught ``a lesson.''
   Both Chen and Wang are serving life sentences in Taiwan after
being convicted in the killing in a Taiwanese military court. Two
intelligence officials who served under Wang are serving lesser
terms.
   Wu Tun, 35, the second gunman, is serving a life term for the
killing in a Taiwan prison.
</TEXT>
