<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BearAttack     03-07 0408</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bear Attack,0421</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Investigators Head to Mansfield to Probe Bear Attack</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN W. CHALFANT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 300-pound bear that mauled a 2-year-old
boy in a shopping mall was under quarantine Monday, as federal
investigators began a probe into the animal's keepers, authorities
said.
   Kevin E. Kuhn of Galion was listed in fair condition at
Children's Hospital with deep cuts to his scalp and face that
required more than 100 stitches, officials said.
   He was attacked Saturday while posing with the Himalayan bear,
named Fluffy, after a children's performance at a shopping mall in
Mansfield, about 60 miles north of Columbus.
   The bear was held at an undisclosed location, said Joe Evans,
director of environmental health services for the Richland County
Health Department. The bear's owners had not sought return of the
animal, and Evans indicated the county would resist any efforts to
return the bear.
   ``We will fight that, if necessary,'' he said. ``We have had
some contact with the owners and indicated our intent ... to take
over custody of the animal until we can find a more permanent
disposition.''
   The county might seek to destroy the animal, but that has not
been determined, he said.
   U.S. Department of Agriculture investigators arrived in
Mansfield on Monday to look into the attack, police Capt. John
Arcudi said. Owners of exotic animals must register with the
Agriculture Department.
   ``At this time, I don't know what criminal charges could be
filed,'' Arcudi said. ``It's more civil than criminal.''
   Fluffy is one of four bears featured in the ``Goldilocks and Her
Bears'' shopping-center attraction. A bear named Fluffy in the same
troupe clawed a Jacksonville, Fla., 4-year-old during a show last
month, police said.
   That child required at least six stiches, police said, and the
bear was quarantined five days before being released to its owner,
Walter Naghtin Sr., 54, of Tampa, Fla.
   It was unclear whether the same bear was involved in both
attacks, authorities said.
   In the Jacksonville case, Naghtin and his son, Walter Naghtin
Jr., were charged for allowing wild animals to perform without a
permit, police said. They pleaded guilty and were fined and
sentenced to six months' probation.
   Permits were obtained for the Mansfield performance, police said.
   Efforts to reach the Naghtins Monday were unsuccessful. Ruth
Naghtin of Northbrook, Ill., who identified herself as the mother
of the elder Naghtin, said she did not know where they were.
</TEXT>
