<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Reagan-NearCollision     03-07 0471</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Near Collision,0485</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Private Involved In Near-Collision With Reagan Sentenced</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Army private who was piloting an airplane
that came close to President Reagan's helicopter last year over
Southern California was ordered to spend 30 weekends in jail Monday
for making false statements about the incident.
   Ralph William Myers, 33, of Fort Lewis, Wash., was convicted of
lying to authorities about the reason he strayed into prohibited
airspace in his rented plane Aug. 13, 1987, at the same time the
president was heading to his hilltop ranch north of Santa Barbara.
   Despite a Probation Department recommendation of probation, U.S.
District Judge Manuel L. Real sentenced Myers to three years in
jail for each of two counts of making false statements. Real then
suspended all but 60 days of the jail time.
   In addition to the suspended sentence and five years' probation,
the judge ordered Myers to donate 1,000 hours to charitable service.
   Myers' jail time will begin April 9 and is not to interfere with
his military service, the judge said. The maximum sentence Myers
could have received was 10 years in jail and a $500,000 fine.
   Myers told the judge he ``cannot justify or condone statements I
made last August. I apologize to the government agencies involved.''
   Outside the courtroom, Myers said he was a scapegoat for federal
government mishandling of his aircraft. ``I haven't gotten a fair
trial since day one because of the hysteria surrounding the near
miss of Marine One,'' he said. ``There was not a near miss.''
   According to the president's Marine pilot, Lt. Col. Michael
Glynn, Myers' plane came passed about 200 feet in front of the
helicopter and 150 feet below it. Myers maintains his plane was no
closer than 800 to 1,000 feet from Marine One.
   His attorney, Manuel Araujo, said they will appeal the sentence.
   Myers was demoted a private's pay grade for being AWOL. He still
has 18 months left to serve in the U.S. Army.
   Myers, and a passenger, Oregon businessman Harlan Lee Jones,
were arrested at John Wayne Airport in Orange County. Marine
helicopters, which had been escorting the president's Marine One,
chased the Piper Cherokee to the airport, but authorities said
Myers seemed unaware that he was being followed.
   Myers told Secret Service and Federal Aviation Administration
agents he was looking for a lost contact lens in the airplane's
cabin when he strayed into the prohibited airspace. He also claimed
he was unaware the airspace was restricted.
   A day later, he admitted he had lied about the lens.
   Myers, who had been absent without leave from the Army since
Aug. 3, 1987, said he lied because he was confused about the entire
situation. ``I was trying to stay out of more trouble,'' he
explained in court documents.
</TEXT>
