<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Test-TubeQuints     03-07 0323</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Test-Tube Quints,0330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three Of Test-Tube Quints Leave Hospital</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto DT5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GRETEL WIKLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROYAL OAK, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Raymond and Michele L'Esperance took
three of their quintuplet babies home from the hospital Monday,
saying they were eager to begin family life with the in-vitro
infants.
   Raymond Jr., Danielle and Erica L'Esperance and their parents
rode away from William Beaumont Hospital in a white limousine
decorated with silver balloons as a crowd of doctors, nurses,
hospital administrators and reporters watched.
   The babies, born Jan. 11, were the first quintuplets born in the
United States after being conceived through in-vitro fertilization,
which involves fertilizing ovum in the laboratory and implanting
the embryos in the womb.
   The other two babies, Veronica and Alexandria, who were placed
on respirators at birth, remain in the hospital. They are off the
respirators now and are expected to be released in a few weeks,
said Dr. Daniel Batton, director of newborn medicine at Beaumont.
   ``They still require special attention and monitoring,'' Batton
said. ``But we expect those problems will resolve in the next
couple of weeks, and we don't anticipate any problems.''
   Looking ahead to the task of raising five babies at one time,
the couple said they are ready to take the infants to their new
house in Clarkston and let them join their three other children as
a family.
   ``We are pleased and overjoyed to have three of our babies going
home,'' said L'Esperance, a corrections officer with the Macomb
County Sheriff's Department.
   ``We can't wait to have the other two home. We'll just start
getting down to being a family.''
   The babies that left the hospital have gained about 3 pounds
each in the eight weeks since their birth. Raymond left Beaumont
weighing 4 pounds, 9 ounces; Danielle weighed 6 pounds, 6 ounces;
and Erica weighed 5 pounds, 14 ounces, said Pamela Wells, nursing
director in the in-vitro fertilization program at Beaumont.
</TEXT>
