<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Jackson 1stLd-Writethru a0721 03-07 0627</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0721,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede BROWNSVILLE</HEAD>
<HEAD>Jackson Campaigns In Texas On Eve Of Super Tuesday</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE; picks up 3rd graf pvs, Jackson
pledged</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson said Monday he's going into the
Super Tuesday elections as an underdog, but thinks he'll do very
well nonetheless.
   ``I don't have a crystal ball,'' he said when asked how many
delegates he might pick up in the day's balloting.
   Jackson pointed to the ``high-tech, well-financed operation'' of
Democratic presidential rival Michael Dukakis.
   ``He has money; I have the message and the grass-roots approach.
It will be interesting to see how these concepts play out,'' he
said.
   Jackson made the comments in an interviw aboard his campaign
plane flying from an airport rally in Laredo to a rally at the
University of Houston.
   As he campaigned on the eve of Super Tuesday, Jackson said Texas
has shaped up to a fight between himself and Dukakis. He also
contended his message has become part of the political mainstream.
   ``When one takes a serious look at my positions, they are very
central to the broad-based American point of view,'' he said.
   Earlier, Jackson visited an AIDS clinic in Dallas and told a
rally in Brownsville: ``I'll be your friend in Washington.''
   Jackson pledged to fight against proposals to make English the
official language of the United States.
   ``We are a great nation. We can speak more than one language.
... Two-thirds of the hemisphere speaks Spanish. We should grow and
speak more languages, have broader culture,'' he said.
   Jackson donned a sombrero and the popular Latin-style shirt
called a guayaberra as he addressed the mixed-race outdoor
gathering where several people waved red United Farm Worker flags.
   Jackson recalled his visit to Brownsville of several weeks ago
when he went into the broccoli fields where there are no portable
lavatories for the field workers.
   UFW organizer Juanita Valdez said that Jackson should get a lot
of farm worker support because ``he came to help us.''
   After Jackson's visit, she said, the state health director
called a meeting to find out why the sanitary laws were not being
enforced in the field.
   ``You need a friend in the White House,'' Jackson said. ``I'm
your friend in Brownsville. I'll be your friend in Washington.''
   Jackson was accompanied by former New Mexico Gov. Toney Anaya,
who addressed the gathering in Spanish, Texas Agriculture
Commissioner Jim Hightower, prominent feminist leader Sissy
Farenthold and Tennessee politician John J. Hooker.
   One man in the crowd, Carlos Martinez, said he was supporting
Jackson because Jackson cares about the Mexican-American problems
and the poor people. Martinez said the once-bustling port of
Brownsville ``is dead'' and that he had been laid off a few years
back from both Marathon and Pyramid oil companies.
   ``We're just about forgotten about down here and the economy is
really bad. We're looking for a change,'' he said.
   Hightower said the Southern region is the second-most depressed
part of Texas after Laredo, where Jackson headed later in the day.
   Earlier he visited with dying men in an AIDS clinic in Dallas.
   Several onlookers said that Jackson and Democratic rival Michael
Dukakis will likely split the Democratic vote in this area.
Dukakis, who speaks fluent Spanish, has been pushing hard for the
Hispanic vote and visited neighboring Harlingen a week ago.
   But county commissioner candidate Gilberto Villarreal, a Jackson
supporter, said, ``Speaking Spanish or marrying a Hispanic does not
give you the heart of a Hispanic.'' He said that while Dukakis has
done ``tremendous work in Massachusetts,'' Jackson has the heart of
a Hispanic. ``He came up from the grass roots. He has not forgotten
what it is to be poor,'' he said.
</TEXT>
