<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Wedtech-Biaggi     03-07 0403</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wedtech-Biaggi,0416</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jury Selection Begins in Biaggi-Wedtech Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ALAN HARPER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jury selection began Monday in the Wedtech Corp.
racketeering case involving Rep. Mario Biaggi, with 48 candidates
being excused and 58 others asked to return.
   Last week, 94 potential jurors were excused for hardship
reasons, leaving 106 who had filled out a 63-item questionnaire
about their feelings and who they might know involved in the case.
   On Monday, U.S. District Court Judge Constance Baker Motley
excused 48 candidates based upon their answers while 58 were asked
to return Tuesday, either to be requestioned or to appear for the
first time.
   The jurors will have to decide the fate of Biaggi, his eldest
son, former Bronx Borough President Stanley Simon and four
co-defendants, who are accused of turning the Wedtech Corp. into a
``vehicle for making illegal payments to public officials.''
   The seven are charged with participating in a racketeering
enterprise that allegedly looted millions of dollars in stock and
cash from Wedtech, a Bronx defense contractor now in bankruptcy
proceedings.
   All are charged with racketeering and conspiracy, each carrying
a maximum 20-year penalty upon conviction. Biaggi also is accused
of extortion, bribe-receiving, wire fraud, perjury and filing false
tax returns, and the other defendants also face various other
charges.
   Wedtech was a small, Bronx machine shop that grew into a
multimillion- dollar-a-year defense contractor. It rose through a
Small Business Administration program that allowed minority-owned
firms to obtain government contracts without competitive bidding.
   A number of federal, state and local inquiries are looking into
allegations of bribery, influence peddling and other wrongdoing.
   Asked about one of his responses to the questionnaire, a
potential juror, Joseph C. Siragusi, told Mrs. Motley he had
problems with the concept of programs set up especially to help
minorities and women.
   When Mrs. Motley further explained the concept to him, Siragusi
said: ``Under that circumstance, I wouldn't consider it unfair.''
   When there were no objections from defense and government
attorneys, Mrs. Motley ruled there was no reason to excuse
Siragusi. He will be reinterviewed Tuesday.
   Raymond Joseph Sullivan, another jury candidate from the Bronx,
was asked if he had stated on the questionnaire that he opposed
programs helping minorities.
   ``Sure did,'' Sullivan said. ``I have four children. I wouldn't
want to see them denied a job.''
   Sullivan was asked to return when court resumes at 9:30 a.m.
Tuesday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
