<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Nicaragua-PeaceTalks     03-07 0463</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua-Peace Talks,0477</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cardinal, OAS Official Agree to Witness Truce Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FILADELFO ALEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cardinal Miguel Obando y Bravo and the
secretary-general of the Organization of American States agreed to
be witnesses at talks between the government and Contra rebels, a
presidential communique said Monday.
   The agreement by Joao Baena Soares, the OAS official, and Obando
y Bravo, Roman Catholic archbishop of Managua, appeared to ease the
way for truce negotiations starting Wednesday in Sapoa, on the
border with Costa Rica about 90 miles from Managua.
   President Daniel Ortega last week said the cardinal was no
longer needed as a mediator in talks with the U.S.-backed rebels.
Obando y Bravo had served as a go-between since last November at
government request.
   The Contras insisted the cardinal be a witness, and the talks
had appeared to be in jeopardy.
   Ortega sent letters this week to Obando y Bravo and Baena Soares
asking them to serve as witnesses, the government's Voice of
Nicaragua radio said Monday.
   No one answered the telephone at the headquarters of the
Washington-based OAS.
   Contra leader Adolfo Calero earlier Monday accused the
government of ``preparing a unilateral show'' rather than planning
for the talks.
   In a telephone interview from Miami, Calero complained that the
leftist Sandinistas had not responded to a Contra demand that
Obando y Bravo be present ``as witness, moderator and guarantor of
the talks.''
   Ortega said last week that the three days of talks would be
headed by his brother, Humberto Ortega, the defense minister and
one of nine members on the ruling National Directorate. Acceding to
a Contra demand, he said the talks would be held in Nicaragua and
suggested the Sapoa site.
   The Contras accepted and named Calero to head their delegation,
but said the cardinal must attend.
   Calero said the Contras received no word from the government
about security arrangements or the agenda.
   The government says the talks should center on laying down arms
as outlined in the regional peace plan signed last August by the
presidents of Nicaragua, El Salvador, Guatemala, Costa Rica and
Honduras.
   The rebels want a proposal outlined by the cardinal last month
to be included.
   His agenda called for the government to grant total amnesty to
political prisoners, review a mandatory military draft law, allow
full press freedom and renew a dialogue with its internal
opposition. In return, Contras were to accept a 30-day cease-fire.
   ``We haven't received any response to our position of last
Thursday ... which included these items,'' Calero said.
   ``We said clearly then that we accept the high-level meeting to
discuss the cardinal's agenda and that we had agreed with the
preliminary details of the meeting, but we haven't had a response
from the Sandinista government,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
