<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dukakis 3rdLd-Writethru a0830 03-07 0572</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0830,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Campaigns in Florida, Carolina, TV Studios</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: DELETES 5th graf pvs, which extraneous</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MORRISVILLE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Don't let them tell you this is a
television campaign,'' Massachusetts Gov. Michael S. Dukakis said
Monday as he raced through a final day of pre-Super Tuesday
campaigning.
   Still, Dukakis packed 21 television interviews into his final
day of stumping before Tuesday's primaries and caucuses in 20
states _ including 14 Southern and border states.
   He campaigned in person Monday in Miami and the Tampa area, then
traveled to an evening rally in the Raleigh-Durham area of North
Carolina before a scheduled flight back to Boston.
   ``If we can emerge from Super Tuesday with the lead in terms of
delegates, we'll be on our way to the nomination,'' he said.
   Dukakis kicked off the day of campaigning in Miami, perhaps his
most solid base of support in the South.
   At a senior citizens rally, Dukakis picked up the valued
endorsement of 74-year-old Annie Ackerman, who has a reputation in
Miami for being able to get out the vote.
   ``You have come out to listen to the man who will be the next
president of the United States,'' Ackerman said. She spoke of
Dukakis' immigrant roots, something he had in common with many of
those at the rally.
   ``My mother would have said he's a mensch,'' she said, referring
to the Yiddish word for good man. ``He's a person of integrity who
gets things done.''
   Ackerman, a former ward organizer for the late Chicago Mayor
Richard Daley, met with several of the presidential candidates but
decided on Dukakis after a straw poll of the residents of her
condominium complex.
   Dukakis traveled from Miami to Plant City to attend a strawberry
festival and also marched in a parade with Florida Attorney General
Robert Butterworth at his side on Monday.
   He planned to vote in his hometown of Brookline, Mass., Tuesday
morning, spend the day at his Statehouse office and then fly to
Chicago to begin campaigning for the Illinois primary.
   Throughout his Southern campaign swing, nearly all of Dukakis'
stops have come in areas where he is expected to win. The strategy
seems to be to reinforce areas of strength rather than seek new
support.
   ``There are only so many hours in a day _ you can't go
everywhere,'' the Massachusetts governor has repeatedly said.
   Asked whether the Super Tuesday primaries were a flop in
attracting moderate and conservative Democrats, Dukakis said,
``It's not been a flop for Mike Dukakis. I don't understand what
the labels mean.''
   Dukakis has not talked much about his opponents. He has
continued to criticize Missouri Rep. Richard Gephardt, seen by many
as his principal rival, but such comments have only come with
prompting from reporters.
   He said he is worried that the negative campaigning between him
and Gephardt is hurting the chances for the Democratic party in
November. In response to a barb from Gephardt criticizing the
Dukakis attacks, he said, ``No, I don't think I've impugned his
integrity.''
   Meanwhile, in Boston, 20 protesters were arrested outside
Dukakis' Statehouse office on trespassing charges as they staged a
sit-in to demand an immediate increase in welfare benefits.
   Most of the protesters went limp when told to leave the
building, so police had to lift them into nearby elevators.
   ``While he's out stumping, our kids are starving,'' one
protester shouted.
</TEXT>
