<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Obit-Samkange     03-07 0225</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Samkange,0233</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Author-Politician Stanlake Samkange Dead</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stanlake Samkange, an author and
politician who fought for independence for Zimbabwe, died in Harare
of heart and lung ailments after a long illness, his widow said
Monday. He was 65.
   Tommie-Marie Samkange said her husband died Sunday.
   Samkange was the first black college graduate in the province of
Mashonaland in 1947 when Zimbabwe was the white-ruled British
colony of Rhodesia. He received a bachelor's degree with honors in
history.
   As a black nationalist, he held top posts in the next three
decades in several political parties including Joshua Nkomo's
Zimbabwe African People's Union and Bishop Abel Muzorewa's United
African National Council.
   Samkange retired from politics in 1979, the year when a
British-sponsored accord provided for independence for Zimbabwe and
rule by the black majority.
   Robert Mugabe's Zimbabwe African National Union won the March
1980 elections and Mugabe became prime minister. Mugabe and Nkomo
had led rebel armies in guerrilla warfare against white domination.
   Samkange also worked as a free-lance journalist and wrote three
books on politics in Africa. He received a master of science degree
from Syracuse University in New York.
   After retiring he opened a publishing house.
   His wife said burial will be Saturday at the family farm at
Msengezi near Harare and a memorial service will be held Friday in
Harare.
</TEXT>
