<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Suicide     03-07 0215</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Suicide,0222</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Funeral For Man Who Burned Self to Death Draws Other Unemployed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WORKSOP, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jobless streetsweeper who set himself
afire near Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's residence was buried
Monday at a service attended by relatives, friends and about 100
unemployed Britons.
   Derek Bainbridge, 41, burned to death in his car parked 40 yards
from Mrs. Thatcher's Downing Street residence on Feb. 16.
   He had been unemployed for 18 months and left a suicide note
saying, ``Too young to retire, too old to live.''
   His family invited unemployed people to attend the funeral in
Bainbridge's hometown of Worksop in central England 180 miles from
London.
   Steven Brown said he came to the burial with other jobless
people ``because I can understand what Derek Bainbridge went
through. People can't understand how you feel having to pay for
rent, gas and electricity when you don't have a job.''
   The Rev. Brian Hunt, who presided at the service, said prayers
for the unemployed and ``for those who are going through
depression, frustration and anger.''
   Britain's unemployment has doubled from 1.3 million in 1979,
when Mrs. Thatcher won her first of three terms in office, to 2.6
million in December. The government has said that was a seasonably
adjusted 9.4 percent of the work force.
</TEXT>
