<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0782 03-07 0525</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0782,000</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Confident Bush Predicts Victory In Oklahoma, Nationwide</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS grafs 4-5 with Arkansas appearance</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GIL BROYLES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TULSA, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush said Monday ``the
person that clearly wins Super Tuesday is going to be the nominee
of the party'' as he coasted on polls that gave him a big lead in
most of the 17 GOP contests.
   Bush stopped short of forecasting a sweep on Tuesday.
   ``You always wish for that but I certainly would never predict
that. It's too much for anyone to expect,'' he said earlier in the
day.
   At his last public appearance of the day, in Rogers, Ark., the
vice president said he was ``optimistic but not overconfident.''
   Asked what he'd do if he didn't win Super Tuesday, he replied:
``I'll have to do what I did when I got kicked in Iowa _ get up off
the canvas, go out and fight hard.'' After his third-place finish
in Iowa, Bush went on to a solid win in the New Hampshire primary
eight days later.
   In a two-hour stop at Tulsa International Airport, he told a
rally that Super Tuesday constitutes ``the most historic political
event in modern political history.''
   ``It's critical,'' he said. ``The person that clearly wins Super
Tuesday is going to be the nominee of the party and I think the
next president.''
   Bush, introduced by Gov. Henry Bellmon at the rally, later
toured the American Airlines Maintenance and Engineering facility
at the airport and took a moment to turn a wrench on an engine.
   Bush appeared tired at a 15-minute news conference following a
brisk walking tour of the sprawling facility.
   The vice president dismissed the possibility of a brokered
convention.
   ``We're talking about victory and he's talking about brokering
something,'' he said. ``I don't see it happening. I think there are
so many events that I think the Republican nominee will be
determined before the convention.''
   Bush was asked about negative ads that he called ``comparative''
spots criticizing Dole's record in the Senate.
   ``When attacked, you'll see some retaliation,'' Bush said. ``But
when you look at the totality and how it all came about, I think
people understand that a person has a right to, in a laser-like
fashion, go after them. I think actually the factual back-up of
those ads is pretty irrefutable.''
   Bush, a former oilman, said he feels ``compatible with the base
of this state.'' But he said he cannot support a tax on imported
oil as a means of shoring up the ailing domestic energy business.
   ``I was in the oil business, and I remember what it was like to
have government controls, allocations of markets and regulation.
And who hated it the worst? The oil industry,'' Bush said.
   ``That also has an artificial, inflationary built-in premise to
it. Everybody's costs go up. It's like any other tax. And I'm
opposed to raising taxes. The industry is split on the oil import
fee. I don't happen to be in favor of it. I think what I propose,
including a tax credit for exploration ... is the way to go.''
</TEXT>
