<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Mecham-Criminal     03-07 0524</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mecham-Criminal,0539</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prosecution Seeks Delay in Mecham Criminal Trial</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Mecham, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURIE ASSEO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prosecutors Monday sought a one-month
delay in Gov. Evan Mecham's criminal trial for allegedly concealing
a $350,000 campaign loan, while defense lawyers said the charges
should be dismissed.
   Maricopa County Superior Court Judge Michael Ryan said he would
rule on the delay motion, which was opposed by the defense,
Wednesday or Thursday. He did not say when he would rule on a
series of defense motions brought Monday.
   Delays in pretrial procedures sought by the defense have left
too little time for prosecutors to prepare, said Assistant Attorney
General Barnett Lotstein. He sought to change the trial starting
date from March 22 to April 21.
   ``The governor's political agenda has no place in this
courtroom,'' Lotstein told Ryan. ``He wants a speedy trial. We want
a trial after the rules have been complied with.''
   Defense attorney Michael Scott argued against a delay in the
trial, adding, ``We want to resolve this matter and put it behind
us.''
   In an indictment handed up Jan. 8, the governor was charged with
six felony counts of fraud, perjury and filing false documents in
his failure to disclose a $350,000 campaign loan. His brother and
1986 campaign manager, Willard Mecham, faces three similar counts.
   Mecham's Senate impeachment trial went into its second week
Monday, and he also faces a May 17 recall election.
   Defense attorneys filed a series of motions Monday seeking:
   _ Dismissal or a new determination of the charges' validity, on
several grounds including a claim that people who had a definite
stance on the Mecham recall movement were unfairly excluded from
the grand jury.
   The motion said the indictments should be dismissed ``because
both those who favored the recall and those who opposed the recall
were blanketly excluded from the grand jury without any regard'' to
their ability to make a fair decision.
   _ Dismissal of the charges on grounds the Mechams were victims
of selective prosecution.
   The motion claimed that other public figures, including state
lawmakers such as former House Majority Leader Burton Barr and
current House Minority Leader Art Hamilton, were not prosecuted
when it was found that they had omitted items from their financial
disclosure statements.
   ``Not only was Governor Mecham not given a written opportunity
to file an amended return, his protestations of oversight and
avowals of no criminal intent fell upon deaf ears,'' the motion
said. ``Why? Because the political turmoil surrounding his nine
months in office threatened to destroy the power and influence the
Republican Party had spent more than 20 years nurturing and
cultivating.''
   _ A change of venue because of massive pretrial publicity, and
separate questioning of prospective jurors in an effort to see that
they are not biased.
   _ Separate trials for Evan and Willard Mecham, who now are
scheduled to be tried together.
   Ryan also took under advisement a defense motion to dismiss two
of the counts against Willard Mecham and four of the counts against
the governor. The defense claimed the grand jury did not have
jurisdiction to bring those charges.
</TEXT>
