<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Obit-Hermit     03-07 0304</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Hermit,0312</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Hermit of Chestnut Hill' Found Dead</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A homeless man who gained national recognition for
his refusal to abandon his makeshift camp on state-owned land was
found dead in his hut Monday by his children, police said. Bill
Britt was 52.
   Britt's badly decomposed body was found by his son and daughter
in his hut about 30 feet from the fence surrounding the Evergreen
Cemetery in Boston's Brighton district, spokesman Scott Gillis said.
   Britt, born Britton William Boughner in the affluent
neighborhood near the state-owned land, had lived at the reservoir
near Boston College since 1969.
   ``In his case, he felt that this was where he wanted to live,
this was his estate,'' said Clyde Raymond, a friend of Britt's.
``He died free, so to speak. He had his own drummer and he stuck
with it.''
   Britt, who was known as the ``hermit of Chestnut Hill,'' had
been dead for several months and his body, dressed in multiple
layers of clothing, was almost reduced to skeletal, Gillis said.
   An autopsy was performed on Britt in an attempt to determine the
cause of death, but results weren't expected until Tuesday, Gillis
said.
   In 1985, officials started trying to move Britt from the
Metropolitan District Commission land in the Chestnut Hill district
on the Boston-Brookline border.
   Britt, who was legally blind, lived on money he earned redeeming
can and bottle deposits. He refused welfare and several attempts to
relocate him to public or subsidized housing.
   In May, Britt's plastic and wood wigwam was destroyed in a fire
while he was in New York City to appear on the ``Late Night with
David Letterman'' television show. He rebuilt it, despite
deteriorating health. Doctors said Britt, who was nearly toothless,
had ulcers and needed a corneal transplant.
</TEXT>
