<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TrooperTrial     03-07 0305</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Trooper Trial,0312</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Refuses To Dismiss Indictment In Trooper Murder Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SELMA, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge Monday refused to dismiss an
indictment or delay the murder trial of a former state trooper
accused of killing a fellow officer in her patrol car.
   Circuit Judge J.C. Norton rejected the defense motions as jury
selection opened in the trial of Joseph Cecil Duncan, 33, who is
charged with shooting Elizabeth Cobb, 31, three times in the head
at close range.
   Miss Cobb's body was found Oct. 12 in her patrol car near a
rural Dallas County church. The FBI has said Miss Cobb was the
first female state trooper in the nation to be slain on duty.
Duncan attended her funeral and was charged in the case later.
   Authorities say Duncan was the beneficiary of a $250,000
insurance policy on the victim's life. Duncan has pleaded innocent
and says he and Miss Cobb planned to marry.
   Jury selection was expedited Monday when the judge declined to
grant a defense motion to question potential jurors individually
rather than have members of the jury pool answer general questions
put to all.
   The defense had argued that the state destroyed evidence that
might have been significant to the defense. The evidence in
question was the bullets from a .22-caliber pistol found in a black
Trans-Am.
   At one point after Miss Cobb disappeared on patrol, officers
issued a bulletin for a black Trans Am that reportedly had been
chased by Miss Cobb's patrol car in Dallas County.
   Defense attorney Henry Pitts said a Texas drifter named Charlie
Shoemaker is being held on drug charges in Okaloosa County, Fla.,
and is the man who was driving the black Trans-Am.
   But Assistant Attorney General William Wasden said Monday that
prosecution witnesses will show Shoemaker is not involved in the
shooting.
</TEXT>
