<FILEID>AP-NR-03-07-88 2246EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Nicaragua-US     03-07 0284</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua-US,0292</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sandinistas Hold Onto $20,000 in U.S. Embassy Money</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leftist Sandinista government
withheld nearly $20,000 belonging to the U.S. Embassy and its
employees when they turned in their money in a currency exchange,
an embassy source said Monday.
   The source, who spoke on condition he not be further identified,
said the embassy turned 208 million old cordobas in to the
government in exchange for new ones in accordance with last month's
economic measures.
   The total, which included private money and embassy funds, was
worth about $20,800.
   The government last month created a new cordoba worth 1,000
times more than the old one and pegged it at 10 to the U.S. dollar.
   The government set an exchange limit of 10 million in cordobas
per person or institution, or the equivalent of $1,000. The U.S.
Embassy was given $1,000, and the rest was withheld.
   According to the new law, the remainder should be put in a bank
account, where it is converted to the new currency but frozen. An
embassy spokesman said Monday the embassy had no information
whether that occurred.
   A Central Bank spokeswoman said she had no information on the
U.S. Embassy account, but confirmed that the money should have been
put in an account.
   The embassy source said the Sandinistas asked for proof that the
cordobas turned over by the Americans were obtained legally in
Nicaragua. Exchange houses issue receipts for dollars turned into
cordobas. The government did not require such receipts from
individuals changing their currency.
   ``I don't know if we have receipts for everybody,'' the embassy
source said. ``I know I always throw mine out.''
   Embassy spokesman Lou Falino said: ``We have no comment.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
