<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-SpyTrial     03-07 0298</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Spy Trial,0305</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trial Begins for Businessman Accused of Being a Soviet Spy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Israeli businessman with reported links to
Israeli politicians and army officers went on trial Monday accused
of being a spy for the Soviet Union, his lawyer said.
   Shabtai Kalmanovich, 46, who emigrated to Israel from the Soviet
Union in 1971, denied the charges, according to defense attorney
Amnon Zichroni.
   He said the Tel Aviv District Court hearing the case barred him
from further comment. The trial is being held behind closed doors
and Zichroni said it is expected to last about seven months.
   Kalmanovich has been in custody since his arrest Dec. 23.
   Israel television has described Kalmanovich as an international
businessman with interests in Africa who ``employed hundreds of
people throughout the world, among them former Israeli (Cabinet)
ministers and reserve officers.''
   The Jan. 10 report said, ``Among his friends were members of the
Knesset (parliament), high-ranking politicians and senior army
reserve officers.'' It did not give any names.
   Kalmanovich was born in Lithuania and after his arrival in
Israel he served in the army and then worked briefly as an aide to
former Israeli legislator Shmuel Flatto-Sharon.
   The television report said Kalmanovich had connections with
people involved in East-West spy swaps in the 1970s. It said that
in August 1977, Kalmanovich traveled to East Germany and met with
Wolfgang Vogel, an East German lawyer who mediated such exchanges.
   In April 1978, Kalmanovich helped bring about the release of an
Israeli prisoner from a jail in Mozambique, according to the
television account. It said that in the same month, East Germany
released an American student and the United States freed Robert G.
Thompson who had been convicted of passing secrets to the Soviets.
</TEXT>
