<HEAD>Actor `Divine' Dies In Sleep In Los Angeles Hotel Room</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 6th graf, `West said...', to CORRECT that `Married ...
With Children,' on Fox Network sted syndicated; SUBS 11th graf,
`Milstead played...', to delete reference to `Trouble in Mind'
being only other non-transvestite role.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY42</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Harris Glenn Milstead, known to moviegoers as
Divine, the campy, 300-pound transvestite star of such films as
``Pink Flamingos'' and ``Hairspray,'' died in his sleep in a hotel
room, the coroner's office said Monday. He was 42.
   Los Angeles County Coroner spokesman Steve Stewart said
investigators went to the Regency Plaza Hotel on Hollywood
Boulevard, where Milstead was a guest when he died during the
night. ``The cause of death is under investigation,'' Stewart said.
   Milstead apparently died of asphyxiation, said spokesman John
West of PMK Public Relations.
   ``He was finally getting respect within the industry,'' said
Milstead's manager, Bernard Jay. ``He was getting the legitimate
screen and television offers that showed the industry had finally
accepted him as the very good character actor he always knew he
was.''
   Milstead got a medical checkup last Friday and was declared in
excellent health, other than his weight, ``which has been a
constant problem throughout his life,'' said Jay.
   West said Milstead, star of the latest John Waters-directed
movie ``Hairspray,'' was in Los Angeles to appear in an episode of
the Fox Network television series ``Married ... With Children.''
   Milstead was to have appeared in that role dressed as a man, but
he was best known to movie fans as the bizarre female impersonating
star of such cult classic films as ``Pink Flamingos,'' ``Lust In
The Dust,'' ``Polyester'' and ``Female Trouble.''
   The Divine character was garishly made up and outrageously
chesty, as well as loud, raucous and foul-mouthed. Milstead's
appearance made the first Waters films a favorite for
after-midnight showings at arty cinema houses.
   But with each film, both Milstead and Waters found a wider
audience, and ``Hairspray'' has enjoyed a good following as well as
flattering reviews, coming in No. 16 this weekend in the box office
with $577,258 at 79 theaters for a $7,307 per screen average.
   In the film, set in the early 1960s, he plays the mother of a
chubby teen-age girl who becomes a teen television dance star and
pioneer integrationist. Dressed as a man, he also plays a
segregationist television station manager.
   In another non-transvestite role, Milstead played a Sydney
Greenstreet-type character in the 1985 film ``Trouble In Mind.''
   Milstead said in a 1985 interview that he grew up fat and
taunted by classmates in Lutherville, a suburb of Baltimore. The
only son of a businessman and his wife, Milstead told an
interviewer he had a fantasy life revolving around female movie
stars and dreams of becoming a celebrity.
   One of his few friends from high school was Waters, whose
obsession with trashy movies nearly matched Milstead's fantasies of
celebrity. Waters began casting his friend in bizarre roles.
   In the 1972 ``Pink Flamingos,'' Divine was introduced as ``the
filthiest person alive.''
   ``The character is a real person,'' Milstead once said of
Divine. ``Sometimes she's just too bold, but she has socially
redeeming qualities, no matter what she does. She's her own person
and a lot of people like that.
   ``The camp element is something out of the ordinary, this big
man playing a sexy woman.''
   Besides film roles, Milstead also used the Divine persona in a
nightclub act.
   He is survived by his mother and father, Frances and Harris
Milstead, who now live in Florida, West said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
