<2ND_LINE>AM-Dole, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0750,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede OKLAHOMA CITY</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE; picks up 2nd graf pvs, ``We
don't</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONNA BRYSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kansas Sen. Bob Dole, on a last-ditch
campaign swing through Missouri Monday, all but conceded Super
Tuesday to Vice President George Bush _ but said he wasn't giving
up the fight for the Republican presidential nomination.
   ``We know that we won't be the front-runner after Super Tuesday,
but it's not over after Super Tuesday,'' he told a crowd of about
80 supporters during a brief rally at the Springfield Regional
Airport. ``We're going to win in November.''
   Earlier, in Oklahoma City, he said Bush appears strong in the
South but ``there may be some surprises'' and Republicans should
nominate someone who will win the general election.
   ``We don't want to lose the White House by nominating the wrong
person,'' Dole said.
   The senator from Kansas said his race against Bush for
Republican votes in the big round of balloting Tuesday was tight in
Oklahoma, Missouri and North Carolina.
   ``We're moving very quick in Georgia. Washington state looks
pretty good,'' Dole said at a news conference at Will Rogers World
Airport. ``There are some opportunities in Rhode Island and
Massachusetts.
   ``The other states? No, I think it's fair to say George Bush has
a good margin. But again, there may be some surprises.
   ``The final analysis is what happens in November,'' Dole said.
``Electability's going to be a big, big factor. We don't want to
lose the White House by nominating the wrong person.''
   Dole displayed a copy of Monday's Birmingham (Ala.) Post-Herald,
which published a survey saying that while Bush is the strongest
candidate among GOP primary voters, Dole is stronger among voters
of all parties.
   ``I attract a lot of Democrats and independents,'' Dole said in
commenting on the newspaper's poll, which surveyed 1,131 voters in
14 Southern states. ``I don't think I scare anybody off. I think I
attract a lot of people.''
   The senator took a verbal shot at Bush when asked whether the
Super Tuesday series of primaries and caucuses, with GOP events in
17 states and Democratic events in 20 states and American Samoa,
was too big.
   ``I think what the Democrats did was try to design a system
where they would in effect select the Democratic nominee. I'm not
sure that's going to work,'' he said.
   ``But what could happen is that they might select the weakest
Republican, so they might get a consolation prize that way.''
   On the GOP side, he said that ``this is a race between Bob Dole
and George Bush.''
   ``I would invite friends and supporters of (New York Rep.) Jack
Kemp and Pat Robertson to take a look at our candidacy and maybe
join us Tuesday night at polling places around the state,'' Dole
said.
   Dole was joined at the news conference by Oklahoma Republican
Sen. Don Nickles and several GOP members of the state Legislature
who are backing Dole. Nickles said Dole is the best-qualified
candidate to deal with the energy and agriculture industries vital
to Oklahoma, and predicted a victory on Tuesday.
   ``You've been to this state many times and have been warmly
received. I hope and expect you'll be warmly received on Tuesday
night as well,'' Nickles said.
   Dole, saying Kansas football teams don't have much success in
Oklahoma, said: ``It's about time you give Kansas a break, and give
America a break by voting for Bob Dole tomorrow.''
</TEXT>
