<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Nimitz-Lawsuit     03-07 0349</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nimitz-Lawsuit,0358</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Appeals Court Blocks Puget Sound Work</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court Monday halted work
on the Navy's plans to relocate the aircraft carrier Nimitz to
Everett, Wash., a project that has been opposed by environmental
groups.
   In a 3-0 decision, the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ordered
the Navy to stop preliminary work on the $272 million project until
an appeals board reviews a state permit, chiefly on the issue of
how to dispose of contaminated sediment from harbor dredging.
   The Washington Shorelines Hearing Board began a final week of
hearings Monday on water quality and development permits for the
project. A decision is scheduled in May or June. Four votes are
needed on the six-member board to reject the state permit.
   ``We fully expect that when the project receives full review ...
there will be significant modifications,'' said Victor Sher, a
lawyer for six environmental groups that oppose the dredging.
   The ruling means ``the Navy must comply with state environmental
laws, just like everybody else,'' he said.
   Also opposing the project is the Tulalip Indian tribe, whose
fishing grounds include Everett Bay.
   Lt. Cmdr. Joe March, a spokesman for the home-port project, said
he would study the ruling to see what options the Navy has.
   The Navy plans to relocate the Nimitz and 12 support ships in
Everett Harbor on Puget Sound, hoping to have the first ships
arrive in 1992.
   The principal dispute is over the Navy's plan to dredge about
3.4 million cubic yards of sediment from the harbor and dispose of
it in Port Gardner Bay near crab beds at depths of 310 to 430 feet.
About a third of the sediment is contaminated with heavy metals and
organic compounds, the court said.
   The Navy plans to ``cap'' the contaminated dredging with a
lawyer of clean sediment. But the court said the technique is
experimental and has been criticized by the U.S. Fish and Wildlife
Service, which said the method had failed both times it had been
tested at comparable depths.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
