<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DeSillers 1stLd-Writethru a0826 03-07 0655</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-DeSillers, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0826,0670</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ronnie DeSillers Estate Frozen By Judge</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 8-11th grafs pvs, `Ms. DeSillers could...', with 6 grafs
to UPDATE with comment from Ms. DeSillers, picking up 12th graf
pvs, `She said through...'.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONALD W. SWINTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bank accounts containing what's left of the fortune
donated to save liver-transplant patient Ronnie DeSillers were
frozen Monday after a judge was told the dead boy's mother had
spent some of the charity money on jewelry, clothes and furniture,
a state attorney said.
   Dade Circuit Judge Francis Christie appointed a curator to
manage the estate in accordance with a petition filed by state
Attorney General Robert Butterworth and State Attorney Janet Reno
of Miami.
   Ronnie's mother, Maria DeSillers, has spent more than half of
the money donated to her 7-year-old son, who died last year while
awaiting a fourth transplant, the petition said.
   Among the donors was President Reagan, who like many others was
touched by news reports of the theft of funds raised by Ronnie's
classmates. He gave $1,000.
   When Ronnie died at Children's Hospital of Pittsburgh last April
29, an account in his name had accumulated $509,913, the petition
said. The account balance on Feb. 17 was $239,288, said Fred
Kerstein, assistant state attorney and chief of the economic
criminal division.
   As recently as Jan. 19, 1988, $25,000 had been withdrawn from
the fund, ``thereby further depleting the assets of the estate,''
the petition said.
   ``Based upon an examination of bank records, at least $47,000
appears to have been expended by Maria DeSillers on jewelry,
clothing, furniture, housing expenses, an automobile and automobile
expenses, these funds having been assets of this estate,'' it said.
There was no further breakdown of the expenditures in the petition.
   Asked about the allegations in the petition, Ms. DeSillers said:
``Why do they not say that money went to charity? Why do they not
say that some of that money was assigned to me personally? ... How
come they don't say how much of that money went to kids?''
   She said she had already planned to use the money that was
frozen to help two ailing children who are awaiting transplants,
one from Miami and the other from Costa Rica, and would go to
probate court to straighten out the dispute.
   ``There are two children that have less than six months to live,
and that's what I want to do with the money,'' she said.
   Ms. DeSillers is being sued by Children's Hospital for failing
to pay $261,189 of Ronnie's $424,302 bill.
   In refusing to pay the balance, Ms. DeSillers charged the
hospital with giving poor care to her son and threatened to file a
malpractice suit.
   Ms. DeSillers and her lawyer, Harold Robbins, said last month
they would refuse to pay a $1,000 state fine for allegedly
violating Florida charity laws.
   She said through Robbins that she had never asked the public to
donate money and she was not legally a charity. She also said she
was entitled to the money as Ronnie's sole heir.
   After Ronnie's death, Ms. DeSillers created the foundation to
assist other children in need of organ transplants.
   She returned to the limelight when it was learned that the
formerly unemployed public relations agent was living in a luxury
apartment building and driving a BMW equipped with a telephone.
   She denied squandering any of the donations, explaining that the
car was second-hand, the car telephone was a gift and the apartment
doubled as her office.
   The petition filed by Butterworth and Ms. Reno asked that
Ronnie's estate be frozen ``to prevent additional assets of the
estate ... from being wasted and to protect persons interested in
the estate, including creditors.''
   ``Immediate and irreparable injury will result to assets of the
estate ... if Maria DeSillers is permitted to withdraw the funds,''
the petition said.
   Attorney Karen Geivers was appointed estate curator, Kerstein
said.
</TEXT>
