<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Poland-Glemp     03-07 0277</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland-Glemp,0287</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Polish Primate Invited To Visit Soviet Union</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cardinal Jozef Glemp, leader of Poland's
Roman Catholic church, said Monday he has been invited to visit
Moscow in early June for ceremonies marking the 1,000th anniversary
of Russian Christendom.
   No Polish primate has ever visited the Soviet Union.
   Glemp said he received the invitation last month to attend
observances organized by the Russian Orthodox church.
   ``There have been no talks yet,'' Glemp told reporters at
Warsaw's Okecie Airport after returning from a weeklong visit to
Rome, where he met with Polish-born Pope John Paul II. ``I only got
a formal invitation. I want to go, obviously.''
   Church sources have said a visit by Glemp to the Soviet Union
could help pave the way for a future visit there by the pope.
   In January, John Paul said he would visit the Soviet Union only
if he could meet with Roman Catholics around the country.
   Glemp has let it be known he would like to visit the Soviet
Union, especially former Polish territories in the Soviet
Lithuanian republic that has a large Polish minority and where the
Catholic faith is quite strong.
   Asked whether he planned to visit other places than Moscow,
Glemp said he ``might change from an official church representative
into a tourist for a few hours ... with pleasure because there are
many things to see there.''
   The Soviet invitation reflects a turnaround since Mikhail S.
Gorbachev came to power three years ago.
   The Soviets previously attacked the Polish church for inspiring
opposition activities, but more recently have made overtures to
Polish Catholics.
   Almost 90 percent of Poland's population is Catholic.
</TEXT>
