<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Bodies-Graham     03-07 0332</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bodies-Graham,0342</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Defendant Waives Jury; Trial Begins In Case Of Bodies Found In
Apartment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE LINDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An unemployed handyman waived his right to a
jury Monday and his trial began on charges of killing seven women
and leaving their bodies to rot in and near his apartment.
   Harrison ``Marty'' Graham's decision came as Common Pleas Judge
Robert Latrone prepared to begin jury selection. Graham then
entered pleas of innocent to seven counts each of murder, voluntary
manslaughter and abuse of a corpse.
   The judge, after determining Graham, 28, understood the charges,
ordered the lawyers to begin presenting their cases. Both sides
waived opening statements.
   Assistant District Attorney Roger King moved for admission of
all testimony and documents from a monthlong pretrial suppression
hearing, including a confession Graham made to police, admitting
strangling the seven women during sex. Latrone granted the request.
   During the pretrial hearing, defense attorney Joel Moldovsky,
contending his client is mentally incompetent, sought
unsuccessfully to suppress the confession.
   Moldovsky argued the confession was made in violation of
Graham's constitutional rights and after Graham allegedly was
beaten by police during 17 hours of interrogation.
   Graham surrendered to police at his mother's urging Aug. 16
after a weeklong manhunt that started when he was evicted from his
apartment because of a putrid stench.
   A police search uncovered the rotting bodies in Graham's bedroom
and leg and foot bones on the roof of his apartment house.
   In the confession, Graham told police the bodies began piling up
in his bedroom and he began having problems with maggots. He also
told of his difficulty sleeping during the day because of birds on
the roof outside his apartment, picking at human remains.
   Moldovsky has indicated that Graham's defense will be insanity.
   The first witness called by the prosecution, acting Medical
Examiner Robert Catherman, said all seven deaths were homicides but
said it was impossible in most cases to determine the cause of
death because of decomposition.
</TEXT>
