<1ST_LINE>r i AM-DominicanRepublic     03-07 0363</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dominican Republic,0376</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Pledges To Control Prices</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUDDY L. GONZALEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTO DOMINGO, Dominican Republic (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soldiers in tanks and
jeeps patrolled the main streets and poorer areas of the capital
Monday to block further protests against the rising cost of living.
   President Joaquin Balaguer summoned his advisers to discuss ways
of controlling inflation, a major factor in recent unrest in this
Caribbean island nation of more than 6.5 million people.
   Protesters burned tires early Monday during a 24-hour strike in
five low-income sectors of Santo Domingo.
   Three days of clashes last week between protesters and soldiers
left one person dead and many businesses damaged. More than 300
people were arrested.
   The previous week, three people were killed and eight injured in
protests in eight of the country's 26 provinces.
   Support seemed to be dwindling for a general strike called for
Wednesday to demand lower prices for basic commodities, wage
increases for public and private workers and better public services.
   ``We are willing to talk and hold sincere discussions with the
authorities to solve the conflict as long as they manifest their
sincere willingness to satisfy our demands,'' said spokeswoman
Virtudes Alvarez of the National Conference of Popular
Organizations.
   The group called for the general strike and organized earlier
strikes in the last few weeks that shut down many parts of the
capital.
   Labor groups opposed the strike, but promised to support it if
it takes place. They want either a later strike or talks among the
government, unions and business community to try to solve the
economic problems.
   The main opposition party, the Dominican Revolutionary Party, is
also against the strike, although left-wing political parties
support it.
   Balaguer said Sunday he would meet with his agricultural
advisers, merchants and business people to develop a plan to
implement price controls.
   Shortages of many goods, including milk, have become prevalent.
   A private economist estimated the February inflation rate at
about 5 percent and predicted a 50 to 60 percent rate for 1988 if
that continued.
   Private sources have estimated inflation in 1987 at around 30
percent, although the government's Central Bank maintains it was
closer to 16 percent.
</TEXT>
