<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Czechoslovakia-Arrests     03-07 0350</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Czechoslovakia-Arrests,0362</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Author Of Religious Petition Charged With Slander</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The author of a petition on religious
freedom in communist Czechoslovakia that was signed by about
300,000 people has been arrested and charged with slander, an
emigre source said Monday.
   The London-based emigre publishing firm Palach Press said
Augustin Navratil was accused of committing ``slander of a state
organ and of a public organization.'' Conviction is punishiable by
up to one year in prison.
   The exact targets of the purported slander were not spelled out.
   Navratil, a Roman Catholic activist from a village in Moravia,
was one of 16 people detained over the weekend in advance of a
Catholic pilgrimage in Prague Sunday.
   Dissident sources in Prague said Navratil was detained Friday
morning. Other activists were held for 48 hours and released late
Sunday or early Monday, the sources said, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   Palach Press said it was not clear if Stanislav Devaty, a
spokesman for the Charter 77 human rights movement, was rearrested
after his 48-hour detention expired.
   In Czechoslovakia, authorities may hold people for 48 hours
without formal charges.
   Dissident sources said Devaty was detained late Friday night
after attending a dinner with British diplomats in an embassy
secretary's apartment.
   Five other dissident activists invited to the dinner were
detained before they could get in, and that action drew a strong
protest from the British Foreign Office.
   Navratil's petition calls for separation of church and state and
for bishops to fill Czechoslovakia's 10 empty Roman Catholic sees.
   Cardinal Frantisek Tomasek gave unprecedented support to the
petition in a letter of Jan. 4.
   Palach Press also reported that in a separate development, 12
people were briefly detained Saturday in Prague as they left the
home of a granddaughter of Thomas G. Masaryk, president of
Czechoslovakia's pre-World War II democracy.
   It said the group had planned a graveside ceremony on Sunday
honoring Masaryk in the village of Lany, about 30 miles west of
Prague.
   Monday was the anniversary of Masaryk's birth in 1850. The U.S.
embassy planned to lay a wreath at the grave.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
