<FILEID>AP-NR-03-07-88 0719EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e PM-APArts:Spain-Books Adv07   03-07 0862</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AP Arts: Spain-Books, Adv 07,0883</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv 07</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon PMs, March 7 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Serious Reading in Spain</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Lluis is cq in 3rd graf</NOTE>
<BYLINE>BY SUSAN LINNEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>ASSOCIATED PRESS WRITER</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BARCELONA, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When publisher Jorge de Herralde saw
novels bearing his Anagrama Logo in all three bookstores on
Lanzarote Island, he knew things were looking up for serious books
in Spain.
   ``Eight or nine years ago, it would have been impossible to find
good novels and essays in bookstores in provincial towns, let alone
on a small island in the Canaries,'' he said. ``It makes me
optimistic about the future of Spanish publishing.''
   Silvia Lluis, director of the year-old publishing company Circe
Ediciones, agrees that now is the time for quality books in Spain.
   ``There's a new, discriminating reading public that wants more
than the pulp best sellers,'' she said. ``They've read Marguerite
Yourcenar, and they don't want to settle for less.''
   The increased interest in quality books in a country where
newspaper readership is the lowest in Europe comes more than a
decade after the demise of Gen. Francisco Franco's dictatorship and
his 36 years of cultural and intellectual repression.
   The change has been fairly sudden. It is due in part to Spain's
1986 entry into the European Common Market which has broadened many
horizons. De Herralde also credited the newfound market to a
decline in ideological topics and obscure experimental writing by
some authors, and a return to the narrative _ both in Spanish and
foreign literature.
   Those in the publishing industry, centered mainly in this
northeastern port city, say Spaniards are now looking beyond their
borders, learning foreign languages and reading good books.
   A 1985 study initiated by the Ministry of Culture on Spanish
cultural behavior said that although 80 percent of Spanish
households possessed books, mainly encyclopedias or technical
manuals, only 41 percent read any of them.
   The study also showed that the Spanish reading public is heavily
concentrated in Madrid and in Catalonia, of which Barcelona is the
capital _ the the most developed and educated regions of Spain. The
illiteracy rate is 7.4 percent in a population of 36.8 million,
third highest in the 12-nation European Economic Community after
Greece and Portugal. Results also revealed that fewer than 11
percent of Spaniards ever set foot inside a library.
   ``Many people are still afraid to go inside bookstores or
libraries because they think they're only for intellectuals,'' said
Manuel Ripoll, producer of ``Entrelineas'' (``Between the Lines''),
Spanish state TV's new literary program. ``That's why so many of
the books sold in Spain are purchased at corner newsstands.''
   De Herralde pointed out that the biggest single bookseller in
Spain _ with items ranging from how-to manuals to poetry
collections _ is El Corte Ingles, the country's only department
store chain.
   Translations of foreign works _ primarily American and English
books _ make up about 70 percent of the lists of Anagrama, Circe
and other quality houses. The other 30 percent is devoted to the
works of established or new Spanish authors.
   Five years ago de Herralde, a 52-year-old former industrial
engineer, took a chance on John Kennedy Toole's ``A Confederacy of
Dunces,'' a cult novel published in the United States when the
unknown author's mother brought the manuscript to a publisher after
his suicide. The book earned the author a posthumous Pulitzer Prize
in 1981.
   The Spanish edition has gone into 22 printings and has sold
100,000 copies. The translation into Catalan, a language spoken by
more than 5 million people in the northeastern part of the country,
is due out in April.
   Pilar Raola, director of the Catalan publishing house Editorial
Portic, said many Spanish-reading Catalans preferred to wait to
read a translation of a foreign novel in their own language,
resulting in a similar upsurge in Catalan-language publishing.
   According to the Spanish Association of Book Publishers, 38,814
titles were published in Spain in 1986 of which 7,483 were novels
and essays. The average press run for a Spanish novel is between
3,500 and 4,000 copies.
   Felix de Azua's ``Diary of a Humiliated Man'' has gone into its
third printing at Anagrama in three months following its
publication in December after winning the firm's coveted Herralde
literary award.
   Chilean author Isabel Allende's ``Eva Luna'' and ``Belle du
Seigneur'' by French author Albert Cohen have been jockeying for
first place on the best-seller list of Spain's leading newspaper El
Pais for the past six months. Five of the 10 top-selling books on
the list are by Spanish authors.
   The most successful Spanish novel this century is Jose Maria
Gironella's ``Cypresses Believe in God,'' set in the years leading
up to the 1936-39 Spanish Civil War. Since its publication in the
late 1950s, the book has sold over 4 million copies.
   The burst of interest in quality fiction has led Spanish
publishing giants to set up smaller collections devoted to serious
fiction and essays, de Herralde said.
   And the nationwide Readers' Circle book club began including
quality foreign and domestic fiction several years ago at the
request of its 1.3 million members, according to spokesman Hans
Gentz.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PM Mon March 7</NOTE>
</DOC>
