<2ND_LINE>PM-Life Abroad-France, Adv 11,0701</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv11</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Fri PMs March 11 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>LIFE ABROAD: France _ A Tax-Free `Pousse Cafe'?</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   This is one of a series of periodic reports by
Associated Press correspondents on the way of life in other
countries.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By FIONA GLEIZES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Robert Gobinot isn't given much chance in his
candidacy for the office of president, but he's getting some
attention with his idea to restore an orchard owner's benefit
dating back to the French Revolution.
   In 1791, owners of orchards were granted the right to distill
tax-free each year 2.6 gallons of eau de vie, the alcoholic
beverage that is sipped after meals and called ``pousse cafe'' or
``digestif.'' The distillers would pay no tax so long as they
didn't offer it for sale.
   The license to distill was passed on from one generation to
another until 1961 when a new law canceled the right to inherit the
license.
   Eau de vie comes in various forms, depending on the region. In
Normandy, for example, it is made from apples and is called
calvados. In Alsace in eastern France, pears and plums are used; in
the Auvergne region of central France it is made from hazelnuts.
   ``When my mother died six months ago, I inherited her orchard,''
said Gobinot, ``but the license died with her and so I can no
longer make eau de vie without paying tax.''
   Gobinot's bucolic campaign headquarters is his 60-acre sheep
farm in the village of Chezeaux in the Haut-Marne department of
eastern France.
   His name does not figure in the opinion polls, he has no
political party machine behind him, or image advisers cultivating a
presidential package for the balloting April 24 and runoff May 8.
   But he has been getting his message out and has already received
letters of support from 500 mayors, the minimum necessary to
declare his candidacy formally.
   ``Our method of raising support is by word of mouth,'' Gobinot
said in a telephone interview.
   But he thinks it unlikely that he will become Francois
Mitterrand's successor in the presidency. He is simply using the
elections, he said, to defend what he sees as an honorable rural
tradition.
   Others, however, compare the lot of French eau de vie distillers
to the tale of Tristan and Isolde, or the myth of the eternal
return, because the argument to restore the inherited licenses
resurfaces from time to time.
   In a country that has one of the highest rates of alcoholism in
the world, the abolition of the right to distill tax-free eau de
vie might seem like a good thing. But Gobinot disagrees.
   He wants to clean up the image of the ``bouilleurs de cru,'' as
eau de vie makers are known.
   ``We want people to realize that we are not just purveyors of
alcoholism,'' he said.
   Gobinot maintains that the major distilleries are more to blame
for the problem of alcoholism than farmers who make a couple of
gallons out of plums or apples.
   According to Gobinot, 2.11 million gallons of alcohol were drunk
in France last year, of which just 15,840 gallons were homemade eau
de vie.
   ``This shows how ridiculous the argument is,'' he said. ``We
make less than 1 percent of the total consumption in France.''
   Gobinot emphasizes that traditional rural skills, and therefore
jobs, are disappearing as a result of the 1961 law. Only a handful
of craftsmen making wooden barrels remain and the fruit trees are
no longer pruned as they used to be, he said.
   The distiller with his ``alambic ambulant'' (mobile still),
going from village to village in Normandy to turn apples into
calvados, was once a familiar figure.
   ``The farmer who picks his own fruit is proud to distill his own
eau de vie,'' Gobinot said. ``He does everything himself and is
making a natural product.
   ``I drink very little myself. But I take great pleasure in
offering a glass of friendship when people come to my house.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Fri PMs March 11</NOTE>
</DOC>
