<NOTE>For Release Mon PMs March 14 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>A Community `Tender Care Corps' Keeps Watch on Newborn</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Japan-Infants, b0123</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARI TAKETA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YAMATO VILLAGE, Japan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of the reasons given for so
many healthy babies in Japan is the Tender Care Corps, an
organization of volunteer women who visit new mothers and their
babies in their own homes.
   The corps operates on the tradition that neighbors look out for
each other. It mobilizes 80,000 mothers who volunteer to keep tabs
on the health of 2 million households with children in Japan's
outlying cities and hamlets.
   Here in Yamato village, a collection of small farms and quarries
perched among mountaintop forests, volunteer Hatsuko Hirayama
visits six families every month. She makes her rounds on foot over
steep paths and concrete-paved roads 60 miles west of Tokyo.
   ``Our purpose is to see that healthy babies are born,''
explained Mrs. Hirayama, a woman in her fifties with children of
her own. ``The public health nurse can't always visit homes, so I
do.''
   One of the mothers she visits is Yoshimi Hirayama, a distant
relative in this town of 1,890 people. The visits began when the
24-year-old housewife became pregnant with her second child, which
turned out to be a daughter, Michiko, who now is now 10 months old.
   ``She told me to breast feed,'' Yoshimi said. ``She told me to
eat things that would build bones _ small fish, lots of milk.
   ``She's like another mother. When I had my first baby I didn't
know anybody here, but I could go to Mrs. Hirayama and ask her
anything.''
   Yoshimi's pregnancy was normal. She followed her doctor's
instructions to undergo health checks every three weeks during the
first two trimesters, then biweekly and weekly until delivery. In
between came prenatal care and childbirth classes at the village
hall.
   In April, after she gave birth to Michiko, a public health nurse
stopped by to check on the mother and baby after their return from
the hospital. Mrs. Hirayama took it from there.
   ``Any teeth?'' she asked on a recent visit, pulling down
Michiko's lower lip. ``Are you hiding them?''
   Her notes on Michiko's diet, bedtimes and skin color are turned
over to the health nurse, who evaluates them and recommends
doctor's visits or looks in on the baby herself, if necessary.
   Mrs. Hirayama fills in monthly visit cards for each child she
sees on her rounds until the child turns 6. Then it is time for
school teachers to keep an eye out.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Mon PMs March 14</NOTE>
