<FILEID>AP-NR-03-07-88 1442EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s e BC-APN--TVWeek Adv20   03-07 1164</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--TV Week, Adv 20,1192</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv20</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, March 20</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 2 b&w
photos.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It was 10 years ago that we first met the
Ewing family, those oil barons of the Southfork Ranch and CBS'
``Dallas.''
   How times have changed _ and how ``Dallas'' has changed.
   Few people today remember that the original star of ``Dallas''
was Pamela Barnes Ewing, played by Victoria Principal, and that her
marriage to Bobby Ewing (Patrick Duffy) would give the show its
theme of ``Romeo and Juliet.'' The feuding Barneses and the Ewings
would be the show's Montagues and Capulets. It also had a dash of
``Giant'' and ``Peyton Place'' tossed in.
   It was even considered, but only briefly, that Bobby would be
killed in the fifth episode and it would be Pam vs. the family.
   J.R. Ewing, played by Larry Hagman, was a supporting character,
and his wife, Sue Ellen (Linda Gray), was such a minor character
she didn't even speak in the first show on April 2, 1978. The
script referred to her only as the ``brunette on the couch'' and
didn't even identify her as J.R.'s wife.
   Still, Hagman emerged with the meatiest role in the first show
and he made the most of it. ``He is deliciously wicked as he
attempts to eject Principal from the family bosom by any foul
means,'' a pre-debut story said.
   Writer David Jacobs created the show with Pamela as the focus.
``This is a poor girl who marries into a rich family _ and her own
family's enemy,'' Jacobs said in a 1978 interview.
   ``Dallas'' was actually a spinoff of ``Knots Landing,'' although
``Dallas'' got on the air first. The Dallas locale was picked
because CBS and Lorimar Productions wanted to get away from the
usual Los Angeles background.
   ``It all seems like yesterday and a hundred years ago,'' says
Leonard Katzman, the current executive producer. He has been with
the show since the beginning except for the season when both he and
Patrick Duffy left the show. He calls it ``the season that didn't
exist'' because it was all passed off as Pamela's dream when Duffy
returned.
   He says there is some talk of putting together a retrospective
of the show's 10 years during the summer for a special.
   ``We came on in the spring with five shows,'' he recalls. ``As
far as we knew that's all we were going to do. Then CBS picked us
up for seven more shows. Then enough shows to complete the first
full season. We had a cliffhanger that year, but nobody remembers
it.''
   Few remember the first cliffhanger, in which Sue Ellen wrecked
her car and you didn't know if she and her unborn baby would
survive.
   The second cliffhanger, in 1980, caused a phenomenon around the
world that was unprecedented in the history of television. ``Who
Shot J.R.?'' was on the lips of millions upon millions of people,
from Seattle to New York to London to Paris.
   By the time it was revealed that Kristin had pulled the trigger,
``Dallas'' had climbed to No. 1 in the Nielsen ratings. It reigned
over the ratings for the next four years, slipping once to second
place, until NBC overtook CBS as the first-place network and ``The
Cosby Show'' put the sitcoms back at the top of the ratings.
   A less well-known event of the summer of 1980 occurred when
Hagman asked Lorimar to raise his salary to $100,000 an episode.
Lorimar not only refused but told Hagman that J.R. could wake up in
the hospital after plastic surgery and be Robert Culp.
   Hagman got the last laugh, however. Katzman says he is by far
the highest paid performer on television today. ``And several other
people on `Dallas' are not too far behind,'' he says.
   ``Dallas'' captured the interest of the audience, Katzman
believes, because there had never been a family like this on
television before.
   ``They were very wealthy, but they had no airs,'' he says. ``Jim
Davis was plain folks. They fought with each other, then made up.
Plus, we showed that you can't equate money with happiness.''
   ``Dallas'' did not become a serial until its first full season.
   ``Sue Ellen became pregnant and no one knew whether the father
was J.R. or Cliff Barnes,'' says Katzman. ``We carried that story
for quite a while. It caught on with the audience. So we began
doing more stories that ran from week to week.
   ``We also found ourselves with the greatest character in
television, J.R. Ewing. It's hard to say when he began to emerge,
but it was probably the end of the fifth show when Pam lost her
baby. J.R. and Pam had a fight in a hayloft and she fell and lost
the baby. At first he seemed contrite, then you began to see how
wicked he could be.''
   Jim Davis, who played Jock, the patriarch of the Ewings, died in
1981.
   ``Jim represented something we've never been able to
recapture,'' says Katzman. ``As bad as the boys could be, if he
walked into a room and told them to knock it off they did. I think
the audience responded to that strong head of the family and the
warm woman (Barbara Bel Geddes as Miss Ellie) at the other end of
the table.
   ``Much of J.R.'s motivation was looking good in his father's
eyes. When Jim died that motivation disappeared. So we had to
transfer it to his son. After that, when he did something terrible
it was to build the empire for his son, as his father had done for
him.''
   Others have left the series and returned. Donna Reed replaced
Bel Geddes as Miss Ellie when she had heart surgery. Charlene
Tilton, who plays Lucy Ewing Cooper, left the show but returned
this season. Patrick Duffy quit in 1985, but returned after missing
one season _ the famous season that disappeared as Pam's dream. Pam
herself is now gone with the departure of Victoria Principal.
   Every departure shifted relationships. Without Bobby, J.R. had
no one to hold him in check. Pamela's departure separates her
brother, Cliff Barnes (Ken Kercheval) from the Ewings.
   Is ``Dallas'' a soap opera or a spoof?
   ``We play it straight, although we sometimes take it to
extremes,'' Katzman says. ``We've never taken ourselves as
seriously as some other shows. `Knots Landing' is the most
reality-based show. We have our own reality, but it's a fictitious
reality.''
   Next season, CBS and Lorimar are considering a move away from
the serial format. Either every story would begin and end within an
episode, or in the manner of ``L.A. Law'' and ``St. Elsewhere,''
some storylines would be resolved and some would carry over a few
weeks.
   ``This show will last as long as the actors want to keep on
doing it,'' says Katzman.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>END ADV for Sunday, March 20</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880307-0217 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-07-88 1445EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s e BC-APN--TheaterWeek Adv20-1stAdd   03-07 0409</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Theater Week, Adv 20-1st Add ,0417</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv20</NOTE>
<BYLINE>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</BYLINE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, March 20</NOTE>
<HEAD>NEW YORK: the other.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Hicks' job doesn't end when the curtain goes up. During the
performance, she's in the dressing room or the wings, ready to do
minor touch-ups.
   As for Crawford, the makeup is with him for 12 hours on
Wednesdays and Saturdays, when he performs twice; seven hours on
the four days when he does just one show.
   At the end of the show, Hicks applies vast amounts of mineral
oil to remove the makeup, which is peeled off gently so as not to
irritate the skin.
   ``There aren't many makeup jobs in theater because nowadays
actors learn to do their own makeup,'' says Hicks, who grew up in
Surrey and moved to Oxford before going to London to study at
Complexions, the London School of Makeup.
   Hicks met Tucker, the makeup designer, when he spoke at the
school. He hired her to work on ``Phantom.'' It was her first job.
   ``It was quite an extensive training period he put her
through,'' Crawford says. ``I remember him throwing all her brushes
from college out the door and saying `What's this, girl? You can't
use this, girl.' It was something out of Dickens, and I had to sit
there absolutely quiet. But it worked.''
   Hicks adapted quickly to her on-the-job training.
   ``We had done a lot of this in theory at school, but in practice
I had never done it although I always wanted to get into prosthetic
makeup,'' she says.
   The makeup design for ``Phantom'' was first discussed during the
summer of 1986, several months before the show opened in London at
Her Majesty's Theater. Tucker, scenic designer Maria Bjornson and
Crawford experimented with many different kinds of makeup. They
found they were limited by practical considerations.
   ``There were restrictions _ not being able to cover the nose
because of breathing or going inside the mouth too far because of
the singing or covering the ears because it would interfere with
listening to the music,'' Crawford says.
   What the three of them came up with is what Hicks tries to
recapture at every performance.
   ``It's interesting. People say `How can you do the same show
every day when you're an actor?''' Crawford says. ``It's exactly
the same thing with the makeup. It's like painting. Every day is a
challenge to paint that picture.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>END ADV for Sunday, March 20</NOTE>
</DOC>
