<DOCNO> AP880307-0221 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-07-88 1420EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s i BC-India-Navy Adv13   03-07 1027</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-India-Navy, Adv 13,1060</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv13</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, March 13, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>India Building Navy in its `Zone of Peace'</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By G.G. LaBELLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation that wants to turn the Indian
Ocean into a ``zone of peace'' has just acquired a nuclear
submarine to add to its two aircraft carriers and 110 other naval
vessels.
   India's acquisition last month of the nuclear submarine from the
Soviet Union is part of a naval expansion since failing in its
efforts of almost 20 years to clear the Indian Ocean of big-power
navies.
   The expansion has aroused criticism from neighboring Pakistan
and the United States, which has warships in the ocean along with
the Soviet Union, Britain and France.
   Within the past two years, India also has acquired five
conventional submarines, its second aircraft carrier and at least
five Indian-built navy ships.
   It has plans to buy more _ including possibly other Soviet
nuclear subs _ and to build warships ranging from submarines to
another aircraft carrier for its fleet.
   ``It's the full range of naval warfare. They're building a
first-class navy,'' a Western naval analyst said.
   When the 47,000-member Indian navy got the carrier Hermes from
Britain last year and renamed it Viraat (Imposing), the chief of
naval staff at the time, Adm. R.H. Tahiliani, said: ``We finally
have a round-the-clock blue (deep) water navy.''
   While greater naval strength seems to belie India's pleas before
the United Nations for a zone of peace in the Indian Ocean, it
matches the country's growing might.
   India also has a 1-million-man army, the world's fourth largest,
and is acquiring modern weapons.
   Each step up, however, is ascribed to the need to match the
growing arsenals of others, chiefly neighboring rivals Pakistan and
China but also the Western powers.
   ``The strategies of outside powers in our region have forced
upon us expenditure in building military strength which we would
much rather have deployed for the removal of poverty,'' Prime
Minister Rajiv Gandhi said as the nuclear sub Chakra was
commissioned.
   ``The Indian Ocean has been militarized and infested with
nuclear weapons flouting the overwhelming sentiment within the
region in favor of establishing a zone of peace.''
   India first proposed a zone of peace for the Indian Ocean in the
early 1970s, and the Non-Aligned Movement (Third World) endorsed
the concept. The proposal then went to the U.N. General Assembly,
which in 1971 adopted a declaration calling for a peace zone and
urging the dismantling of big powers' air and naval bases in the
Indian Ocean. But a planned U.N. conference on the issue has never
been held, although a committee has been meeting in hopes of
bringing one about by 1990.
   The Soviet Union has endorsed the idea, but the United States
has not.
   India's naval buildup initially was attributed to the
development of a U.S. Navy base in the early 1980s at Diego Garcia,
an island in the Chagos Archipelago about 1,000 miles southwest of
India.
   An Indian naval expert, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
he did not believe his nation faces a real threat from U.S. or
other Western ships protecting oil shipping in the Persian Gulf,
but he added: ``If you have troubled waters close to home, you
think about what you might have to do.''
   He said India believed more sea power was needed to protect its
4,937 miles of coastline and to keep a competitive edge in naval
technology.
   Of the newly acquired nuclear sub, he said: ``It's a system
without which a navy is not viable. It takes the game to a new step
altogether.''
   Prime Minister Mohammad Khan Junejo of Pakistan has condemned
the acquisition of the sub as an escalation of the military buildup
in the region. Press reports say Pakistan, with no nuclear
submarine, is pressing the United States for P-3 anti-submarine
aircraft.
   U.S. State Department spokesman Charles Redman has said India's
acquisition of a nuclear sub ``clearly introduces a new weapons
technology into the South Asian region.''
   The United States is opposed to India having a nuclear submarine
because of a lack of safeguards, Redman added.
   Neither India nor Pakistan has signed the nuclear
non-proliferation treaty. India exploded a nuclear device in 1974,
and Pakistan is thought to be on the verge of developing nuclear
weapons. Both nations say their nuclear plans are peaceful in
design.
   The new Chakra submarine, for the moment leased by the Soviets
to the Indian navy, is not believed to carry nuclear weapons.
   The Western naval analyst, who insisted his name not be used,
said the Charlie I class sub is ``1960s technology. It's an old
boat.''
   India's second aircraft carrier, the Viraat, was originally
commissioned in 1959, and the Western expert noted that India
``does not have enough planes for one carrier, let alone two.''
   India, however, is buying British Sea Harrier aircraft and Sea
King commando helicopters for its carriers.
   It also has bought three late-1970s vintage Kilo class Soviet
submarines and two West German HDW 209s, called ``search and kill
subs,'' to update its fleet of eight Soviet-made Foxtrot subs.
   In addition, India is upgrading its three shipyards to build
warships and constructing its largest naval base near Karwar, 285
miles south of Bombay on the west coast.
   There are reports the navy is expanding an existing base on its
far-flung Nicobar islands, 1,035 miles from the country's southern
tip but only about 100 miles from Indonesia.
   The Indian naval expert saw these developments in light of
India's need to protect itself.
   ``You need military power for your own security, not that you
have expansionist ambitions,'' he said.
   His Western counterpart said India's rationale for an expanding
navy was its view of itself as the regional power of South Asia.
   Indian navy men also see themselves as heirs to British sea
power from the days when Britain controlled the Indian Ocean to
protects its trade routes to Asia, the Western analyst said.
   ``They want a navy they can operate throughout the Indian
Ocean,'' he said. ``The Brits were there before. They want to be
there too.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, March 13</NOTE>
</DOC>
