<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The board of governors of the Postal Service
may decide this week to boost U.S. postage rates, including an
increase in the cost of first-class letters to 25 cents from 22
cents.
   The independent Postal Rate Commission recommended on Friday a
series of postage rate hikes totaling 17.5 percent. The Postal
Service requested a 16 percent increase. The rate proposals now go
to the board of governors of the Postal Service, and could be
ordered into effect within two weeks.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The economy's growth slowed in February although
exporters continued to show strength, the nation's purchasing
managers say.
   The National Association of Purchasing Management said Sunday
its index fell to 54.9 percent in February from 57.4 percent in
January and was the lowest since a reading of 54.7 percent in April
1987.
   A reading above 50 percent indicates that the economy is
generally expanding; a reading below that indicates it is generally
declining.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's civilian unemployment rate has
dropped to 5.7 percent, indicating a stronger U.S. economy than
most analysts had thought.
   The Bureau of Labor Statistics said Friday that the unemployment
rate fell by 0.1 percentage point from 5.8 percent in December and
January. Non-farm payrolls rose by 531,000 jobs, a separate survey
said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chicago banker A. Robert Abboud has won
shareholder approval of his $1.5 billion plan to rescue First City
Bancorporation of Texas Inc.
   The plan approved Friday includes nearly $1 billion in federal
assistance, a spin-off of poorly performing assets and an infusion
of privately-raised capital. Abboud will be become chairman of
board and chief executive officer upon consummation of deal.
   J.A. Elkins Jr., First City's senior board chairman, said the
bank had received a commitment for a line of credit and obtained
necessary tax rulings to complete the transaction.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Takeover target American Standard Inc. has
sweetened a defensive recapitalization plan to $2.3 billion, but
hostile pursuer Black & Decker Corp. countered by raising its
takeover offer to $2.2 billion.
   American Standard's sweetened recapitalization offer, announced
Friday, would pay shareolders $64 in cash, $5 in securities and one
share of stock in the recapitalized company for each old share. The
earlier cash portion was $59.
   Black & Decker, a Towson, Md.-based maker of tools and
appliances that has been pursuing American Standard since late
January, responded by raising its offer from $68 a share to $73 for
American Standard's 31 million shares.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Campeau Corp. says it would sell the Filene's
and Foley's divisions of Federated Department Stores Inc. to May
Department Stores Co. if Campeau succeeds in its $6.18 billion
tender offer for Federated.
   Campeau, which is battling R.H. Macy & Co. Inc. for Federated,
said Friday the sale of the two department store divisions would
bring between $1.3 billion and $1.5 billion and help finance its
acquisition.
   Campeau is proceeding with a tender offer for Federated although
Federated has agreed to be acquired by Macy in a cash-and-stock
deal valued by some analysts at $6.1 billion.
</TEXT>
