<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Japan-Engines     03-07 0175</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Japan-Engines,0182</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Isuzu Motors to Use GM Engines</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Isuzu Motors Ltd. will purchase U.S.-made engines
for vehicles it exports and Isuzu trucks produced in the United
States, a company spokesman said Monday.
   Isuzu Motors plans to purchase 30,000 gasoline engines from
General Motors Co. annually, of which 10,000 units will be imported
to Japan, Takashi Fujii said.
   The GM engine will be used in about 10 percent of the small
pickup trucks and multi-purpose four-wheel drive cars Izusu plans
to export to the United States from this fall, Fujii said.
   The remaining 20,000 engines will be installed in a third of the
60,000 small pickup trucks Izusu will produce annually in an
Indiana factory set up jointly with Fuji Heavy Industries, to begin
in the fall of 1989.
   The American engines will boost the amount of locally supplied
parts from 60 percent to 70 percent, the original target, Fujii
said.
   The engines that Isuzu plans to purchase are six-cylinder
gasoline engines, which GM uses for passenger and commercial
vehicles, he said.
</TEXT>
