<FILEID>AP-NR-03-07-88 0852EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Europe-Takeover     03-07 0447</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Europe-Takeover,0464</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>De Benedetti Names Allies in Bid for Societe Generale</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Italian investor Carlo De Benedetti on
Monday named new international partners to help him in his bid for
control of Societe Generale de Belgique SA.
   Cerus SA, the French investment firm through which De Benedetti
is vying for control of Belgium's largest holding company, said the
alliance controlled 47.01 percent of share capital of Societe
Generale.
   The group is opposed by a Franco-Belgian alliance which claims a
majority stake of 52 percent.
   For the first time, Cerus said the Swiss bank Banque Financiere
de la Cite, Australia's FAI Insurances Ltd. company and the U.S.
company Odyssey Partners were helping its bid for control of the
company which has a stake in a third of the Belgian economy.
   Earlier known partners are the U.S. investment firm Shearson
Lehman Hutton Inc., the Swiss bank Companie de Banque et
d'Investissements and two Belgian partners.
   On Monday, the Dutch technology giant N.V. Philips and the Swiss
food company Nestle SA were invited to become partners.
   Cerus, Shearson and CBI have formed the holding company Europe
1992 in support of their bid. Europe 1992 refers to the date when
goods, services and people should be able to move without
restrictions in the 12-nation European Economic Community.
   De Benedetti wants to turn Societe Generale in a pan-European
holding company.
   De Benedetti's rival group is formed around Belgium's biggest
insurer, Groupe AG, and the French investment firm Companie
Financiere de Suez. That group wants to keep the 166-year-old
Societe Generale firmly anchored in Belgium.
   Both sides have said they wanted to discuss the future of
Societe Generale. But the Franco-Belgian alliance has said De
Benedetti must first renounce his ambition to take a leading role
in the company and stressed it could also act unilaterally.
   De Benedetti still has a public offer going for more shares to
get control of the company. But to extend his offer he needed to
name his allies.
   Cerus said within its alliance, Europe 1992 had 15.9 percent of
Societe Generale's 28.2 million shares, CBI 11.72 percent, Cerus,
9.02 percent, BFC and FAI each 3.24 percent, Odyssey 0.97 percent
and others 2.92 percent.
   Cerus said this breakdown did not include the initial results of
its bid for an additional 7 percent of Societe Generale stock.
   De Benedetti was told to name his allies by Belgium's banking
commission, a regulatory agency, as a condition for getting
approval to extend the bid.
   Societe Generale has a stake in some 1,400 companies around the
world and has important interests in Belgium's energy sector,
technology development, strategic resources and the nation's
relationship with its former colony Zaire.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
