<HEAD>Korean Grain Purchase Mission Goes To United States</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A South Korean feed grain purchase
mission is scheduled to tour the United States later this month to
help reduce the country's trade surplus, the Agriculture and
Fisheries Ministry said Monday.
   Officials said the group, led by President Park Chan-kung of the
Korea Feed Association, will visit Iwoa, Missouri and other states
to puchase 1 million tons of feed grain such as corn and soy beans.
   Park's aides said the mission is scheduled to leave Korea March
20 and stay in the United States for about 10 days.
   The group also will visit Washington to meet with U.S.
administration officials and Congressmen to try to ease growing
American pressure on Korea to buy beef and other American farm
products.
   The United States has threatened to take retaliatory steps if
Korea failed to lift import restrictions. The United States ran a
trade deficit of nearly $10 billion with Korea last year.
