<DOCNO> AP880307-0234 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-07-88 0919EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Japan-ForeignLabor     03-07 0312</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Japan-Foreign Labor,0323</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japanese Favor Accepting Foreign Workers in Certain Conditions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The majority of Japanese responding to an opinion
poll favored accepting temporary foreign workers into Japan if
their skills and effciency are needed, the Economic Planning Agency
said Monday.
   An agency official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
11.0 percent of those responding thought Japan should allow
temporary foreign laborers, such as construction workers, waiters,
maids and waitresses, to find work in Japan without any conditions.
   He said 63 percent said Japan should accept foreign workers
under certain conditions. Only 4.8 percent opposed Japan's
acceptance of any foreign workers at all, the official said.
   The agency questioned 3,000 people aged 20 or over and 1,000
firms throughout the nation at random last October.
   Among Japanese firms that had employed foreign workers, 62.7
percent of those responding said they would employ them in the
future, while 3.1 percent said they would not employ them any more.
The others said they did not know.
   Of the Japanese firms that never had employed foreign workers,
21.9 percent of those responding said they would employ them in the
future and 29.9 percent said they would not.
   In general, Japan now limits foreigners working here to
scholars, language teachers, technicians and performing artists,
including musicians and dancers.
   But an increasig number of foreigners have been working
illegally in Japan, where wages paid in the strong yen currency
make jobs more attractive.
   Last year, the number of foreigners who violated Japan's
immigration laws _ mostly by working illegally _ rose by 33.6
percent from a year earlier to a record 14,129, the Justice
Ministry said Monday.
   A ministry official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
11,307 people were caught overstaying their visas and working
illegally.
   The Labor Ministry asked employers in late January not to hire
any foreigners who have only tourist visas.
</TEXT>
