<HEAD>Common Market's 1987 Exports Down, Industrial Output Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The European Economic Community's
exports dropped 1 percent in 1987, but imports among the 12 nations
edged up by the same amount, bringing the EEC's foreign trade into
balance.
   Eurostat, the Community's statistical service, said the EEC's
sluggish exports picked up in the third quarter, but not enough to
make up for lost ground.
   EEC economic data released Monday also showed that the
Community's industrial production rose an estimated 2 percent in
1987 from the previous year. The report said EEC industrial output
rose 3 percent in the fourth quarter of 1987, the highest growth
rate for the past 18 months.
   Growth was boosted by a steep rise in the production of capital
goods, which gained 3.7 percent in the fourth quarter compared with
the year-earlier period. This was the highest rate of growth for
capital production for two years, Eurostat said.
   Unemployment rose 2.6 percent in January from the previous
month, bringing the number of jobless to 16.7 million, Eurostat
said.
   However, it said that January's unemployment figure was about
2.7 percent below that in January 1987. The drop was caused by a
decline in the numbers of jobless in the Netherlands, Belgium,
Britain, Ireland, France and Denmark.
</TEXT>
