<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Firestone-Pirelli 2ndLd-Writethru   03-07 0649</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Firestone-Pirelli, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0671</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pirelli Bids For Firestone</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 6th graf pvs, Wall Street ..., to UPDATE
with stock price; picks up 7th graf pvs, Firestone stock.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>AKRON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Italian tire manufacturer Pirelli today
launched a $1.86 billion offer for Firestone Tire and Rubber Co.,
complicating Firestone's plan to sell 75 percent of its tire-making
division to Bridgestone of Japan.
   Pirelli, in an advertisement in The Wall Street Journal, offered
$58 a share cash for all 32 million Firestone common shares
outstanding.
   Pirelli said in a statement today its offer was conditioned on
acquiring at least two-thirds of Firestone's shares, on the
agreement beween Firestone and Bridgestone not being signed and on
the removal of Firestone's anti-takeover defenses.
   ``We won't have anything more to say until the board has had an
opportunity to make a review. I would expect that would begin
immediately,'' Firestone spokesman Robert Troyer told the Akron
Beacon Journal on Sunday in a telephone interview from Chicago,
home of Firestone's corporate headquarters.
   An acquisition of Firestone would substantially increase
Pirelli's current 1.5 percent share of the U.S. tire market, the
world's largest. It would also give the Italian company its first
manufacturing facilities in the United States.
   Wall Street analysts had speculated on Thursday that Pirelli
would make an offer for Firestone.
   Firestone's stock leaped $11.37{ a share in early trading today
to $61 a share, above Pirelli's $58-a-share offer, indicating that
speculators expected an even higher offer to emerge.
   Firestone stock closed at $49.62{ Friday, up $5.50 for the week
in heavy trading. Nearly 4.2 million shares of Firestone's common
stock changed hands last week, compared with about 850,000 in an
average week.
   It was not immediately clear what effect an investment or
takeover attempt by Pirelli would have on the pending proposed
joint venture between Firestone and Bridgestone Corp. Firestone's
board and ultimately shareholders will have to decide which offer
to accept.
   Pirelli could block the Bridgestone deal if it was able to
purchase a sufficient number of Firestone shares.
   Pirelli said today that if it was successful in its bid for
Firestone, it would spin off parts of the company to the French
group Michelin.
   Michelin would pay about $650 million to acquire Firestone's
Brazilian holdings as well as Master Care Inc., Firestone's U.S.
service company, Pirelli said.
   Michelin would also have an option to buy 50 percent of
Firestone's synthetic rubber and diversified product holdings in
the United States for about $150 million.
   On Feb. 16, Bridgestone and Firestone said they intended to form
a new Akron-based tire business, to be called Firestone Tire Co.,
that would own Firestone's worldwide tire manufacturing operation.
Bridgestone would own 75 percent of the joint venture.
   Firestone Chairman John J. Nevin has said the company wants to
distribute to shareholders ``a very substantial portion'' of about
$1 billion in cash that would be generated by the joint venture.
   Firestone has been considered an attractive target for both
foreign-based companies because of their interest in gaining U.S.
market share.
   Troyer said Bridgestone officials were notified upon learning of
possible action by Pirelli on Sunday.
   At the time the $1.5 billion Bridgestone deal was announced,
Firestone's board approved an anti-takeover measure that took
effect Tuesday.
   That measure would raise the cost of a takeover by creating a
special class of preferred stock in the event an individual or
group acquired 20 percent or more, or made a tender offer for 20
percent or more, of Firestone's stock without approval of the board.
   In a letter to shareholders released last week, Nevin said the
anti-takeover plan was not intended to prevent a fair offer for the
shares of the company and should not deter anyone from acquiring
the company if the buyer gives shareholders full value and
negotiates in good faith.
   Pirelli, headquartered in Milan, had sales of $3.65 billion last
year.
</TEXT>
