<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Manufacturer'sHanover     03-07 0251</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Manufacturer's Hanover,0260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Say Big Bank Planning Sale of Profitable Subsidiary to Raise Cash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Manufacturers Hanover Corp., wounded from
possibly uncollectable Third World loans, is seeking to sell its
profitable consumer finance unit to raise capital, the Wall Street
Journal reported Monday.
   Quoting banking sources it did not identify, the newspaper said
the nation's sixth-largest banking concern is asking between $500
million and $600 million for Huntingdon Valley, Pa.-based
Manufacturers Hanover Consumer Services Inc., which has about $3
billion in assets.
   The banking company has been forced to take austerity measures
because of a $1.14 billion loss last year, due mainly to a $1.7
billion addition to reserves that reflected the questionable
collectability of some Third World loans, a problem afflicting many
American banks.
   John Meyers, a Manufacturers Hanover spokesman in New York, said
he could not comment on the Journal report. But he said the bank
has consistently stated it would rebuild capital partly via
property sales and expense cuts.
   ``We've said all along there is a host of assets we can realize
gains on,'' Meyers said. ``It is part of our game plan to get
shareholder equity replenished.''
   Banking industry analysts have said Manufacturers Hanover's
consumer finance business is considered highly prized and
profitable within the company, so a sale would reflect on the
seriousness of the bank's capital needs.
   On the other hand, the consumer finance unit is a stand-alone
operation, so it could be sold much more easily that other company
property.
</TEXT>
