<1ST_LINE>r f BC-PaperForecast     03-07 0414</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Paper Forecast,0429</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Paper Group Forecasts Record Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Production in the U.S. paper industry appears
poised for a third consecutive record-breaking year as demand
remains strong for all major grades of paper and paperboard, an
industry trade association said Monday.
   The American Paper Institute, a trade association for American
pulp, paper and paperboard companies, said production is running at
a rate of 75 million tons a year, or about 3 percent above its pace
at the same point last year.
   Production for all of 1987 amounted to a record 74.4 million
tons, up from 70.9 million tons in 1986, and is expected to rise by
about 2 percent in 1988, according to figures supplied by the trade
association.
   The group's forecast was released as it began its national
conference.
   The institute's president, Red Cavaney, said the forecast for
1988 presumes avoiding a recession, a pro-growth trade policy, a
fairly low interest rate climate and no major tax increases.
   Last year was also a record in terms of the dollar value of
paper and paperboard sales, the group said. It said it expects
final figures for 1987 will show sales of about $87 billion, or 16
percent more than the previous high of $74.8 billion set in 1986.
   The paper industry derived its strength in 1987 from heightened
demand in the various markets its serves, the institute said.
   Demand for white papers, for instance, reflected trends such as
increased use of office copy and computer printout papers and of
envelopes.
   Strength in direct-mail advertising helped fuel robust growth in
commercial printing, stimulating printing paper demand, the paper
institute said.
   Paperboard production set a record last year as packaged goods
production surged, triggering increased demand for paper used for
shipping containers, folding cartons and fiber cans, the institute
said.
   Newspapers and the high quality color-printed advertising pieces
that retailers and businesses use to reach their customers
performed strongly in 1987, the group said, pushing newsprint
production to a new high last year.
   Exports of market pulp and paper products reached a high in 1987
as a decline in the dollar made them more competitive with prices
charged overseas, the institute said.
   While sales surged in 1987, so did the profits of paper
companies that had already begun aggressive cost-containment
programs, the institute said.
   It said after-tax profits in the U.S. paper industry rose 56
percent in the first three quarters of 1987, reaching a decade high
of 5.7 percent of sales.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
