<FILEID>AP-NR-03-07-88 1239EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Scotus-Taxes     03-07 0415</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Taxes,0431</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>No Tax Break From Stock Losses, Court Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Businesses that lose money from the sale of
stock aren't entitled to special tax breaks no matter why the stock
was purchased, the Supreme Court decided today.
   The court, voting 8-0, ruled against an Arkansas conglomerate
that sought to claim as an ordinary-loss deduction for federal tax
purposes a $10 million loss from the sale of stock in a Texas bank
it once controlled.
   Arkansas Best Corp. of Fort Smith in 1969 had acquired more than
65 percent of the stock of National Bank of Commerce, the fourth
largest bank in Dallas.
   Congress passed a law in 1970 that prohibited conglomerates that
owned a bank from expanding their non-bank business through new
acquisitions in other industries.
   Arkansas Best, which owns trucking, furniture manufacturing,
data processing and other businesses, decided to divest itself of
the bank stock. The 1970 law gave it 10 years to sell the bank
stock.
   Because of public awareness that Arkansas Best was under legal
obligation to divest itself, disposing of the bank stock without
taking a big loss was difficult.
   At the same time, the bank's finances were deteriorating.
Arkansas Best therefore acquired additional stock in the bank in an
attempt to keep it solvent.
   The conglomerate began selling off the bank stock in 1975, and
sought to claim the losses as ordinary losses rather than capital
losses _ a tax advantage.
   The Internal Revenue Service ruled that the losses suffered by
Arkansas Best were capital losses. The IRS rejected Arkansas Best's
arguments that the stock was not bought for typical investment
purposes but for business purposes _ and therefore its sale should
yield ordinary losses.
   The 8th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals agreed with the IRS but
other federal appeals courts had reached conflicting conclusions.
   Writing for the high court today, Justice Thurgood Marshall said
motivation behind the stock purchase is irrelevant ``to the
question whether the asset is property held by a taxpayer ... and
is thus within (federal tax law's) general definition of capital
asset.''
   ``Because the capital stock held by (Arkansas Best) falls within
the broad definition of the term `capital asset' in (the tax code)
and is outside the classes of property excluded from capital-asset
status, the loss arising from the sale of the stock is a capital
loss,'' Marshall said.
   Justice Anthony M. Kennedy did not participate in the decision.
   The case is Arkansas Best vs. Commissioner of Internal Revenue,
86-751.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880307-0244 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-07-88 1245EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Bonds     03-07 0499</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bonds,0517</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bond Prices Little Changed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bond prices and interest rates stabilized in
quiet early trading today following Friday's sell-off.
   ``The market seems to be on dead center right now,'' said
Marshall B. Front, an economist at Stein Roe & Farnham, a Chicago
investment and mutual-fund management firm. ``There doesn't seem to
be any news affecting the market.''
   By midday, the Treasury's 30-year bond was up about 1-32 point
while its yield, which moves inversely to its price, slipped to
8.46 percent from 8.47 percent late Friday.
   The bellwether issue had plunged about two points, or $20 per
$1,000 in face amount, on Friday, after the government reported
unexpectedly high February employment levels, raising doubts about
forecasts of an economic slowdown later this year.
   The government said the economy created half a million jobs last
month, dropping the civilian unemployment rate to 5.7 percent, its
lowest since 1979. The January rate had been 5.8 percent.
   Front said the market was currently involved in a ``tug of war''
of sorts on the outlook for interest rates.
   ``The bulls point to lower commodity prices _ the price of gold
continues to fall, oil prices continue to slip _ and other signs of
weakness in economic activity,'' he said. ``The bears look at the
employment numbers ... which were shockingly good and say ... the
economy is likely to accelerate.
   ``I think a lot of people are going back to their drawing
boards.''
   Interest rates have fallen sharply since fears of recession
surfaced after the stock market crash five months ago. But
bondholders worry that with some signs of economic growth, the
Federal Reserve may want to tighten its credit policies, thus
pushing interest rates higher, to prevent inflation from heating up.
   In the secondary market for Treasury bonds today, prices of
short-term governments were unchanged, intermediate maturities rose
1-32 point and 20-year issues were off 1-32 point, according to
figures provided by Telerate Inc.
   The movement of a point is equivalent to a change of $10 in the
price of a bond with a $1,000 face value.
   The Merrill Lynch Daily Treasury Index, which measures price
movements on all outstanding Treasury issues with maturities of a
year or longer, fell 0.01 to 113.3. The Shearson Lehman Daily
Treasury Bond Index, which makes a similar measurement, lost 0.04
to 1,183.34.
   In corporate trading, industrials and utilities were unchanged
in light trading, according to the investment firm of Salomon
Brothers Inc.
   Moody's Investment Grade Corporate Bond Index, which measures
price movements on 80 corporate bonds with maturities of five years
or longer, was off 0.06 to 284.36.
   Yields on three-month Treasury bills were up 2 basis points to
5.72 percent. A basis point is one-hundredth of a percentage point.
Six-month bills -fell 1 basis point to 5.94 percent and one-year
bills were unchanged at 6.27 percent.
   The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between
banks, traded at 6 9-16 percent, up from 6{ percent late Friday.
</TEXT>
