<HEAD>Third Qtr Earnings Up 22 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leading foodmaker H.J. Heinz Co. reported a 22
percent surge in third-quarter earnings Monday, attributing the
improvement to higher sales volume, acquisitions and the beneficial
effects of a cheaper dollar.
   The company said earnings for the three months ended Jan. 27
totaled $91 million or 69 cents a share, compared with $74.7
million or 55 cents a share in the year-earlier period. Sales
totaled $1.25 billion vs. $1.08 billion, a 15 percent rise.
   ``We are encouraged by the earnings record achieved to date
through our existing business base as well as the superior market
opportunities offered by our strategic world-wide acquisitions,''
said Chairman Anthony J.F. O'Reilly. ``We are optimistic that we
will again achieve fiscal year results consisted with our
historical trends.''
   The Pittsburgh-based company embarked on a series of
acquisitions last year, notably in the pet-food business, in which
it bought Mavar and California Home Brands, two American concerns.
Heinz also recently acquired Orlando S.A., an important Spanish
food company.
   The dollar's depreciation also helped Heinz because its
U.S.-produced foods became more competitive overseas. At the same
time, profits from goods produced and sold by Heinz's foreign
operations rose when converted into dollars.
   For the nine-months ended Jan. 27, Heinz said it earned $284.3
million or $2.14 a share, a 16.3 percent gain over the $244.4
million or $1.78 a share in the year-earlier period. Sales rose 13
percent from $3.3 billion to $3.8 billion.
</TEXT>
