<FILEID>AP-NR-03-07-88 1326EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-USTourism Bjt   03-07 0592</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US Tourism, Bjt,0614</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cheap New World: Europeans Rediscovering America</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NESHA STARCEVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Spurred by the low dollar and
cheaper air fares, Europeans from Spain to Scandinavia are
rediscovering America at a record pace.
   Tourist visa applications are flooding U.S. consulates across
Western Europe, and tour operators say the number of bookings to
the United States is up sharply from last year's record.
   ``The numbers (of visa applicants) are increasing
dramatically,'' said Ira Levy, chief of the non-immigrant visa
branch at the U.S. Embassy in London.
   Donald Mudd, chief of consular services at the U.S. Consulate in
Frankfurt, said the consulate issued about 600,000 tourist visas
last year.
   ``We expect a 30 percent to 50 percent rise this year, and this
pretty much reflects the rest of Western Europe,'' Mudd told The
Associated Press.
   The Association of European Airlines, which includes 21 major
airline companies, said the total number of Europeans flying to the
United States has increased about 48 percent since 1985.
   According to the most recent statistics available to the
Brussels-based association, 7.2 million Europeans took flights to
the United States from January to October 1987.
   Officials across Western Europe polled by the AP said the first
two months of this year indicate that 1988 will be a boom year for
travel to the United States.
   Britain and West Germany provide the bulk of tourists visiting
the United States, and the two countries are expected to combine
for nearly 2 million U.S. trips this year.
   Levy said the number of non-immigrant visas issued in Britain
for the United States was expected to reach 900,000 this year from
642,000 in 1987.
   January saw a 69 percent increase in non-immigant visas over
January 1987, and February figures rose 66 percent over the same
month last year, Levy said.
   Sheila Beecham, owner of American Round-up, a travel agency in
Hemel Hempstead, 25 miles north of London, said her business was
flourishing.
   ``The growth in America travel because of the dollar recently is
tremendous. In the last three months I've had the same amount of
business as all last year,'' said Ms. Beecham, whose agency
specializes in adventure vacations to the Western states.
   In West Germany, where the dollar has dropped 50 percent in
three years, travel agencies also are thriving as U.S. tours become
cheaper.
   ``Our January figures are 25 percent over last January's when we
had 25,705 bookings,'' said Rolf Nielander of Deutsches Reisebuero,
a travel agency.
   His agency offers two-week trips to Florida for $1,000 dollars,
only $350 more than a two-week stay at a Mediterranean resort.
   The Swiss are also frequent international travelers: 235,000 of
them visited the United States last year, a 27 percent increase
over 1986. A further rise is expected this year.
   In Greece, a Pam Am official in Athens said bookings for U.S.
destinations were up 30 percent this year compared with 1987.
   Alex Pantelides, manager of Manos Travel System, Greece's
largest travel agency, said the dollar's drop was a windfall for
U.S. trips.
   ``America is much better value for money compared to Europe.''
   In Italy, Mark Dillen, spokesman for the American Embassy in
Rome, said there has been a 12 percent increase in the past five
months in tourist visa applications for the United States, compared
with the same period in 1987.
   In Spain, U.S. officials reported a 60 percent to 70 percent
rise in the number of visa applications, and in the Netherlands
they said it was up 38 percent in the last five months.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
