<FILEID>AP-NR-03-07-88 1353EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Fireman'sFund     03-07 0218</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Fireman's Fund,0225</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Insurance Concern Buys Back Stock From American Express</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Insurance giant Fireman's Fund Corp. will
purchase 8.5 million of its stock from American Express Co. for
$200 million plus 3 million shares of American Express stock, both
companies announced Monday.
   Based on American Express's stock price of $27.50 a share Monday
afternoon, the agreement would be worth about $282.5 million.
   Fireman's Fund also has an option to purchase an additional 4.5
million of its shares from American Express for $162 million, the
companies said.
   If the agreement is approved by boards of both companies,
Fireman's Fund will terminate a previously announced plan to
repurchase some of its stock on the open market or via a private
purchase, the companies said in a statement.
   American Express once owned 100 percent of Fireman's Fund shares
but later decided to get out of the property and casualty insurance
business and began selling the company's stock. Upon completion of
the agreement announced Monday, American Express would own 20
percent of Fireman's Fund.
   American Express is a diversified financial and travel services
concern that owns Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc., one of the largest
Wall Street brokerages. Fireman's Fund is an insurance holding
company that owns Fireman's Fund Insurance Co., one of the largest
property-casualty insurers.
</TEXT>
