<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Dollar-Gold     03-07 0304</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Dollar-Gold,0317</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Falls In Europe, Gold Varies</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: AMer planned by 5:30 p.m. EST</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar fell against most major currencies
in European trading Monday. Gold prices were mixed.
   Foreign exchange dealers said the British pound gained almost 4
cents against the dollar _ a remarkable one-day advance _ and also
rose against every other currency.
   Reports in London that British interest rates would stay high
and that the economy was growing at a strong pace were credited for
the pound's strength.
   Sterling's rise quickened when it became clear the state-run
Bank of England was not selling pounds to prevent sterling from
rising against the West German mark.
   A higher exchange rate means British goods become more expensive
abroad. The bank's refusal to act was in line with government
policy to encourage companies to be more competitive by becoming
more efficient.
   In London, one British pound cost $1.8135 late Monday, up from
$1.7740 late Friday.
   Other late rates for the dollar late Monday, compared with late
Friday's rates, included: 1.6765 West German marks, down from
1.6940; 1.3870 Swiss francs, down from 1.4030; 5.6880 French
francs, down from 5.7300; 1.8840 Dutch guilders, down from 1.9010;
1.239.75 Italian lire, down from 1,248.00; and 1.2562 Canadian
dollars, up from 1.2547.
   In Tokyo earlier, the dollar closed at 128.87 Japanese yen, down
from 129.22 late Friday.In London late Monday, the dollar traded at
128.30 yen.
   Gold prices were mixed. In London, the major trading center,
gold closed at a late bid price of $437.20 a troy ounce, down from
$437.50 late Friday. The late bid price in Zurich was $436, up from
$432 late Friday.
   Earlier in Hong Kong, gold closed at $438.75, up from $438.21.
   Silver bullion traded late in London at a bid $6.42 a troy
ounce, up from $6.41.
</TEXT>
