<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreet2pm     03-07 0299</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 2pm,0315</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market gave ground today amid concern
over the interest-rate outlook.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials dropped 11.11 to
2,046.75 by 2 p.m. on Wall Street.
   Losers outnumbered gainers by about 9 to 8 in the overall tally
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 693 up, 783 down and
458 unchanged.
   Prices and interest rates showed little change in the bond
market today. But developments late last week raised concern that
the drop in interest rates since last fall had about run its course.
   Rates rose sharply on Friday after the Labor Department reported
much stronger growth in employment than expected for February.
   If the economy is robust enough to support a big increase in
jobs, credit-market traders reason, the Federal Reserve is unlikely
to take any further steps soon to relax its credit policy.
   Given that prospect, investors seemed to be focusing their
attention mainly on numerous stocks involved in takeovers and other
deals.
   Firestone Tire & Rubber jumped 12 to 61|. Pirelli Group of Italy
made a $58-a-share bid to acquire the company, which is planning to
sell its tire business to Japan's Bridgestone Corp.
   Roper Corp. climbed 10~ to 48\. General Electric made a
$45-a-share offer for Roper, which previously agreed to be taken
over by Whirlpool Corp. for $37.50 a share.
   Mobil gained 1 to 44|. The company said it had reached a
definitive agreement to sell its Montgomery Ward subsidiary to a
group led by Ward's top management.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks fell
.49 to 149.94. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was down .31 at 293.43.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 110.30 million shares with two
hours to go.
</TEXT>
