<FILEID>AP-NR-03-07-88 1553EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-WeeklySteel     03-07 0171</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Weekly Steel,0173</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Steel Output Fell 1.5 Percent in Week Ended March 5</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Steel production fell to 1.971 million tons in
the week ended March 5, a decrease of 1.5 percent from the previous
week's 2.002 million tons, the American Iron and Steel Institute
reported Monday.
   The industry's production amounted to 91.8 percent of capacity
during the week, compared with 93.2 percent in the previous week.
   Estimated figures for the year to date showed production at
17.769 million net tons, an increase of 38.4 percent from the
12.837 million net tons in the previous year. The steel operations
of USX Corp., the nation's largest steel producer, were shut down
by a strike during the first month of 1987.
   Production so far this year used 89.1 percent of capacity,
compared with 64.9 percent a year earlier.
   Net tonnage by district for the week ended March 5: Northeast
Coast, 284,000; Pittsburgh, 194,000; Youngstown, 122,000; Lake
Erie, 167,000; Detroit, 172,000; Chicago, 518,000; Midwest,
197,000; Southern, 221,000; and Western, 97,000.
</TEXT>
