<FILEID>AP-NR-03-07-88 1604EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f BC-RigCount     03-07 0236</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Rig Count,0245</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rig Count Drops By Five To Total 978</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The number of oil and gas rigs working in the
United States decreased by five this week to total 978, Baker
Hughes Inc. announced.
   The total reflects the number of rigs actively exploring for oil
as of last Friday, not the number of rigs producing oil. The
previous week, the count had increased by five to 983.
   A year ago, the rig count was 766, Baker Hughes announced Monday.
   Houston-based Baker Hughes, an oil toolmaker, tallies the number
of working rigs and the count is the widely-watched industry index
of drilling activity.
   Hughes Tool Co., which merged last year with Baker International
Corp. of Orange, Calif., has kept track of the number of working
rigs since 1940.
   The rig count reached a peak of 4,500 active rigs in December
1981 _ the height of the oil boom. But as oil prices plunged to
less than $10 per 42-gallon barrel in the summer of 1986, the count
fell to 663, the lowest since Hughes began compiling figures.
   Among the major oil producing states, Oklahoma gained seven rigs
this week, Wyoming gained five, while Colorado, New Mexico and Ohio
increased by two each.
   The rig count in Michigan dropped by one, while California,
Kansas, and Louisiana each lost three. Texas and Pennsylvania each
lost four rigs and Wyoming's rig count dropped by five.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
