<1ST_LINE>u f AM-HiringSurvey     03-07 0285</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hiring Survey,0296</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Strong Second-Quarter Growth in Hiring Predicted</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A significant number of American companies will
bolster hiring this spring, a leading temporary job service said
Monday in an unusually optimistic quarterly forecast on U.S.
employment.
   Manpower Inc. said its Employment Outlook Survey indicated 29
percent of respondents plan to raise employment rolls in the
April-June quarter, while 6 percent expect declines. Sixty-two
percent plan no change and 3 percent don't know, the survey stated.
   Mitchell S. Fromstein, Manpower president, said it was the
strongest spring hiring forecast in four years and suggested
manufacturers in all regions of the country are unusually buoyant
about the economy.
   Makers of large durable goods are among the most optimistic of
all employers, with 32 percent planning payroll increases and 7
percent planning cutbacks, the survey showed.
   Among construction companies, 36 percent anticipate payroll
increases and 7 percent anticipate cutbacks. Among retailers, 31
percent plan increased payrolls and 6 percent plan decreases.
   Even in the financial services industry, which was particularly
affected by the October collapse in stock prices, the spring hiring
forecast was still optimistic. Twenty-three percent of respondents
plan to add employees and 7 percent will cut back.
   Manpower has issued the quarterly survey for the past 12 years
and calls it as a significant indicator of employment trends.
   Conducted in last two weeks of February, the survey was based on
telephone interviews with more than 13,000 public and private
employers in 401 U.S. cities. The margin of error is 5 percent, the
company said.
   Based in Milwaukee, Manpower describes itself as the world's
largest temporary service firm, annually providing jobs to more
than 700,000 people through 1,350 offices in 33 countries.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
