<1ST_LINE>u f AM-WallStreet 1stLd-Writethru   03-07 0490</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wall Street, 1st Ld-Writethru,0511</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Takeover news and speculation provided most of
the excitement in an otherwise quiet, drifting stock market session
Monday.
   Analysts said the general market was held back by new doubts
about the outlook for interest rates.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials slipped 1.49 to 2,056.37.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by about 8 to 7 on the New
York Stock Exchange, with 847 up, 725 down and 417 unchanged.
   Big Board volume came to 152.58 million shares, down from 201.41
million in the previous session. The NYSE's composite index edged
up .10 to 150.53.
   Prices declined slightly in the bond market, pushing yields on
long-term Treasury bonds up to the neighborhood of 8.5 percent.
Developments late last week raised concern that the drop in
interest rates since last fall had about run its course.
   Rates rose sharply on Friday after the Labor Department reported
much stronger growth in employment than expected for February.
   If the economy is robust enough to support a big increase in
jobs, credit-market traders reason, the Federal Reserve is unlikely
to take any further steps soon to relax its credit policy.
   Given that prospect, investors seemed to be focusing their
attention mainly on numerous stocks involved in takeovers and other
deals.
   Firestone Tire & Rubber led the active list, up 13{ at 63[.
Pirelli Group of Italy made a $58-a-share bid to acquire the
company, which is planning to sell its tire business to Japan's
Bridgestone Corp.
   Roper Corp. climbed 11 to 48]. General Electric made a
$45-a-share offer for Roper, which previously agreed to be taken
over by Whirlpool Corp. for $37.50 a share.
   Mobil gained 1[ to 44}. The company said it had reached a
definitive agreement to sell its Montgomery Ward subsidiary to a
group led by Ward's top management.
   Lorimar Telepictures, traded on the American Stock Exchange,
rose 2] to 14~. The company said it had been approached by Warner
Communications for talks about a possible business combination.
   Moore McCormack Resources, which opposed a $31-a-share offer
from Southdown Inc., added | to 36{.
   Analysts also noted buying of some technology issues. Compaq
Computer gained 2 to 54; Cullinet Software ~ to 6~; Digital
Equipment 2} to 124]; National Semiconductor { to 12{, and Ultimate
Corp. 1] to 15[.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market increased $2.48 billion, or 0.09
percent, in value.
   Nationwide turnover in NYSE-listed issues, including trades in
those stocks on regional exchanges and in the over-the-counter
market, totaled 180.64 million shares.
   Standard & Poor's index of 400 industrials rose .54 to 309.52,
and S&P's 500-stock composite index was up .08 at 267.38.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market
gained 1.18 to 374.54. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index closed at 294.14, up .40.
</TEXT>
