<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp     03-07 0733</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp,0762</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Livestock Futures Soar As Market Looks Forward To Greater Demand</HEAD>
<BYLINE>DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Livestock and meat futures prices rose sharply Monday as traders
looked beyond the cash market's current problems and saw meat sales
improving in the months ahead.
   On other markets, energy futures slid lower; grains and soybeans
were mostly higher; precious metals retreated; and stock-index
futures advanced.
   Slack retail demand for meat during Lent led to a slowdown in
slaughters last week, prompting fears of a growing supply of
slaughter-ready cattle and hogs.
   Analysts said those fears, along with the closing of at least
one major beef packing plant, were largely responsible for losses
on livestock futures last week at the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   But indications of a cattle buildup did not surface Monday,
leading many traders to rethink their positions and look ahead to a
resurgence in demand after Easter, analysts said.
   ``Prices went down last week on ideas we were backing up cattle
(but) we haven't seen any proof of that yet,'' said Charlie
Richardson, an analyst in Denver for Lind-Waldock & Co.
   In Chicago, Philip Stanley of Thomson-McKinnon Securities Inc.
said traders had turned their attention to the future and away from
the industry's current woes.
   ``They're thinking that retail demand will pick up, packers will
have to accumulate supplies and the cattle feeders will reap the
profits by being able to sell cattle at higher prices,'' Stanley
said.
   Richardson said some traders also bought livestock futures on
ideas that prices for future delivery of cattle and hogs had fallen
more sharply than conditions warranted.
   And some were betting that a winter storm moving into the Great
Plains would disrupt the movement of animals to market, resulting
in temporarily tight supplies and higher prices, Richardson said.
   The bullish enthusiasm for cattle futures overflowed into the
pork pits, analysts said.
   Live cattle settled .87 cent to 1.38 cents higher with the
contract for delivery in April at 71.55 cents a pound; feeder
cattle were .80 cent to 1.10 cents higher with March at 80.35 cents
a pound; hogs were .25 cent to 1.25 cents higher with April at
43.60 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were 1.20 cents to 1.85
cents higher with March at 54.70 cents a pound.
   Energy futures prices retreated in moderate trading on the New
York Mercantile Exchange following a slight advance in the previous
session.
   Analysts attributed the decline to speculation that some member
nations of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries were
selling oil at a discount.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 15 cents to 22 cents
lower with April at $15.37 a barrel; heating oil was .13 cent to
.25 cent lower with April at 43.41 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .34 cent to .57 cent lower with April at 43.94 cents a
gallon.
   Grain and soybean futures finished mostly higher on the Chicago
Board of Trade, although soybean futures were mixed.
   Expectations of new export business supported the markets.
   The Agriculture Department announced after the close that it had
sold 1.6 million bushels of wheat Friday in the last of last week's
three auctions for surplus, government-owned wheat.
   The USDA had targeted 10 million bushels for sale at that
auction.
   The agency also announced it would hold three auctions a week,
each with a 10-million-bushel target, through March 25.
   Wheat settled } cent to 2 cents higher with March at $3.04 a
bushel; corn was 1{ cents to 2} cents higher with March at $2.00} a
bushel; oats were \ cent to 4 cents higher with March at $1.90} a
bushel; soybeans were 1\ cent lower to 2{ cents higher with March
at $6.13} a bushel.
   Gold and silver futures retreated slightly on the Commodity
Exchange in New York.
   But despite its weak tone, the market appeared to have shaken
off the recessionary expectactions that had weighed on prices in
recent weeks, said Craig Sloane, an analyst in New York with Smith
Barney, Harris Upham & Co.
   Gold settled 10 cents to 30 cents lower with April at $438.60 a
troy ounce; silver was 3.2 cents to 3.5 cents lower with March at
$6.395 a troy ounce.
   Stock-index futures advanced on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange,
where the contract for March delivery of the Standard & Poor's 500
index settled 1.10 points higher at 268.30. The underlying spot
index closed nearly unchanged at 267.38.
</TEXT>
