<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Iacocca-Book     03-07 0215</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iacocca-Book,0223</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Second Iacocca Book To Appear June 1</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lee Iacocca's second book, a meditation on
lessons he has learned in business and private life and how they
can be applied to modern problems, will go on sale June 1, his
publisher announced Monday.
   The book, entitled ``Talking Straight,'' was written with New
York Times reporter Sonny Kleinfield. A first printing of at least
500,000 copies is planned, according tom Stuart Applebaum, a
spokesman for Bantam Books.
   Iacocca draws upon his experiences he has had as son, husband,
father, friend and Chrysler Corp. chairman to comment on the
problems of Wall Street, Washington and the world.
   ``He proposes fresh answers to some very tough questions that we
face as individuals and as a nation, perhaps most important among
them, how do we retrieve the values our parents and grandparents
gave us?'' said Linda Grey, president and publisher of Bantam.
   Iacocca's first book, ``Iacocca: An Autobiography,'' has sold
more than 2.6 million copies in hardcover; it was on the New York
Times bestseller list for 80 weeks, 40 of them in first place. It
also has sold more than 3.5 million in paperback, and has been
published in 18 languages.
   He has been working on the new book since October 1986.
</TEXT>
