<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Black&Decker     03-07 0307</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Black & Decker,0315</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American Standard To Consider Sweetened Black & Decker Buyout
Offer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Standard Inc. said Monday its board of
directors would consider the latest hostile buyout offer from Black
& Decker Corp. and indicated it might sweeten its own alternative
plan a second time.
   Black & Decker, which has been pursuing American Standard since
late January, last Friday sweetened its outstanding tender offer to
$73 a share from $68 for American Standard's 31 million common
shares outstanding, or a total of about $2.26 billion.
   That move came after American Standard, a plumbing and air
conditioning maker, sweetened its defensive recapitalization plan
to $2.3 billion.
   The revised recapitalization announced Friday would pay
shareholders $64 in cash, $5 in securities and one share of stock
in the recapitalized company for each old share. The earlier cash
portion was $59 a share.
   American Standard rose 75 cents to $73.25 a share Monday on the
New York Stock Exchange. Black & Decker dipped 37{ cents to $18 a
share, a decline stemming partly from an adjustment for a dividend
payment.
   William B. Boyd, American Standard's chairman and chief
executive, said the company's recapitalization plan already was
financially superior to Black & Decker's sweetened tender offer and
advised shareholders not to tender their stock.
   ``In the meantime, stockholders should be aware that, if Black &
Decker increases its offer beyond the values we can achieve for our
stockholders in a recapitalization, we would vigorously pursue
other alternatives in order to enhance stockholder value,'' Boyd
stated.
   He also said American Standard was ``working on ways to further
improve'' its recapitalization plan, but did not elaborate.
   Black & Decker, a Towson, Md.-based maker of tools and
appliances, also has indicated it would attempt to win shareholder
support for taking control of American Standard's board of
directors.
</TEXT>
