<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Lorimar-Warner 1stLd-Writethru   03-07 0723</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lorimar-Warner, 1st Ld-Writethru,0749</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lorimar Discussing Business Combination with Warner</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Retransmitting to show f0257 is a writethru.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROGER GILLOTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CULVER CITY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Loss-plagued Lorimar-Telepictures
Corp., which was formed two years ago by a merger but has seen its
aggressive expansion plans disintegrate, said Monday it is
discussing the possibility of being acquired by Warner
Communications Inc.
   Word of the negotiations helped push Lorimar's stock price up
$2.50 a share to $15. In the past year, the stock has traded as
high as $25.25 and as low as $6.62{.
   ``I'd say the odds (of a takeover) are 50-50,'' said Harold
Vogel, an entertainment industry analyst with Merrill Lynch in New
York.
   He estimated the final price of a deal would be ``somewhere
between $14 and the high teens.''
   Lorimar has about 45.9 million shares outstanding.
   In a brief statement, Lorimar, a leading supplier of original
television programming, said it was approached by New York-based
Warner and preliminary talks were under way ``to explore the
desirability of a business combination.''
   However, Lorimar said its board has made no decision as to
whether such a deal would be in the best interests of shareholders.
   The company also noted it has been approached about possible
mergers in the past and nothing came of those overtures.
   The Culver City-based company was formed in February 1986 by the
stock-swap combination of Lorimar Inc., best known as the producer
of such long-running television series as ``Dallas'' and ``Knots
Landing,'' and New York-based Telepictures Corp., which got most of
its revenue from animated shows such as ``Thundercats'' and such
programs as ``Peoples Court'' and ``Love Connection.''
   For the 1987-88 television season, the company is producing 12
hours of prime time and 16{ hours of syndicated shows, including
``The Days and Nights of Molly Dodd,'' ``Mama's Family,'' ``It's a
Living'' and ``She's the Sheriff.''
   For the first nine months of of its current fiscal year, Lorimar
posted a loss of $82.6 million on revenues of $616.8 million. The
deficit included $45 million in writedowns on five movies and $22
million in reserves for possible future losses in its home-video
unit.
   Management of both its movie and home-video units was recently
ousted.
   For fiscal 1987 ended last March 31, the company lost $58.6
million, mostly because of restructuring costs, on revenues of
$766.2 million.
   In recent years, Lorimar sought to expand far beyond its
successful roots as a producer of television shows.
   It bought advertising agencies, sought to build a network of
television stations and acquired a children's publishing unit, but
it has shed most of those operations in a back-to-basics
restructuring announced last June.
   The company has just completed the sale of the ad agencies _
Bozell, Jacobs, Kenyon & Eckhardt Inc. and Poppe Tyson Inc. _ to
members of their management for about $100 million, posting a
pre-tax profit of $16 million.
   In late 1986, Lorimar had agreed to buy seven big-city Storer
and Wometco television stations from Kohlberg, Kravis & Roberts for
$1.85 billion. The move would have given Lorimar 12 stations around
the U.S. and in Puerto Rico.
   However, the deal with Kohlberg collapsed as the bottom fell out
of the market for television stations, and the company has sold
some of the stations it already owned and is seeking buyers for the
remainder.
   The company also sold its children's publishing unit.
   Warner is the parent of Warner Bros. studio, is a leading record
producer and is a major cable television operator.
   Warner's financial results have been strong.
   In 1987, its profit rose 77 percent to $328.1 million, or $2.09
a share, from $185.8 million, of $1.26 a share, the previous year.
   The 1987 figures included a net gain of $37.3 million on the
sale of investments while the 1986 results included a gain of $48.4
million from the sale of investments and a gain from discontinued
operations.
   Revenue for 1987 rose 20 percent to $3.4 billion from $2.84
billion.
   Its Warner Bros. film unit had the best year in its history,
with an operating profit of $176.4 million, compared to $172.2
million in 1986.
   Warner's music operation posted a 1987 operating profit of
$213.9 million, up from $150.6 million, and operating profit from
the cable and broadcasting division jumped to $46.1 million for the
year from $16.2 million in 1986.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
