<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Robins     03-07 0240</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Robins,0251</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>A.H. Robins Reports Net Loss Despite Record Sales</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Although sales for the A.H. Robins Co.
jumped 11 percent for the final three months of 1987, the
pharmaceutical company reported a net loss of $1.69 billion for the
period because of costs related to its Dalkon Shield birth-control
device.
   Robins said its loss in the period compared to a profit of $26.2
million, or $1.08 a share, in the same period a year earlier.
Revenue rose to $234.8 million from $210.8 million a year earlier.
   For all of 1987, Robins suffered a loss of $1.63 billion
compared to a profit of $81.8 million, or $3.38 a share, in 1986.
Revenue for the year rose to $855.8 million from $789.9 million.
   Robins was forced to set aside $1.75 billion last year to help
cover the costs of claims concerning women who were injured by the
Dalkon Shield, which has been discontinued.
   The accrual represents the difference between the $2.30 billion
provided in the company's fifth amended reorganization plan and the
$548 million which remained from the reserve for Dalkon Shield
claims established by the company in 1984.
   Robins' results were also hurt by the costs of its Chapter 11
reorganization in federal bankruptcy court.
   E. Claiborne Robins Jr., the president and chief executive, said
consumer products in the U.S., international operations and medical
instruments were the principal contributors to the higher sales for
the year.
</TEXT>
