<1ST_LINE>u f AM-UAW-Chrysler     03-07 0394</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UAW-Chrysler,0409</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tentative Settlement Ends Threat of Strike at Key Stamping Plant</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANET BRAUNSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tentative settlement reached early Monday
between the United Auto Workers union and Chrysler Corp., derailing
the threat of a strike at a key Sterling Heights stamping plant.
   ``Obviously, the company is hopeful that the workers will ratify
the agreement and that the threat of a strike will disappear,''
Chrysler spokesman Lloyd Northard said.
   Sterling Heights makes metal hoods and trunk lids for all
domestically made Chrysler cars and most trucks and makes fuel
tanks for all Chrysler cars except one.
   A strike there would soon have hurt all Chrysler production, and
additional strikes at a few other key plants could have crippled
Chrysler within days.
   UAW Vice President Marc Stepp had joined negotiations between
Chrysler and UAW Local 1264 on Friday, a day after Chrysler
announced it would not sell its Acustar Inc. parts subsidiary.
   The union would have been the first to receive Stepp's
permission to strike over local issues such as health-and-safety
grievances and violation of work rules.
   Stepp had promised to give immediate strike authorization to all
locals with legitimate grievances. But after Chrysler decided to
keep its 28,000-worker Acustar subsidiary, he began moving to
resolve local disputes.
   Stepp and other negotiators bargained through the weekend and
reached a tentative settlement on Local 1264's grievances at 5 a.m.
Monday, the union said. Stepp was unavailable for comment Monday.
   The union said it was withholding details of the agreement until
March 11, when the local's 3,600 active and 500 laid-off members
will vote on the settlement.
   ``We saved a lot of jobs and got additional jobs,'' said Fred
O'Brien, Local 1264 recording secretary and a member of the local's
bargaining committee.
   O'Brien said Chrysler agreed to add workers to clean up oil that
leaks from the plants massive presses onto the shop floor and to
clean and repair the machines as a matter of routine.
   Workers had complained that because the presses are run around
the clock, they don't receive adequate maintenance, particularly
cleaning, and the machines and the floors around them are covered
with oil and dirt.
   Local 1264 had accumulated nearly 140 unresolved grievances
since last year. Other locals had been gathering grievances so they
could be ready to strike if Chrysler had decided to sell Acustar.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
