<DOCNO> AP880307-0274 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-07-88 1941EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Homestake-Pickens     03-07 0348</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Homestake-Pickens,0361</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Homestake Turns Down Pickens Takeover Offer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Homestake Mining Co. rejected as inadequate
an unsolicited $1.88 billion buyout offer from the partnership led
by T. boone Pickens on Monday and said it wished to remain
independent.
   The board of directors of Homestake, the nation's biggest gold
producer, unanimously rejected the $20 a share buyout offer made
last month by Pickens' Mesa Limited Partnership.
   Homestake stock closed at $17.12{ a share Monday on the New York
Stock Exchange, unchanged from Friday's close.
   Pickens had labeled the buyout offer a friendly bid and proposed
a negotiated transaction with Homestake's managers.
   But Homestake's board concluded the offer was inadequate and not
in the best interests of the stockholders, said company officials.
   ``In light of our business prospects, we are better off served
as an independent company, said Stephanie Kushner, Homestake's
manager of financial services. ``We are trying to focus on the
financial future of the company.''
   ``We're really in a strong position right now with significant
cash assets and a very strong balance sheet, and our management is
in a better position to put that money to work for the company,''
Kushner stated.
   Homestake, one of the largest gold producers in the western
world outside of South Africa, owns the Homestake gold mine in
South Dakota and the McLaughlin mine in Northern California. The
company also has a one-quarter interest in the Round Mountain mine
in Nevada.
   In addition, Homestake owns a 42.5 percent interest in The Doe
Run Co., the largest U.S. producer of lead products, and a 48
percent interest in two mines in Western Australia.
   Kushner noted Pickens had not made a tender offer to Homestake
shareholders, and she was unsure whether he would now pursue a
hostile takeover in light of the board's rejection.
   The offer was Pickens' second move on a gold-mining company in
six months. His $2 billion takeover attempt for New York-based
Newmont Mining Corp. was blocked when Newmont's biggest
shareholder, Consolidated Gold Fields PLC, acquired a controlling
stake in the company to help thwart the hostile bid.
</TEXT>
