<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Brazil-Bankers     03-07 0174</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brazil-Bankers,0182</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Top Brazilian Bankers Quit, Fired</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Central Bank President Fernando Milliet
resigned Monday and the government fired the president of the
semi-official Banco do Brasil, Camilo Calazans, officials said.
   No immediate explanation was given for the dismissals.
   Milliet, the fourth Central Bank President under Brazil's
3-year-old civilian regime, was in charge of negotiating the
refinancing of Brazil's huge $113 billion foreign debt.
   Milliet was to be replaced by Elmo de Araujo Camoes, an
experienced banker with the Banco do Brasil, the Sao Paulo State
Bank Banespa and the Sogeral bank. He is a member of the
government's national monetary council.
   Calazans, an economist who used to head the government's coffee
agency, reportedly disagreed with Finance Minister Mailson da
Nobrega about wage restrictions for federal employees. Da Nobrega
favored a wage freeze to reduce the federal deficit, but Calazans
nevertheless granted a raise for Banco do Brasil employees.
   Calazans was to be replaced by Mario Gusmao Berard, the
secretary-general of the finance ministery and closely tied to da
Nobrega.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
